<HEADLINE>Sympathy shown to man who smashed office</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995457</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SUCCESSFUL businessman whose life was said to have been ruined by a
long-running dispute with a number of lawyers yesterday escaped punishment for
arming himself with a hammer and smashing up equipment in his solicitor's
office.
Iain McIntyre, 44, of Corsebar Road, Paisley, was given an absolute discharge
after pleading guilty to breach of the peace.
Glasgow Sheriff Court was told Mr McIntyre had been involved in a 10-year
dispute with two law firms: Wright and Crawford, of Glasgow Road, Paisley; and
MacRoberts, of Bath Street, Glasgow.
Mr McIntyre alleges lawyers' incompetence has cost him his housebuilding
business, his health, and his home. He is claiming #2.75m damages for loss and
legal fees.
The court heard that, in a moment of ``temporary insanity'', Mr McIntyre went
into the offices of Grant &amp; Co in West Regent Street, Glasgow, smashed a
telephone and fax machine, then locked himself in a room and tried to cut his
wrists.
Grant &amp; Co were helping Mr McIntyre with his claims but, in December last year,
he became ``overwhelmed by the hopelessnes and helplessness'' of his situation.
The court heard he may have thought the firm was distancing itself from his
case. He brandished the hammer and smashed equipment, causing #150 damage, as
staff ran from the office and telephoned police. He was arrested and remanded
in custody over New Year until January 6.
Mr George More, defending, blamed the incompetence and negligence of previous
lawyers for pushing Mr McIntyre to the brink of insanity.
``He has lost his business and the conduct of the lawyers has affected his
health, it could even be said, ruined his life. It was a cry for help,'' Mr
More said.
Mr McIntyre had been a property developer who lost his busines after a
conveyancing error by a partner at his first lawyers, Wright and Crawford. The
second firm he employed, MacRoberts, was also negligent, it was alleged, though
Grant &amp; Co fought ``vigorously'' on his behalf.
Sheriff George Crozier said he had decided to grant an absolute discharge
because Mr McIntyre had already spent one week in custody for his first
offence, a written apology to Grant &amp; Co had been accepted, and he had promised
to pay for the damage.
After studying articles from The Herald and medical reports, Sheriff Crozier
said: ``This is an extremely worrying case. Obviously the accused has been
sadly wronged and lost a tremendous amount of money, indeed has been ruined,
because of negligence in drawing up his title deeds.''
The sheriff added: ``Looking at all the reports and history before me, I do
agree he was under extreme strain and stress at the time this happened. This
does not excuse the remedy he took but it does make it more understandable. I
hope this good citizen will not be in trouble again.''
After the case, Mr McIntyre said he was delighted at the sheriff's sympathetic
decision.
Mr McIntyre is still involved in four Court of Session actions against law
firms. The Law Society of Scotland declined to comment because of those
forthcoming actions.
Mr Hugh Grant, senior partner of Grant &amp; Co, said after the hearing that Mr
McIntyre had been forgiven and the compensation money would be donated to
Children in Need.
</TEXT>
