<HEADLINE>Back to basics BICC writes  off #78m in Clarke sale</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995460</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CABLES and construction group BICC is writing off a total of #78m on the sale
of its Clarke Homes housebuilding activities following upon the strategic
decision to return much more to its core activities.
The buyer is the highly regarded Westbury which is paying #60.7m cash. That is
being funded by a rights issue to raise #32.2m net and the remainder is coming
from bank borrowings.
Shareholders are being offered one new share at 150p for every three held.
Market reaction was to knock 6p off the existing shares to 176p while BICC was
down 2p - both falls being on relatively small turnover.
The move will be welcomed by the housebuilding industry, which is anxious to
rationalise the number of participants.
BICC bought Clarke in 1987 for #51m for a company with assets of #7m.
At its peak, it was building 1200 houses but, like the vast majority of the
small to medium size housebuilders, numbers dropped considerably during the
recession and in 1994 it achieved a build of 600 units. The majority were in
the Midlands and the South of England and some in Scotland.
Last year, the loss was some #3m and in the first half of the current year, it
was trading at near breakeven.
Clarke owns some 2228 plots with planning consent. Its aquisition will require
a #1.7m provision against Westbury's current year profits which the City
estimates will rise from #12.6m to around #16m and be one of the few
housebuilders to show an improvement over the preceding year's trading.
</TEXT>
