<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why nuclear generators feared power of the pen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995461</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FEW weeks ago Scottish Nuclear asked me to write an article for its staff
newspaper outlining my views on the proposed privatisation of the industry.
The ideal, which I found perfectly acceptable, was that it would then have the
right to reply which would be appended to my article. That was fine by me. The
article was written and receipt acknowledged, without any hint of a problem. I
heard nothing more.
Yesterday I found out that Scottish Nuclear had reneged on that arrangement.
The article was not published. I have looked at it again and it does not seem
so defective in style, syntax, or content as to merit that treatment. So here,
for a wider audience, are some of the arguments if not the article.
We know, of course, that nuclear privatisation has nothing to do with Britain's
energy needs or, indeed, of public finances. As with railways, the decision to
privatise is purely a political one, driven by the urgent desire to raise more
money next year for last-gasp tax cuts.
As the Financial Times put it: ``Privatisation is to be shaped by political
pressures and the interests of future shareholders, not by the needs of
electricity consumers.'' Indeed, it is uncharacteristically frank to put a ``Mr
Robb'' in charge of a privatisation exercise. (I didn't even include that line
in the article for Scottish Nuclear!)
I did, however, gently remind Robin Jeffrey, formerly chief executive of
Scottish Nuclear, that as recently as April of this year, he stated: ``Let's be
absolutely clear. The creation of a single UK nuclear company is a proposal
which has little or nothing going for it. It would mean less competition in the
generating industry.''
Indeed it would. The giveaway is in the name - British Energy - selected for
the new company (which has so little going for it) of which Robin Jeffrey is
now, of course, deputy chairman to John Robb.
That name is intended, we know, as confirmation that the people who have been
placed by Ministers in the privileged position of running the company have no
intention of restricting their activities to nuclear generation.
But it is also a slap in the face to the men and women who have devoted so much
commitment to establishing a successful civil nuclear industry in this country.
Now the architects of privatisation dare not speak its name, as they organise
their share options and rub their hands at the prospect of joining the more
lucrative dash for gas.
I did try to tell the Scottish Nuclear workforce about a conference on nuclear
privatisation which I spoke at in London. Just as I arrived, the previous
speaker was being congratulated by the chairman - a former Tory MP - for the
most effective presentation he had heard in support of nuclear privatisation.
But the speaker in question was not a Government Minister or even a ``British
Energy'' director. He was the man from Greenpeace and his enthusiasm for
privatisation was based entirely on the belief that this was the quickest
possible way of killing off the entire nuclear generation industry.
For a whole range of reasons - including, I would argue, environmental ones - I
do not think that is a very good idea. But the logic is clear. Left to its own
commercial devices, ``British Energy'' will soon lose interest in nuclear
generation, which will slowly wither on the vine.
Where will that leave my constituents at Hunterston and their successors? I do
not think it was unreasonable for me to alert the Scottish Nuclear workforce to
the reasons why Greenpeace is the unlikely (but perfectly logical) cheer leader
for nuclear privatisation.
And where would an ``eight nuclear power stations for the price of one''
sell-off leave the taxpayer? For starters there is plenty evidence buried in
the small print of last week's public expenditure proposals that the costs of
nuclear privatisation to the Treasury are soaring almost as fast as those of
the proposed rail sell-off.
We're talking billions of additional public spending in each case, to
facilitate two utterly unwanted privatisations - and this at a time when axes
of Thatcherite proportions are being wielded in so many areas of useful public
expenditure.
This, of course, is only for starters. The costs of Magnox decommissioning -
which would, naturally, be left for the taxpayer to bear - are certainly
massive but still undefinable.
I am sorry that Scottish Nuclear - or was it British Energy? - decided that
this and other arguments against privatisation, from someone who has supported
the company and the industry as a member of Parliament, were not deemed
suitable reading for employees and their families. One might have thought that,
given the last word, it might have had a little more self-confidence in its
case.
And I don't know if British Energy will carry on the engaging Scottish Nuclear
custom of hosting a Burns Supper at the Caledonian Club in London. But if so, I
recommend a reading of one of the poet's sharpest verses:
Here's freedom to him who would
read;
Here's freedom to him who would
write;
There's none ever feared that the
truth should be heard,
But him that the truth would
indict.
</TEXT>
