<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Report urges more action on policy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT ROSS, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995462</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Report urges more
action on policy
THE Scottish farming industry should be organising itself now to put forward
proposals for the re-shaping of the Common Agriculture Policy in Europe,
according to the Trustee Savings Bank's latest analysis of agriculture in
Scotland.
Donald MacRae, the bank's agricultural adviser, welcomes the National Farmers'
Union of Scotland decision to get involved in the CAP debate. ``This has come
not a moment too soon, given the speed and scale of the turn-round in
Brussels,'' he said.
``The major thrust of the reform can be identified now. Less support will be
linked directly to production and increasing amounts will be paid for
environmental reasons. Compliance with environmental standards such as levels
of inputs applied, stocking densities, and measures of agricultural intensity
will have to be devised.
``The sooner the industry in Scotland puts its case on these matters the
better. It is strategically more powerful to have an input to the formation of
policy now than attempt to change decisions after they have been taken.''
One obvious dilemma for the Scottish industry is identified. Given the larger
size of the Scottish farm, policies constructed for the average European farm,
with support skewed towards environmental and social measures paid to
small-scale farmers, would, initially, leave Scottish and UK farmers at a
disadvantage.
Mr MacRae is convinced, however, that the competitive advanatage of superior
farm size will eventually persist and benefit British farmers.
One area of disadvantage is the UK and Scottish farmers' attitude to
co-operation, which is less positive than in some EU countries. About 30% of
Scottish agricultural output is sold co-operatively, compared to up to 90% for
some products in Europe.
``The difference is more than skin-deep,'' he said. ``Co-ops in European
countries concentrate on adding value after the produce has left the farm. This
is in direct contrast to Scotland where many co-ops still concentrate on a
supply of agricultural inputs. The potential for the future is in adding value
through processing agricultural products.'' One result of the lacklustre
approach to co-operation is that UK farmers have little market power compared
to multiple retailers who are among the biggest and most powerful in Europe.
Matching the market power of the multiples is not immediately feasible, he
concedes. ``However, there is little disagreement that co-op mergers are
required to give the market size capable of delivering buying and selling power
in the food industry. The day of the transnational co-operative is in the
offing.''
The analysis looks at the world scene and points to the aggressive American
stance on food exports compared to an unambitious approach from the EU. Part of
the blame may be laid at the door of the quota system, it is suggested. ``A
rational analysis of quotas concludes that they solve problems short-term, but
impose increasing economic costs medium to long-term.''
</TEXT>
