<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Carisma whistles in from the not-so-far east</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995463</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MITSUBISHI's vehicle division offers the biggest range and number of individual
products imaginable, from 550cc city runabouts to 22-litre trucks. But while
several of its rivals set up factories in the UK to tap into the European
market, Mitsubishi seemed to be lagging behind.
However, it took a different route into Europe, collaborating with Volvo and
the Dutch government in a joint-venture factory at Born near Maastricht. The
Carisma, built there and already on sale on the Continent, has arrived in this
country as the first-ever Mitsubishi not brought in from Japan.
This is a well-proportioned five-door hatchback. Bearing in mind that it is a
properly roomy car, with better rear-seat legroom and headroom than many of its
Far Eastern rivals, as well as good equipment levels, the prices are very
reasonable.
The 1.6 GL manual, with Mitsubishi's own 88bhp 16-valve engine and a Renault
gearbox, costs #10,999. The top price is #15,349 for the 1.8-litre GLS, powered
by a 114bhp engine linked to the Mitsubishi four-speed automatic transmission
which, as in the Galant, adjusts itself to a certain extent to the driver's
technique and the type of road being travelled.
As usual, the basic specification in each version can be enhanced by asking for
the extra-cost Diamond option pack. That designation has always seemed rather
twee, but it is quite justifiable, bearing in mind that Mitsubishi means
``three diamonds'', which is what the marque badge displays.
While many manufacturers try to convince you of how inexpensive their cars are,
when judged on a ``whole life'' basis, Mitsubishi has some quite convincing
independent figures to help put its case. Within the last month, the EMMOX
survey for fleet managers has shown the Carisma as likely to be the cheapest
car in its class to run.
EMMOX takes into account not just original price, insurance ratings, servicing
charges and warranty arrangements, but also likely residual values. Mitsubishis
are strongly placed here, since the controlled-supply situation means that
demand rarely runs in advance of what stock is available. The importers must
have a fair idea of how to run their business, because Mitsubishi claims
customer loyalty levels around 80 per cent.
Short familiarisation runs in Perthshire last week suggested that the various
models of Carisma have meaty mid-range performance, handling and ride qualities
which are better for the typical owner than some magazine reports suggest, and
a higher-than-expected level of wind noise, although it may be the reduction of
mechanical noise which brings up the wind whistle.
</TEXT>
