<DOCNO>GH951208-000007</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000007</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cool cat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995464</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROBERT FIELDS is Glasgow's top rock geezer. How can you tell? Because when we
meet, Robert is in public possession of tight leather trousers and a Little
Angels tour jacket - within the hours of daylight! Nay, at 11 o'clock on a
Tuesday morning!
Robert is also inordinately proud of the fact that Lee Kerslake, late of
riffmeisters Uriah Heep, is his son's godfather. Additionally, Robert bears
more than a passing resemblance to one of his top rock-geezer mates, Ozzy
Osbourne.
Most tellingly, Robert is a master of the pithy, all-purpose lingo of
rock'n'roll. ``No boomph,'' he will say apropos of this band or another. Other
acts are variously deemed ``not dangerous'' or ``too safe''. Of his eight years
as a roadie with the aforementioned Uriah Heep, he has a major philosophical
conclusion. ``Earplugs were for wimps!'' Robert shouts deafly.
These days the erstwhile welder from Springburn is making a PR noise for the
new improved Cathouse. After five successful years by the Clyde, the Glasgow
rock venue has relocated to more central premises in Union Street. On three
floors formerly occupied by such long-gone clubs as Viva and Vamps, the
Cathouse is owned by Donald McLeod and Michael Pagliocca, the partnership who
so splendidly reinvented another Glasgow venue, the Garage.
Despite its success, though, the only healthy-looking thing about the old
Cathouse was the light which shone brightly above the door of the men's lavvy.
In contrast, the new Cathouse is more stylishly grungy.
As well as in decor, money has been invested in an in-house sound system. ``As
we've our own PA, there's no cost to us in giving gigs to young local bands who
are desperate to play,'' says Robert, ever keen to encourage Scottish music at
a grassroots level.
This concern extends to free admissions for organised parties of 15 or more.
``We want the Cathouse to be a proper club, not just a weekend disco. But we're
also aware that people hear the name Cathouse and just think `Oh aye, rock',
when rock covers a number of sins. On our dance-floor, for instance, you'll
hear Bryan Adams, Def Leppard, the Kinks, and the Beatles, alongside more
modern brain-damage metal.
``And as well as gigs by Pearl Jam, the old Cathouse staged the Bhundu Boys, an
all-girl ceilidh band, the Average White Band, the Lemonheads.'' It also made
its mark on rock history as the site of an Oasis live B-side, I Am The Walrus.
Robert continues to make his own mark on Scottish rock history as promoter at
the Bruce Hotel, East Kilbride, an out-of-the-way gig with a Britain-wide
reputation.
Oh aye, the Cathouse: not too safe, not too dangerous, plenty of boomph. Robert
Fields? Welding people together with the force of rock. Top geezer.
n Forthcoming Cathouse highlights include Luna (December 14) and Jayne County
(December 18).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
