<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP calls for dairy industry  to hire fraud investigators</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995466</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEADERS of Britain's dairy farmers were yesterday urged to employ investigative
journalists to prove EU fraud in the milk sector of Mediterranean countries.
The advice to the Royal Association of British Dairy Farmers came from Dale
Campbell-Savours, Labour MP for Workington, during a Commons select committee
meeting on the British dairy industry and the CAP dairy regime.
In evidence to the committee, the association said that in addition to the
technical and economic problems of the regime and quota restrictions, there
were further distortions caused by certain countries' actions.
``What has angered producers is that dairy producers have tried to produce to
their quota ceiling. Unless, and until a quota regime can be enforced on an
equitable basis across the European Union, it will be those countries with a
more regulated farming structure who will continue to be penalised.''
Mr Campbell-Savours asked if the association had been able to establish the
scale of the fraud. Dr Robert Bruce, chairman of the association's board, said
he was not aware of any work in this area.
William Powell, Conservative MP for Corby, asked why the association had not
done anything about this itself. Dr Bruce said it was a question of resources,
suggesting that European farmers' unions pursue the matter.
Pressing the point, Mr Campbell-Savours said it seemed as though nobody wanted
to do anything about the issue and turn a blind eye.
``Maybe we should have investigative journalists in Europe paid for by the
RABDF to establish that this is going on and its scale. The regime is being
subverted by fraud but good old Britain plays the game.''
The MPs turned to the potential policing role of doorstep delivery people.
President Lord Rayleigh - whose Essex-based business employs 400 people -
pointed out their importance in watching for neighbourhood crime. ``They are
the eyes and ears of the police when everyone else is asleep,'' he said.
Chairman Sir Gerry Wiggin, Conservative MP for Western-super-Mare, asked how
many reports of criminal activity the delivery people had given. Lord Rayleigh
said he had no information on this but would compile a report for submission.
The association, the Country Landowners' Federation, and the Tenant Farmers'
Assocation all agreed that milk quotas introduced in 1984 had led to the
ossification of the dairy industry but had largely protected farmers' incomes.
This had resulted in a substantial re-investment programme on farms to cope
with the lean years expected ahead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
