<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Devers, Senior share lead</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995467</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN Clay Devers and Australian Jeff Senior yesterday shot bogey-free six
under par rounds of 66 to share the lead after the first round of the Western
Vietnam Open.
In Vietnam's first ever professional tournament, they led by one stroke from
Taiwan's Lin Keng-chi.
``My driving helped me get past most of the trouble spots on the fairways,''
said Devers, winner of last week's Malaysian PGA championship.
Senior attributed his low score to a fine putting performance on the front
nine. ``I putted well before the turn, but had a little trouble reading the
grain coming in,'' he said.
66 - C Devers (USA), J Senior (Australia). 67 - L Keng-chi (Taiwan). 68 - D
Boulet (Hong Kong). 69 - S Taylor (USA), D Mijovic (Canada), B Ruangkit
(Thailand), Y Sone (Japan), A Sophon (Thailand).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MOTOR-SPORT DIARY</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<FLAG>motor sport diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974995468</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN Fife's place as Scottish rally championship co-ordinator (see first page)
has been taken by Anne Parker, herself from a rallying family. The series
continues in its unique situation as the only motor-sport championship of its
kind in Britain which, although sponsored, is run entirely by the car clubs
organising the individual events.
The 1996 championship begins with the Snowman Rally on February 10 at
Inverness. The Valentine Rally in Fife and the Trossachs follows on March 9,
and the third-round Granite City Rally on March 30 at Aberdeen is also a
counter in the British national championship.
Argyll provides the forest stages for the Weldex Rally on May 4, and the
international-status Perth Scottish Rally will be a two-day event on May 31 and
June 1.
On July 6, the Jim Clark Memorial Rally in Berwickshire may use closed public
roads. August 17 is the date of the McRae Motorsport Stages Rally in the Tweed
Valley, and the championship finishes with the successor event to the Ayr-based
Weir Toyota Stages Rally on September 21.
Competitors count their best seven scores from the eight rounds. There are 12
subsidiary classes for cars of various engine capacities and stages of
preparation. Additional categories include Juniors, who are drivers under 25 at
the start of the year, and Challengers, drivers of any age who have not
previously finished more than three times in the top ten of a Scottish
championship event.
New for 1996 is a championship for 1300cc cars running on nominated control
tyres. They tackle six events and count five scores.
Fuller details are available from Anne Parker at 1 Strand Court, Auchterarder,
Perthshire PH3 1JE.
More immediate events:
q Sunday: Machars Car Club runs its final 1995 cross-country vehicle trial at
Penkiln Farm, north of Garlieston in Wigtownshire, starting at 10.30. These 4x4
events attract drivers who use off-road vehicles for work and go motor-sporting
with them at weekends, as well as enthusiasts who have built up competition
specials. Peter Vance has already clinched the club 4x4 championship with a
Suzuki, but there are also Lada Nivas, Daihatsus, Subarus and wild devices like
a four-wheel steer Land Rover with a Mini body! Drivers come over from Ireland
to take part.
q Sunday: Closing event of the MG Car Club season is the traditional Old Year
Trial at Bonaly, in the Pentlands foothills. The site will be signposted from
Bonaly Road above Colinton. MGs and other makes of car will take part, and it
is worth noting that anyone wanting to compete can take up a 1996 club
competition licence on the spot, because the licence year runs for 13 months
from December 1. Runs at the first observed hill start at 11.15.
</TEXT>
