<HEADLINE>Your own electronic navigator</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995469</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Mitsubishi Carisma 1.8-litre GLS is the first car to come as standard with
a Philips Routefinder, writes ROSS FINLAY. This intriguing little gadget is a
demountable electronic navigator.
If you select the starting and finishing points of a planned journey, it will
mull things over - passing the time by showing a little car pottering across
the screen - then come up with navigational instructions for the most direct
route.
These include details like an accurate overall distance, mileages to all the
quoted intermediate points, where any motorway service areas are, and an idea
of how long the journey is likely to take. If you would rather follow an
indirect route, you can avoid motorways or miss out specific locations on the
way.
I happened to be near Braco in Perthshire when I tried it first. Close by on
the directory were Bracora and Bracorina, beside Loch Morar; so this is by no
means just a big-built-up-area device.
The instructions go from junction to junction, stating road numbers where they
exist, and ``local route'' elsewhere. On my imaginary jaunt to Bracora, all the
main junctions were clearly given, while a hotel, the White Corries ski centre
and the Ballachulish bridge were added as checks.
Obviously, the Routefinder is something to be glanced at rather than studied at
length in heavy traffic, and there is a built-in light which I thought was much
too feeble in the dark.
</TEXT>
