<HEADLINE>EU backs `compact' licence</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE, European Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995471</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN Union transport ministers last night gave their final blessing to a
new EU driving licence.
The plastic, credit-card sized licence will replace Britain's bulky paper
document for those who wish to make the change - there is no compulsion - from
July 1, next year.
All other EU member states agreed that the new card would carry a photograph of
the holder but Britain won a derogation on this until the year 2001.
The progress of the debate on a ``compact driving licence'' in Europe has
become entangled with the internal debate in the British Government over the
question of identity cards.
The Home Office is currently considering whether to introduce compulsory ID
cards to combat crime, street disorder, football hooliganism, and illegal
immigration. The idea is opposed by the civil liberties lobby.
Options being considered range from doing nothing to making ID cards compulsory
as they are in some other EU countries already. Britain won its derogation
because it wanted to keep its options on a dual-purpose licence/ID card open.
The licence in other EU member states will not routinely show the nationality
of the holder. It will show merely the country of issue. Britain's will have
the letters UK or GB printed inside the EU's circle of stars.
Mr Neil Kinnock, European Transport Commissioner, resisted the British move. He
has insisted that the harmonised EU licence is not an ID card but Commission
officials said later there had been no major dispute on the issue.
</TEXT>
