<DOCNO>GH951208-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Faithfull unto herself</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>boss grooves</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995472</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A voice of the sixties which is still being heard brings a certain decadence to
Edinburgh tonight.
MARIANNE Faithfull's media-minders request that interviewers concentrate on her
work in the here-and-now, forsaking reruns of salacious old headlines - Naked
Girl In Rolling Stones' Country-Cottage Drugs Party Shocker - and ancient
questions pertaining to her long-ago role as Lorde Micke of Jagger's blonde
rocke-chicke courtesan.
I fret slightly, pondering whether this is akin to being magically granted an
audience with Cleopatra on two conditions. No queries about Cleo's boyfriend,
Tony What's-His-Face. And please ignore the fact that Cleo's holding yon deadly
snake-thingie to her bosom.
Actually, there's no need to retread oft-tramped lines of inquiry about
swinging-sixties London and Sussex drug-busts. For Marianne herself last year
honestly bared everything there is to bare about her life as Mick's main
squeeze in her autobiography, Faithfull (published by Michael Joseph, #15.99).
It's all there. Early pop stardom. Sexy rompings. Odd leisure-time activities
involving chocolate confectionery (not). Heroin addiction. Artistic rebirth.
A rattling yarn, but somewhat lacking till you've heard bits of it phrased in
that primeval voice of Marianne's, a sinuous mixture of gravel and honey. Last
week I heard those deep, dark tones down the phone. Yum yum.
I'm in Glasgow. Marianne is reclining on a hotel bed in Berlin. Initial
pleasantries having been exchanged, there is a hiatus. Marianne must finish
dismissing a man from her room - hey, no, nothing like that, mucky pup! It's
just the waiter who's appeared, bearing Marianne's mid-morning tea on a tray.
A grandmother who's three weeks short of being 49, Marianne views her
autobiography as ``me old-age pension, dear''. I inform her of her PRs' desire
to obscure her past. She offers reassurance: ``You must ask whatever comes into
your heart or head.''
Music is always in Marianne's heart and head, so we'll start with that,
beginning with Marianne's sole British performance of An Evening In The Weimar
Republic, tonight in Edinburgh's Queen's Hall. Next spring the show should
visit Glasgow. Long-term, Marianne hopes for an Edinburgh Festival berth. So
please explain the ongoing Bertolt Brecht-Kurt Weill-Marianne Faithfull
three-way tango.
``I was asked to do a weekend of decadent twentieth-century composers,''
Marianne says, before That Voice breaks into a breathy, giggly confession. ``It
was lovely.''
Don't get the wrong idea. They were New York's Brooklyn Academy, the opera
house in which Laurie Anderson got her performing start. Mahler and Hindemith
were two of the alleged twentieth-century decadents. The Brooklyn Philharmonic
handled them. Marianne provided her own well-established Weimar Cabaret, based
on Brecht and Weill.
Hang about, though. Marianne Faithfull and twentieth-century decadence . . . if
I were a lesser man, I might impute a certain tabloid sleaziness.
``Ah, but it's not the MTV definition of decadence. The Nazis and the
Bolsheviks both denounced the art of the Weimar Republic as decadent because it
was Jewish. It was the intellectual flowering of mixed European races, and
therefore racially and ideologically impure.
``And when we hear the word decadent today we're meant to think of evil, but
the Weimar Republic's art wasn't evil. And I don't choose to perform it because
it's decadent and evil, and so therefore I must be decadent and evil.''
A chance invitation led Marianne to sing The Soldier's Wife's Song on a Kurt
Weill tribute album 10 years ago. In turn, that led to her performing The Seven
Deadly Sins, Weill's little operetta for his main squeeze, Lotte Lenya.
Gradually Marianne found that Weill's music was her past, her heritage. For
Marianne Faithfull's family heritage is not the straight
blonde-English-rose-aristo bloodline you might imagine.
``My mother and grandmother were both Jewish, from Vienna, Austro-Hungary, the
decadent Hapsburg Empire. My mother was a little dancer in pre-war Berlin, part
of the corps de ballet, working under Max Rhinehardt, and curtseying `Good
morning, Mr Weill,' as Weill went past.
``She would dance in clubs in the evening, professionally, with a partner. But
then she had to go back to Vienna when the Nazis came to power. And I remember
that she used to whistle The Alabama Song as she cooked when I was a child.''
And you were somehow drawn to the doominess of the pre-war era in which Weill
composed? Music for a lost generation, swept away by the Holocaust . . .
``With hindsight, there's the notion of Weltzschmerz. And a vague idea that the
music survived even though some of its audience didn't. But Weill wasn't
Jewish. And Weill and Lotte Lenya went to America and had a happy life, writing
Broadway musicals, so it wasn't all tragedy.
``And the audiences for his music weren't exclusively Jewish. In fact, Weill's
work was funny, witty, ironic, written by a man who was fascinated by the US
and by jazz, by syncopation.
``So much so that he wasn't considered as serious a composer as Schoenberg.
Using a brass section, jazz rhythms, and orchestration hadn't been done before.
Weill's was merely dance music. The Threepenny Opera was judged a light work.
``Plus What Became Of The Soldier's Wife was written as an anti-war song in
1943 when Brecht and Weill were both in Santa Monica, hating it, and hearing
news of the siege of Stalingrad and feeling tremendous sadness for the deaths
of millions of their countrymen, not just Jews but ordinary soldiers, not
big-cheese Nazis . . . I say all this in my show, actually. It's evident that
both my parents were teachers.''
And you have lectured on music, too.
``I did three years of summer schools, giving songwriting seminars at a school
of meditation in Boulder, Colorado, run by Allen Ginsberg. I still have the
laminated pass which says that I am a professor at the Jack Kerouac School of
Disembodied Poetics. I'm very proud of that. But I think rather than me
teaching, meditation meant I learned. I learned tolerance, compassion,
acceptance of other people's idiocies. And my own.''
Learned rock academics are reaching more fully-rounded verdicts on your solo
career, it seems, too. According to one such you are a demi-monde chanteuse
with a Gauloise-rich, uningratiating voice and an intelligence which few had
suspected.
``God! They've rethought their shit since the last time I looked in one of
those music encyclopaedias! The older ones write as though I'm going to be dead
any minute. I'm seen as the twit, the victim, when I'm no more a victim than
anyone else.
``But `uningratiating' is interesting. As for the rest, it's a back-handed sort
of compliment . . . pretty women can only be whores and fools. An intelligence
few had suspected . . . but I suppose I never did give much away, did I?''
Of course, Marianne Faithfull hasn't always coped quite so airily with
slighting criticism. ``When I was younger, I coped not very well. It hurt me
terribly. To the point of being suicidal. But as you get older, you take the
bull by the horns. `I'll assume you think this because you don't know me. I'll
let you know me, and then see what you think.' ''
Does Marianne Faithfull have any regrets?
``Not really. I wish I hadn't done heroin. I could have done without that.
There are things about my character I'd change. I'd like to be more loving . .
. to show the people I love that I love them. And I wish I'd been a better
mother to Nicholas, although I have a good relationship with him now. Better
than I could have wished for.
``He's forgiven me. I haven't. Yet. But I hope I can . . . I will. Yes.''
</TEXT>
