<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>France reduces intervention rate</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995473</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of France cut its key intervention rate yesterday and gave a boost to
financial markets and the economy that were sagging because of a two-week
strike of transport and other public service workers.
After a meeting of its monetary policy council, the bank reduced the
intervention rate, which sets a floor to money market rates, to 4.70% from
4.80%.
The decision pleased financial markets, where traders had feared authorities
might raise rates to defend the franc against weakness caused by the crippling
anti-austerity strikes.
The CAC-40 share market index rose 12.05 to close at 1846.80. Bonds also turned
positive while the franc remained steady.
Economists were surprised by the move but they said it was an economically
justified vote of support for the conservative French government's fiscal
policies. The size of the cut made it more of a symbol than anything else, they
said, but emphasised it was a powerful symbol.
</TEXT>
