<DOCNO>GH951208-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>George warns of inflation doubts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995474</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Governor of the Bank of England outlines his reasons for the Chancellor to
tread carefully
BANK of England Governor Eddie George warned MPs yesterday that there was a
great deal of uncertainty about whether or not the Government was on course to
hit its sub-2.5% inflation target.
But he conceded that the outlook had improved since May, when he unsuccessfully
tried to persuade Chancellor Kenneth Clarke to increase rates.
``I would have to say that the uncertainty is as great now as I can remember
for some time,'' Mr George told the Treasury and Civil Service Select Committee.
In the City, this was seen as an indication that he would advise the Chancellor
not to cut rates on Wednesday.
Mr Clarke's upbeat assessment of the economy - which he predicted in November's
Budget would grow by 3% next year - suggests he will agree with Mr George's
advice.
Mr George cited three reasons why uncertainty about inflation had increased
since May. He said there was a danger of pay rises taking off if the benchmark
Ford deal, in which the unions are asking for a 10% increase, was successful.
That would be a ``very serious development,'' he said.
Mr George said there was also continued concern about the weakness of the
pound, which pushes up import costs.
Worries remained about the strength of M4, the broad measure of the money
supply, which includes cash in circulation and bank and building society
deposits. It is currently hovering near the top of its 3% to 9% monitoring
range.
Earlier, Mr George agreed that Mr Clarke's decision to reject his advice in May
had had a ``happy outcome'' in the short run but said it had had a cost for the
economy in the long term. By being seen not to err on the side of caution,
suspicions about the UK's lack of commitment to price stability had been fanned.
This was reflected in the weakness of the pound on the foreign exchanges and
higher rates of return demanded by investors for buying government bonds.
Matthew Carrington, Conservative MP for Fulham, asked about the Treasury's
prediction that growth in the G7 countries - the world's leading industrial
nations - would drop from 3% to 2.5% next year.
He said: ``This is quite a significant drop when we are expecting our growth
rate to pick up.''
Mr George replied: ``It certainly is another issue, another considerable area
of uncertainty.''
He added that the G7 forecast was a sensible assumption to make but said it
would be a surprise for the British economy to go up while the G7 economies
went down in the long term.
Mr George also claimed the domestic housing market would improve, but suggested
that houses would never again be the worthwhile financial investment they were
a decade ago.
He said: ``For decades housing was not just somewhere where people lived, it
was a financial investment and in fact for most people it was the biggest and
best financial investment they made in their lives.
``In terms of the perception of houses as a financial asset, I think that is
changing.
And he added: ``People are less likely to buy houses as a financial investment
rather than as somewhere which provides housing services.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pay rises are blamed  for German slowdown</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995475</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GERMANY'S gross domestic product stagnated in the third quarter of 1995 while
unemployment surged in November, figures out yesterday showed.
The data prompted economists to call on the country's powerful Bundesbank to
cut interest rates and stimulate the economy.
German GDP was unchanged in the third quarter of 1995 from the second and was
1.5% higher than the same quarter of 1994, the Federal Statistics Office said.
The year-on-year rise was the weakest since the fourth quarter of 1993. In the
second quarter, GDP had risen 1% from the previous quarter and was 2.2% up from
the second quarter of 1994.
The office said the weakness in third-quarter GDP was largely due to weak
capital investment and construction. Stockbuilding by firms was strong.
The ministry described the figures as representing a ``clear slowdown'' in the
economy blaming the strong rise in the value of the mark earlier this year,
high wage rounds in the spring and higher taxes.
The ministry said pan-German growth for 1995 would probably only be around 2%
as the Council of Economic Advisers, known as the ``Five Wise Men'' forecast
recently.
Unemployment rose by 42,000 after seasonal adjustment in November to over 3.7
million, its fourth rise in a row, the Federal Labour Office said. The rise was
much worse than economists had expected.
The jobless rate rose by 1% to 9.7% in October. The Office said seasonally
adjusted west German unemployment rose by 23,000 to 2.62 million while in the
east, unemployment rose 19,000 to 1.1 million.
The number of part-time workers in Germany rose to 211,000 from 179,000 in
October while vacancies fell to 273,000 from 289,000 a month earlier.
Economists said taken together, the data showed the economy was weaker than
believed and appealed to the Bundesbank to cut rates.
``Lower rates would be the most important support for the economy in 1996,''
said Klaus Friedrich, chief economist at Frankfurt's Dresdner Bank.
He said this would stimulate the economy more effectively than next January's
tax cuts.
``The case for a discount rate cut is almost unanswerable,'' said Julian Jessop
of HSBC Markets in London.
Mr Jessop said the sharp fall in capital investment in the third quarter was in
line with ``gloomy business surveys'' and a recent dip in capacity
utilisation.-Reuter
</TEXT>
