<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish athletes given a  contract of improvement SAF names 25 to spearhead coaching initiative</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Doug Gillon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995476</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE spectre of Linford Christie and Colin Jackson bickering about money and
declining to compete in important British meetings cast a shadow over a
revolutionary initiative launched yesterday by the Scottish Athletics
Federation.
The SAF unveiled 25 athletes being put under contract as part of a new athlete
and coach support programme designed to increase the number of Scots in British
teams, and improve the status of Scots in UK rankings at all levels.
Members of the so-called performance management group will be eligible for
grants for warm weather and altitude training, medical support, and advice on
sports science, psychology, physiology, and nutrition.
The Scottish Sports Council has provided #35,000 to look after the squad, and a
further #12,000 for scientific back-up.
The council invested a substantial sum in preparing the Commonwealth Games
squad, but concludes that in future, this will be a better way of using their
funds.
SAF has been faster off the mark than their UK counterparts. The British
federation is still attempting to sign up their main athletes to prevent the
friction which kept Olympic sprint champion Christie out of major UK meetings
last summer, and led to a damaging split with world hurdles record-holder
Jackson.
BAF's failure to resolve their contractual problems has put the signing of the
Scots on hold.
``Scots law is different from English, but the two sets of contracts have to be
compatible,'' explained Jim Scott, chairman of the Scottish performance
management group which will be managed by national coach Andy Vince.
Vince believes the project should prevent the national vest, being stigmatised,
in recent years, as he put it: ``as almost a free gift from a Cornflakes
packet.''
In return for being given a share of what, after all, is public money, the
squad will be expected to support promotional initiatives (like come-and-try
days), grass-roots development programmes, and marketing opportunities for
sponsors.
More importantly, SAF expects them to participate in national championships and
be available for matches where these do not conflict with UK interests. They
will also be expected to sign a code of conduct similar to that adopted in golf
and tennis.
``If they break the code, there will be repercussions,'' said Scott, who, as
SAF treasurer is acutely aware of the need for the best athletes at
championships to secure sponsorship. He insisted SAF will be reasonable over
other commitments: ``There is no question of forcing athletes to compete.''
As Europa Cup 400 metres champion Neef acknowledged: ``We'd just have a sudden
cold, or an illness.''
The only athlete among the 25 likely to be offered a BAF contract, Neef added:
``I don't see any conflict of interest, and if SAF is going to deliver these
benefits, I see nothing wrong in them asking us for something in return.''
Yvonne Murray, Liz McColgan, Tom McKean, Brian Whittle, and Tom Hanlon, the
most successful Scots of recent years, were left out on the basis that it is a
development initiative. More curious is the omission of UK marathon
international, Karen Macleod.
Olympic contender Macleod was furious. Fourth in the last Commonwealth marathon
alone should have got her on the squad, she believes. So, too, should selection
by Britain for the last world and European championships, as might being ranked
second in Britain to McColgan at the half marathon this year.
Her husband and coach, John Davies, said last night: ``Karen finished second in
the UK 10,000m road championships, to Vikki McPherson - who is in the squad -
then ran 40 seconds faster the following week - all while recovering fom injury.
``Her performances were achieved before the selection meeting on October 17.
These people are obviously totally out of touch, and we are clearly wasting our
time. Karen has spent a lot on treatment of a foot injury. It would have been
nice to be recognised.''
Great Britain international walkers Martin Bell and Verity Snook may also feel
they have grounds for complaint, as aleady indicated by road and track runner
Glen Stewart.
Vince promised the system will operate ``like a revolving door'' with constant
reassessment. This not only puts pressure on the individuals to deliver, but on
the whole squad.
The Sports Council is unlikely to continue backing the programme if objectives
are not met, though Vince believes that with the average age of squad members
being 21, the long-term benefits will not be fully apparent for six years.
Squad:
Women: Mel Neef, Allison Curbishley (400 metres), Lorna Jackson and Joanne
Walker (javelin), Sinead Dudgeon (200m), Allison Grey (shot), Vikki McPherson
(10,000m), Aileen McGillivary (100m), Ruth Irvine (long/triple jumps).
Men: Ken Campbell, Ross Baillie (110m hurdles), Ally Donaldson, Des Roache,
Andy Young (800m), Charles Robertson-Adams, Barry Middleton (400m hurdles),
Duncan Mathieson, Jamie Quarry (decathlon/long jump), Stephan Hayward (shot),
Darren Ritchie (long jump), Doug Walker, Ian Mackie (200m), Chris Robison
(10,000m/cross-country), R Quinn (cross-contry), T Murray (cross-country/hill
running).
</TEXT>
