<HEADLINE>Another trophy for Ryder Cup team</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GOLF: By RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995477</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR the third time in 11 years the Ryder Cup team has won the Association of
Golf Writers' Trophy, awarded annually ``to the person or persons, born or
resident in Europe, who have made the outstanding contribution to golf during
the preceding 12 months.''
The achievement of the 12-man side, captained by Bernard Gallacher for the
third and last time, in becoming only the second in the history of the match to
beat the United States on their own soil, gained overwhelming recognition
despite the strong credentials of several other candidates who helped to make
the 1995 season one of the most exceptional on record.
Yet, in face of the unique feat of Sweden's Annika Sorenstam of leading the
women's professional money lists on both sides of the Atlantic; Colin
Montgomerie's third successive year as winner of the European order of merit;
and Britain and Ireland's defeat of the United States in the Walker Cup match,
the Oak Hill triumph attracted almost 70% of the votes cast by the AGW
membership.
Yesterday, in expressing his appreciation, Gallacher, who will receive the
trophy at the Association's annual dinner during next year's Open Championship
at Royal Lytham and St Annes, said: ``I hope all the players can be there
because it was a real team effort that enabled us to bring the cup home. But
I'm so delighted I can hand the cup on to my successor, as Tony Jacklin handed
it to me.
``Some people are saying that it was a greater achievement than the 1987 win at
Muirfield Village. All I would say is that they were both great because eight
years ago we broke the duck on their patch and this year because we came from
behind in the singles, where in the past the Americans have been at their
strongest.''
q WITH American golf ``all shook up'' by this season's loss of both Ryder and
Walker Cups, it was perhaps not surprising that more people watched the
practice workouts of Arnold Palmer and Jack Nicklaus than the actual play of
the regular but duller tour pros like Tom Kite, Payne Stewart, and Lee Janzen
at the Diners Club matches in Palm Springs, California, yesterday, writes John
Ball.
Nicklaus, now 55, has always maintained that a great deal more of the kind of
matchplay here would benefit the USA's international performances, as it did in
his college and Walker Cup days. He and Palmer (66) take on last year's senior
winners Ray Floyd and Dave Eichelberger today.
Meanwhile, Kite, 46 tomorrow, played beautifully to give himself and Billy
Andrade a one-hole lead after six holes against Fred Funk and Blaine
McCallister.
Last year's winners Jeff Maggert and Jim McGovern were two down after 10 to
Kirk Triplett and Steve Stricker while in the most entertaining match the
former US Open champions Stewart and Janzen were all square after five against
Paul Azinger and Phil Mickelson.
Britain's Laura Davies tees off today with her friend Mardi Lunn and her big
hitting will illicit the usual cries of approval from American spectators who
love to watch this female John Daly.
q LEADING first round scores in the Daikyo Open in Onnason yesterday (Japanese
unless noted):
66 - T Sugihara, H Hamano.
67 - B Watts (USA), N Serizawa, H Meshiai, T Nakamura.
68 - S Mori, F Minoza (Philippines), S Ginn (Australia), M Ito, Y Kuramoto.
Other scores included: 69 - A Gilligan (Australia). 70 - H Chin-sheng (Taiwan),
Y Chang-ting (Taiwan). 74 - L Chie-hsiang (Taiwan), C Tze-chung (Taiwan). 75 -
C Tze-ming (Taiwan).
</TEXT>
