<HEADLINE>Guppy free to contest judgment on compensation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995478</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DARIUS Guppy, disgraced friend of Earl Spencer, was freed on bail yesterday
after being given leave to appeal against a jail term for refusing to pay
compensation for a bogus gems robbery.
Mr Justice May, at the High Court, allowed bail on condition of a #200,000
surety and that he stay at his home address.
Mr Spenser Hilliard, Guppy's counsel, said after the hearing that Guppy had
finished his five-year sentence for staging the bogus robbery but was now
appealing against a three-year sentence for failing to comply with a
compensation order.
In April, Guppy lost his appeal against the five-year sentence but fines of
#539,000 were cut to #227,000 and converted into a compensation order in favour
of Lloyd's insurers who were defrauded when they paid up #1.8m for the bogus
gems robbery.
Guppy was told to pay the money within three months or serve the extra three
years.
Guppy, 30, of Notting Hill, was sentenced at Snaresbrook Crown Court in March
1993 for conspiracies to defraud, steal, and commit false accounting and VAT
offences.
In 1990, the Old Etonian who was best man to Earl Spencer at his wedding,
conned insurers for compensation after faking an armed robbery of a #1.8m
jewellery collection in a New York hotel room. His business associate, Benedict
Marsh, was jailed for five years and similarly fined.
They paid Peter Risdon, an acquaintance, #10,000 to stage a bogus raid,
stealing gems from their hotel safe and leaving them tied up on their beds.
Last April, the judge said he believed Guppy still had access to ``ill-gotten
gains''.
</TEXT>
