<HEADLINE>Maryfield ready to take centre stage</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joseph Dillon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995479</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN some ways Dundee has been a deprived area with regards to the availability
of international standard sporting facilities but that will change dramatically
with the input of #1!sm of lottery money towards the redevelopment of the
Maryfield complex.
The Tayside centre is set to become the envy of hockey enthusiasts all over
Scotland for, apart from the building of two new artificial pitches, it will
also have an indoor arena.
Stephen Cumming, the Midlands secretary, now sees a bright future for the sport
in the area. ``With Dundee being the central city of Scotland it gives us a
great opportunity of attracting some of the major international tournaments,''
he pointed out.
As Maryfield will be the only facility in Scotland with two artificial pitches
on site, Dundee must now be favourite to become the centre for hockey in
Scotland.
Peffermill, in Edinburgh, has long been the principle contender for that honour
but, as there are no plans for an indoor facility at the complex, Maryfield
looks a much better bet.
The main interest in the men's indoor league this weekend will be focused on
the Bells Sport Centre in Perth where the second division will hold centre
stage.
Clydesdale presently occupy pole position but Stepps look menacing in second
place.
JOSEPH DILLON
</TEXT>
