<HEADLINE>`Big two' set for a capital showdown</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joseph Dillon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995480</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE first meeting of the season between defending champions Edinburgh Ladies
and Western Klick Photopoint in the indoor league at Meadowbank tomorrow could,
if history repeats itself, have a vital bearing on the destination of the
trophy.
The winners of the opening encounter have always gone one to lift the title.
But the situation may be a little clouded as neither side is able to put out
its recognised side.
Great Britain restrictions have deprived Edinburgh of two of their key players,
Diane Renilson and Pauline Robertson. Western's Susan MacDonald is also out for
the same reason, while examinations also cost them Gail Crawford.
On this occasion, however, Western appear to have the upper hand. They will
have Wendy Fraser directing operations but, equally important, they have Ellen
Murray and Sheena McKelvie in brilliant form.
The form of Hyndland in the opening series of games was disappointing but,
according to Sharon Duncan, who is playing the best hockey of her career,
``that was only a temporary setback''.
Bonagrass Grove finished second last weekend at the Montrouge tournament in
Paris but their aspirations could rest on the outcome of their matches against
Edinburgh Ladies and Western.
JOSEPH DILLON
</TEXT>
