<DOCNO>GH951208-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jingle without jangle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>joan grady</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>training</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974995481</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
There's more to shop-assisting than meets the eye, especially over the festive
period, finds Joan Grady
GOOD Christian men rejoice . . . but retail workers are shaking in their shoes.
The Christmas shopping season is revving up to full throttle, and with spending
expected to be very similar to last year's, the sense of dread emanating from
High Street stores is almost tangible.
Not from the retailers, however. A survey carried out by management consultants
Touche Ross of more than 100 top UK retailers and 1430 consumers shows that
retailers are expecting a Christmas spending rise of 6%. Consumers don't quite
agree.
``There are many mismatches between what consumers say they will do and what
retailers are predicting,'' says Touche Ross partner Ralph Adams.
``Contrary to the forecasts of the retailers, most consumers expect to spend
the same or only slightly more than last year. The average expected spending
increase is only 1%.''
Retailers also think more consumers will be shopping in out-of-town centres and
from catalogues, while consumers are convinced their shopping patterns will not
change - which might bring a sigh of relief from the bosses; but how do staff
cope with the extra pressures Christmas brings?
It has long been thought that working in retail takes only the minimum of
training. New staff are thrown in at the deep end and expected to pick up the
system of an operation which has been functioning effectively for the best part
of a century in half-an-hour.
Knowing how a store works takes time - and ladies fashion retailer Jaeger gives
its staff that time to learn the ropes before asking them to cope with the
extra pressures of busy seasons.
``We don't take on Christmas staff,'' says branch manager Wilma Allardice. ``We
have a permanent part-time worker who comes in as and when we need her.
Temporary staff just don't give the customer what Jaeger is all about.
``We do a lot of on-the-job training, and try to build up mentally to busy
periods - then we're halfway prepared. We know it's going to be a long, hard
slog through December, but we also know that we just have to get through it.''
Preparation does improve staff performance. Many retail staff are not prepared,
and are therefore taken aback by their first experience of Christmas shopping
from the other side of the counter.
They need to know a lot more than how to wield a broom, hang up fallen clothes
or punch figures into a cash register. Jaeger's commitment to training takes
all members of staff to London twice a year.
``Every six months we take all our girls down to London to learn about the
company,'' says Mrs Allardice. ``They learn about our products and stock - they
have to. It's a particular kind of selling, a very involved selling, and they
have to know what they're doing.''
Marks &amp; Spencer favours the more traditional approach. It provides on-the-job,
in-house training under the watchful eye of a more experienced supervisor.
Staff take part in an induction day, which involves getting around the store,
fire and safety rules, cash training, and basic customer service.
Staff do not receive extra training for Christmas, but there is a support
network if things get too much.
``Christmas is definitely our busiest time of the year, and the staff are under
pressure,'' says Sue Sadler, corporate press officer. ``We have personnel and
medical teams if the stress gets too much.
``The majority of our staff have already experienced it, however, and will know
how to cope and help our new members. There's no additional training.''
In my first job - part-time seasonal staff for a well-known retail outlet,
training was minimal but everything was fine - until the Christmas crowds
started rolling in.
The ensuing melee, which lasted throughout December and January, was
overwhelming. Even with four working at each till, the queues were enormous. If
you think those customer service queues look frightening when you're waiting in
them, you should see them from the other side.
Apart from making life easier for staff, training also improves customer
service. While The Disney Store's HQ in London thought it ``wouldn't be
interested in divulging that sort of information'',  a little tweety bird tells
me its American-style training is rigorous. Staff must know where to be, when
to be there, and what to do when they get there. Not a lot of fun, but being on
top of the job makes both the working and shopping experiences a great deal
easier for everyone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
