<DOCNO>GH951208-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Flexible labour `is costing real jobs'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS, Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995482</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DAMNING indictment of employment practices in the nineties, with permanent
full-time jobs being steadily phased out in favour of part-time and temporary
work, mainly to the detriment of employees, has emerged from new studies
commissioned by the Equal Opportunities Commission.
The growth in the so-called flexible labour market has many advantages for
employers but few for employees, particularly women, whose experience of
flexible working tends to involve being low-paid with few chances of promotion
or training.
EOC researchers found that the use of part-time and temporary workers had
increased ``substantially'' in the past five years, with women doing most of
the jobs.
Part-time work traditionally has been seen as helping women to combine home and
employment. However, research by Industrial Relations Services for the EOC
found that employers now tend to use part-time workers for commercial rather
than equal-opportunity reasons and that temporary and casual jobs are growing
at the expense of permanent posts.
Two out of five women of working age have a part-time job compared to one in 10
men, with much of the work being low paid.
Around 390,000 women - 4% of the total - have two part-time jobs, according to
the report.
In higher-status jobs the ``long hours culture'' prevented women from gaining
promotion, forcing them to work long hours for low pay to make ends meet. Even
when women do win promotion, the status of their managerial role is often
downgraded from that previously carried out by men.
Ms Kamlesh Bahl, the commission's chairwoman, said flexible working should be
good news for everyone trying to combine work and family responsibilities.
``However, we realise that flexibility also has its downside and we want to
find ways of overcoming this. We want to see equality of opportunity in
business strategies so that every business can make better use of all its human
resources to remain competitive. Equality has to be at the heart of the
workplace agenda.''
</TEXT>
