<DOCNO>GH951208-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Beef trade needs defending</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995483</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AM I alone in being horrified at the deliberate destruction of the beef trade
in the name of consumer protection?
The media wheel out bizarre specialists periodically to air their own
far-fetched theories about BSE and the dangers to humans thereof along with
unproven links with CJD, all glorying in the limelight of creating a story.
A clutch of fearful women profess to ``be done with beef for good'' because it
might harm their kids.
But has anyone pointed out to those same women that smoking, especially in
pregnancy, and passive smoking will definitely harm their kids; alcohol
dependency will harm the family; unprotected casual sex can lead to HIV
infection; and a diet ``rich'' in sweets, Cokes, chocolates, and ice-cream will
not only rot their their teeth but ultimately their guts as well?
Earnest do-gooders proclaim that 30 CJD deaths in two or three years are quite
intolerable while 50,000 dead and injured on the roads are quite acceptable,
but no-one suggests banning the motor-car!
Where are the NFU in all this while local authorities and private schools ban
the use of beef? Is it beyond them to promote a balanced view and get this
whole wretched business in perspective? Talk about fiddling while Rome burns!
Just the simple fact that red meat, especially beef, is one of the richest
sources of dietary iron readily available and easily assimilated by a child's
digestive system, needs to be given far more publicity.
There is a question of balance and probabilities. Every single scaremonger and
``Concerned parent of Bearsden'' will definitely be indulging in something
potentially more harmful than beef.
Renewing my subscription to the NFU in these circumstances is clearly an act of
faith, even if divorced from business sense.
J Brian Finlay,
Manor Cottage,
Ross, Borgue,
Kirkcudbright.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Delight at forest transfer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995484</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I READ your report (December 4) of the transfer of Strathmashie forest to
community control and the hands of the people of Laggan, with delight and
relief.
As a very callow young forester, I had the privilege of starting Strathmashie
in 1952, and recall vividly the expectations we had for it, and what it could
do for the district. Within a few years we had built a dozen houses (though in
the wrong site - they should have been added to the village) and employed over
20 men with planting and maintenance work.
That was just to be a beginning. We had great visions of when we started
producing timber from thinnings, and the expansion of labour demands that would
entail.
I go back there occasionally. Laggan was a magical place for me, and still is.
Above all, I wanted to see the thinnings start, and during one visit, met the
last survivor of ``the good old days''.
He confirmed that thinning had actually started, but then said: ``Mr Carlaw,
don't go to see it, it will break your heart''.
He was right. It looked as though the forest had been shelled. If that was
thinning, God save forestry. From having a resident forester and staff, not one
of the forestry houses holds a forestry worker in it. Not one man is now
employed at Strathmashie.
Supervision is I believe from Aviemore, and I can only guess at how frequent
and close this is, but if someone tells me it's non-existent, that will be no
surprise.
I do not blame the Forestry Commission for this dereliction, they can only
pander to the standards of this ostensibly Conservative Government, who have
not the slightest interest in anything other than the destruction of State
forestry.
When I think of the esprit de corps, the unpaid hours of work we all cheerfuly
put in, and how all this effort is nullified by a bunch of political
prostitutes masquerading as a Government, I could weep.
It will be interesting to see whether a financial arrangement can be made,
which will allow Laggan to assume control of the forest, but the idea of
Michael Forsyth changing into the regalia of Santa Claus stretches my
incredulity to breaking point.
Roy S Carlaw,
Burleywell,
St Mungo, Lockerbie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
