<DOCNO>GH951208-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Further research should take priority</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995485</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SINGULARLY the most significant problem currently affecting British beef
consumption is Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE), or ``mad-cow'' disease
as it has become more colloquially known.
Continually the Department of Health and the Chief Medical Officer have
persisted with the view that BSE cannot be transmitted to humans through the
consumption of beef. From where have they derived this evidence and what
scientific basis do they have for making this statement?
The problem with BSE and other TSEs (Transmissible Spongiform Encephalopathies)
is that the molecular mechanism of transmission still remains relatively
obscure and, as yet, the link between BSE and Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD)
is unclear.
Recent advances in molecular biology have started to ``unlock'' the elusive
nature of BSE and its transmission, albeit this work is at an early stage.
Research at the University of California, San Francisco, has identified
specialised proteins, known as ``prions'', which are thought to act
co-operatively with other proteins in the mechanisms associated with
transmission of BSE. If this work is correct then the basis of transmission may
finally be elucidated at some point in the future.
Clearly CJD is a matter of concern to the public; at the moment the scientific
fraternity knows much about the pathology of the disease but comparatively
little about its transmission.
Furthermore, since BSE and CJD are caused by what are thought to be ``slow''
viruses, it is difficult to estimate the time- course over which the first
outward manifestations of the disease may become evident, if it is transmitted
from cattle to humans.
Unquestionably, BSE and CJD pose numerous questions as to their origin and
transmission. Is there a hereditary basis to CJD? Do environmental factors play
a role in these neurodegenerative diseases? Is transmission from cattle to
humans the major route of transmission?
Since these pertinent scientific questions still remain largely unanswered
maybe the Department of Health would consider funding further research in these
fields instead of squandering money on full-page public health warnings in
national broadsheets.
Dr Victor J Furay,
14 Strowan Square,
Abbotsgrange, Grangemouth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Facing down the CBI's blackmail</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995486</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS amazed that unnamed members of the CBI in Scotland were given so much
publicity (December 6) without ``coming out'', until I reflected on the
situation.
Given that the tide of public opinion has swung firmly in favour of
constitutional change, and many business people are now finding the confidence
to support change, it is perhaps inevitable that we should see such an
attempted retrogressive coup at CBI Scotland.
However, their efforts and their methods are worthy of close scrutiny by the
Scottish people, and we should present them with a list of questions, in
keeping with their plans for Tony Blair. These could include:-
Do they view Scotland as some kind of Kazakhstan dependent on ``Mother
England''?
Do they wish to continue to subordinate Scotland's relationship with Europe
downstream of Westminster?
Do the business concepts of down-sizing, focus, empowerment, and management
buy-outs not apply to something as important as a nation?
Will they be entirely happy, once their names are known, about continuing
scrutiny of their personal and corporate motivation?
Will they accept a lower priority on grants from a Scottish government given
their latent tendency to ``quit Scotland``?
My own view is that this is an attempt to blackmail the aspirations of the
Scottish people, and as such it should be faced down. Scotland with increasing
power to determine our economic future in Europe will attract replacements for
any withdrawals, and will be able to generate a ``can-do'' self-help confident
culture that will energise business and individuals.
It will be interesting to see if the Scottish Council of the CBI can handle
this attempt to railroad policy, and whether the ``leading companies'' and
their spokespersons deign to name themselves.
Indeed it will be interesting to see if CBI Scotland starts to plan for a time
when, in line with the creation of a devolved Scottish parliament, it creates
the Confederation of Scottish Industry.
J S Mather,
13 Sutherland Avenue,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How the minimum wage endangers jobs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995487</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS the managing director of a medium-size management company I am becoming
increasingly concerned about the implications of the minimum wage with regard
to small businesses.
I fail to understand how the introduction of a minimum wage will lead to
anything other than a huge increase in unemployment levels, particularly among
the young.
For any company to be competitive, it must keep a tight rein on the amount of
money it pays its staff. The one common factor with most companies which pay
salaries above the market rate is that sooner or later they go bust, thus
placing all their employees on the dole.
It is not for Government to dictate what a particular job function may or may
not be worth. Someone's wage is not a reflection of their worth, it is a
reflection of the financial return they generate, directly or indirectly, for
the company that employs them.
Someone of similar ability in a different job to which they are better suited
may earn twice as much.
John Prescott calls for full employment, which is a sentiment we all support in
theory. The trouble is we live in the real world where we have to find
practical solutions to everyday problems.
The Labour Party's solution to unemployment is to introduce the minimum wage at
a yet to be determined level. If this is the solution why is it that countries
which have already tried John Prescott's solution of the minimum wage have
unemployment levels so much higher than our own?
In Britain the unemployment level is 8.3% of the population, in Scotland 8.1%,
yet in Belgium, France, and Spain the unemployment levels are 14.9%, 11.4%, and
22.7% respectively, all of them merrily putting into practice Mr Prescott's
solution of the minimum wage.
The Labour Party should re-examine its policies on employment, drop the minimum
wage, and come up with a practical solution that will create jobs and
investment similar to the 3300 new jobs created in Lanarkshire by the Taiwanese
company Chunghwa.
Hugh Craigie Halkett,
24 Dean Park Street,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bus questions</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995488</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BUS deregulation throughout the country has proved not to be the panacea for
the travelling public for whom it was intended.
Now that the police are calling for stricter limits on potential drunk drivers
and encouraging them to use public transport over the festive period, ask
yourself some questions about the bus company you travel with.
Do they provide a service outwith normal working hours? Will they be there to
bring you home from your party night? Do they exist only to exploit the popular
market? Do they exploit their employees by paying low wages with little
training and few career opportunities? Can the local community and particularly
the elderly depend on them? Is your safety their priority?
What is needed is a properly funded, regulated public transport system that
answers all these questions satisfactorily.
Jim Sheridan ,
TGWU Convener,
Barr &amp; Stroud,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unified network</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995489</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN my recent letter I shared some of my experiences while travelling on the
InterCity West Coast line, particularly the failure of the system to ensure
connections following the splitting up of the whole network into smaller
companies.
Weary of the misadventures on the West Coast line, my wife and I transferred
our custom on an experimental basis to the long-distance coach services from
Glasgow provided by National Express. We have been most impressed with the
service.
Out of 14 journeys over the last eight months we have had punctual arrivals in
all but two; the coaches are clean and comfortable; pleasant staff in general;
service a little slower than the train but at a fraction of the price - and no
cancellations.
The service seems to work. A glib analyst might suggest this is because it is
privatised, but it is more fundamental than that. It is because National
Express operates a single, unified network covering the whole of England and
Wales, and, in association with Scottish Citylink, the extremes of Scotland as
well.
Peter Garside,
73 Argyle Way,
Dunblane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Best service to Amsterdam</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995490</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN response to the letter headed Air monopoly to Amsterdam (December 6), I
believe that the author should consider the facts.
The Scotland to Amsterdam route is currently one of the most important European
routes for business travellers to and from Scotland.
With an investment that is unmatched by any other domestic carrier, Air UK has
provided this service since the company's inception in 1980. Services are now
operated daily from Aberdeen, Edinburgh, and Glasgow airports.
Far from operating a monopoly as suggested by J D McLaren, Air UK has faced
intense competition since its inception and its successful operation is based
on both a highly efficient and quality conscious service.
More and more passengers are also choosing to fly to and from Scotland to
Amsterdam Schiphol due to our interline link with KLM - a European business
partnership which allows our customers to connect to KLM's ``wave'' system of
flights to over 150 worldwide destinations.
The lack of competition is not due to monopoly conditions but rather the
inability of any operator, to date, to provide a better service on these routes.
Alex Donald,
Air UK,
177/179 West George Street, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The avoidability of Aids</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995491</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAVING passed many people sporting the red ribbon to mark empathy for Aids
sufferers and later having watched television on which almost every person also
wore the red ribbon, it came as a breath of fresh air to read J P Leach's
article in which he blew the cool air of proportion on political correctness
(December 2).
Of course people who have Aids suffer, but for the population in general
avoiding unprotected homosexual sex and sharing needles if taking drugs will
protect them.
Involved as I am with people who have Marfan's Syndrome, with higher death
figures than Aids, I wonder often how to grab public awareness for a syndrome
which can also be passed on in the womb but which does not allow the sufferers
the luxury of avoiding it through lifestyle.
Christine M Mitchell,
Support Group Leader,
The Marfan Organisation Strathclyde,
1 Border Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No headline present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995492</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE cautious and slightly jaded responses by both the SNP and Labour to the
community ownership initiative by the Secretary of State over Strathmashie
Forest are understandable if regrettable (December 5).
It seems that in the hurry to mitigate any potential political gains which
might be made, these parties have forgotten the immense boost this initiative
will give to both the confidence and economic security of people in this
fragile place.
The crisis of living in sparsely populated areas with the constant reality of
economic sustainability and environmental fragility seems to have been lost in
the welter of complaint against what is a bold, timely and imaginative move.
The impact of the 15 jobs, the securing of local forestry skills and competence
and the celebration of hope this will give to the people of Laggan will be
enormous.
It would seem too early for electioneering and too congruent to the Secretary
of State's oft-declared position on power decentralisation to be called
anything else other than welcome.
For the people of Laggan this is their Millennium Forest: and I suspect it
hasn't come a moment too early for them.
Geoff Fagan,
Project Manager, Conservation and Development in Sparsely Populated Areas
(Scotland),
Jordanhill Campus,
University of Strathclyde.
</TEXT>
