<DOCID>GH951208-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nigerian wins expulsion delay</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995493</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NIGERIAN yesterday won a last-minute reprieve from being deported from
Britain.
Solicitors representing Mr Ade Onibiyo, 19, were granted five working days to
seek leave to move for judicial review of the decision to expel him.
Home Office Minister Ann Widdecombe said any application for judicial review
would be contested. Mr Onibiyo's removal has been rescheduled for December 14.
Campaigners have argued that Mr Onibiyo will be in serious danger if he is
returned to Nigeria. His 53-year-old father, Abdul, was deported to Lagos in
October and has not been in contact with his wife and five children since.
Nigeria was suspended from the Commonwealth for executing nine activists,
including dissident writer Ken Saro-Wiwa, last month.
The country will be expelled in two years unless there are major human rights
improvements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
