<DOCNO>GH951208-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Japanese growth of 1.8% predicted</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995494</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S economy is likely to grow less than 2% next year after four years of
negligible growth, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development
(OECD) said today.
The Paris-based think tank predicted in an economic survey of Japan that gross
domestic product (GDP) would grow 1.8% in calendar 1996 after estimated growth
of 0.3% this year.
It revised downward its June forecasts of 2.3% growth in 1996 and 1.3% in 1995,
citing the yen's sharp rally in earlier this year as a factor in an ``aborted
recovery''. ``The economy is experiencing an exceptionally long period of
depressed activity, as hopes of a recovery, evident in 1994, did not fully
materialise,'' said the report.
Tokyo was not happy with the forecasts, saying that the OECD appeared to have
underestimated the stimulative effect of a government economic package
announced in September.
Japan will set a growth target of more than 2% for the business year starting
next April, government sources said.-Reuter
</TEXT>
