<HEADLINE>The season to be jolly professional</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Francis Shennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>scotlands appointments</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974995495</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Planning a festive
party? `Bring on the the experts' is the theme as corporate hospitality
becomes big business at this time of year, says Francis Shennan
IT'S party time and, for companies, throwing a bad Christmas party is worse
than no party at all. Used properly, the right social occasion can help to
build or cement relationships with customers, suppliers or staff.
But just as no other part of business relationships would be entrusted to
amateurs, entertaining guests is increasingly entrusted to professionals. No
matter how professional the managing director's secretary is, it does not make
her a good party-giver, regardless of her private life.
Helping people to relax, to mix, to enjoy themselves is a skill and the more
important the people the more essential it is to achieve. Hence the growth of
the corporate hospitality industry.
The image of the industry is still largely one of the marquees arranged around
a sporting event like the camp of a marauding army, filled with executives
being filled in turn with food and drink. The potential for those with the
locations to host events was quickly spotted.
Hotels, conference centres, universities and colleges, football clubs, even
buildings such as Glasgow's Museum of Transport, can earn income from corporate
hospitality. But location is not enough. Guests need to be entertained, and the
corporate entertainment business grew accordingly.
``It's building up: I have a lot more people booked this year than last year,''
says Alison Low, who started Premier Leisure Scotland Ltd five years ago.
She books the Strathclyde Suite at the Glasgow Royal Concert Hall and then
organises evenings for companies such as ScottishPower, Scottish Mutual,
Scottish Prudential and Scottish Provincial. ``The majority of people I have
coming along are people who would otherwise be booked into a hotel,'' she says.
Her evenings, attended by up to 330 people, include a three-course dinner,
disco, ceilidh band and entertainment casino provided by Top Hat (see separate
story).
``There is something for everyone,'' she says. ``The thing about the casino is
that guests get to meet people. They are all from different places and they get
to meet and talk over the tables.''
Corporate entertainers and organisers have to understand the business needs of
their clients. The entertainment must be professional yet must not intrude too
much into the opportunities for guests to meet and talk.
``They want flexible entertainment which will not overshadow the opportunity to
network,'' says Dusty the Magician, also known as Bill Miller, senior events
consultant for The Entertainment Company which provides entertainment to all
Scotland's major five-and four-star hotels.
``The last thing clients want to feel is that they are coming there for a hard
sell. Magic is a wonderful medium because it is so flexible. It can be a
two-minute or a 20-minute show. People like a laugh and I use magic as a
vehicle for all-round entertainment.
``You can tailor the act to a customer's product or message. The cards which I
make reappear in a guest's pocket can carry a message like `The Magic of Esso'
or `Texaco Takes a Trick'.''
He performs close-up magic at small dinner parties, cocktail receptions and
larger functions, as well as with Top Hat Casinos where he often sets up his
Bunco Booth. Two years ago he became the first Scot to be named Close-up
Magician of the Year by the International Brotherhood of Magicians.
``I tend to find I would treble the amount of work I do at this time of year,''
he says. ``Companies are going for fewer guests and a bigger spend. Clients are
deciding that, rather than 100 people, they will have 20 guests and spend the
money on their 20 best customers or staff.''
Entertainment is also becoming a Scottish export. ``We are exporting our
services south of the border. Companies like Scottish Equitable and Scottish
Life, which we have done work for in Scotland, will take me down to Birmingham
or London for functions there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
