<DOCNO>GH951208-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>It's a safe bet you don't need real cash to have real fun</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Francis Shennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Scotlands appointments</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995496</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CORPORATE entertainment might be fun for the customer but it is a serious
business for the leading companies. Top Hat Casinos was one of the firms
selected to compete in the latest series of Scottish Television's Business
Game, alongside computer equipment manufacturers and sophisticated engineering
firms.
The West Lothian-based business describes itself as ``The Entertainment
Casino'', for its function is to entertain its clients' guests. It uses only
fun money, which can be specially printed with the client's logo.
Yet all its staff are casino-trained and its equipment - roulette, blackjack
and dice tables down to chips which can cost 50p each - is full-size, genuine
casino equipment. It adds to the problems of transportation, even in the firm's
specially-equipped and liveried van, but it ensures guests enjoy the authentic
feel of a casino. And the use of fun money does little to dampen the enthusiasm
of the players. Guests are given a set amount of fun money when they arrive and
try to increase their stake. At the end of the evening, the client presents
prizes to those who have won the most.
Charities use Top Hat Casinos for fund-raising. Guests still compete for prizes
but in this case they buy the fun money. At no time do casino staff members
handle real money.
Casinos can be themed to include Western nights, gangster nights and Las Vegas
nights, complete with Elvis and Frank Sinatra lookalikes - and soundalikes, of
course.
``Our clients include major companies, such as J&amp;B Whisky and upmarket car
distributorships,'' says Top Hat's owner and founder, Marion Young. ``The
venues where we appear include the best hotels such as Gleneagles, the Hilton,
and the Moat House.
``So our standards of professionalism have to be at least as high as theirs. We
have been chosen by these clients to entertain their personally-invited guests
so in a way we are representing that company.
``We have first-hand knowledge of most of the major locations but in the case
of a new one, we will reconnoitre entrances and exits to ensure that all our
staff and equipment are in place on time and that we get our tables out without
any disturbance to guests.
</TEXT>
