<DOCNO>GH951208-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prisons paralysis Pressure for an alternative to remand</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995497</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE recently-retired prisons inspector for England, Judge Stephen Tumim, in an
interview with this newspaper last week, said most people he had encountered
behind bars were uneducated, socially inadequate young men and that, prison
being fundamentally about cutting the crime rate, we should be throwing at them
education, in all its forms. But when the jails are chronically overcrowded, as
they are in Scotland, that goal becomes impossible to attain. We literally pour
money down a bottomless prisons pit because reoffending cannot properly be
addressed. An even worse feature of the overcrowding is that so much of it is
caused by untried remandees, 60% of whom will be judged innocent or given a
non-custodial sentence. It remains an affront that they receive the worst deal
of all our numerous Scottish prisoners.
It is not a new problem but one which seems to have caused a paralysis in our
judicial and social systems. At the centre of this is the conundrum that the
Government is genuinely worried about having too many people on remand, while
at the same time, because of its own love affair with prison, is forced to
respond over-strongly to concerns such as the level of reoffending on bail.
There has been considerable pressure from a frustrated police service over
this, which is understandable.
Bail has undoubtedly become less attractive to a judiciary who were not noted
for views informed by liberality in the first place. Crime rates in Scotland
are also falling, with more effective policing playing a part, and that has
consequences for the prisons. The other element in the chain, which also has
the effect of swelling the prison remand population, is the question of fine
default, and here it does not appear that the judiciary is solely to blame.
Successive Scottish Ministers seem to have dragged their feet over the
provision of an alternative and their attitude is still that they want more
proof that the diversion schemes work before further resources are committed.
But how much more proof do they need? The highly-reputable reform body, SACRO,
says Scotland urgently requires a shift of focus away from remands in custody
towards community-based facilities to support people on bail and reduce the
risk of their reoffending. Over 80% do not offend on bail and we should target
the resources towards supporting the minority who do. Their own programmes are
known successes. We also know of the real dangers in the hardening of
attitudes; the families of three young women who died in Cornton Vale Prison
have told us about that and we know that self-harm and attempted suicides are
over-represented among remands.
The Scottish Office should now signal a more positive attitude towards bail
hostels, fine supervision, and other community-based support systems. There is
also scope for a genuinely innovative approach to actual remand which would
require some change in the law. At the moment most remandees, more than 1000
prisoners in any single day, sit around doing nothing, because neither work nor
education is compulsory. The system is therefore clogged by idle, bored, and
traumatised people, around 15,000 of them a year, for whom nothing can be done.
They often appear to be there, not because they represent any real danger to
the public, but because they are a persistent nuisance. For all the wrong
reasons the Government continues to ignore its own oft-repeated dictum that
prison should be for those from whom society needs physical protection. The
pressure for change is mounting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
