<DOCNO>GH951208-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How training makes the service smiles better</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>joan grady</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>training</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995499</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STAFF training also benefits the retailer. While most consumers in the Touche
Ross survey put customer service sixth on the list of their shopping
priorities, few would return to any shop which did not serve them well.
Fashion retail chain French Connection bases much of its training on this
principle. ``We believe if we train our staff to improve their product
knowledge it improves their customer service as well,'' says store manager
Laura Clink at Glasgow's Union Street store.
``This hopefully also boosts customer loyalty. If our customers feel they've
been treated well and are pleased with the results they are more likely to come
back and shop here again.''
Laura and her team train every Saturday morning. Topics are not always centred
around product - there are too many other elements to the job. ``We all sit
down and discuss the day's training topic,'' she says. ``It could be customer
service, till procedures, administration, filing in the office, or new staff
incentive schemes.
``We run different incentives where staff get prizes for performing well.
Prizes can be anything from a free meal to additional discounts on
merchanise.'' The few weeks leading up to Christmas will see the store become
progressively busier as people flock to the shops to buy their presents and
party outfits. Over the next three Saturdays Laura will prepare her team for
the Christmas rush by recapping all customer service training. She'll be
getting them ready for the difficult business of remaining calm and collected
in the face of stressed shoppers.
``We want our customers to leave the shop feeling as though they've been well
looked after,'' she says. ``If we don't recap on training we can't be fully
efficient - and we want to make sure we keep our customers happy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The senseless killing of Spike</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995500</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
.ON Sunday, in the quietness of a cemetery in Stirling two women linked
inextricably by grief and love will stand together in silent prayer. One will
be remembering the man she was going to marry, the other the son she brought up
to be a scientist. The murder of Dr Michael Meenaghan, a 33-year-old Oxford
biochemist gunned down in his own home in the university city exactly a year
ago remains unsolved. Police investigations into the killing all but closed in
June, although a #10,000 reward for information is still on offer.
Colin Dexter, creator of Inspector Morse, plans to use this town-and-gown
slaying as the background to a future mystery plot. All that though, is
meaningless to the mother who shared his past, and the lover who planned to
share his future. Their shared grief has helped them cope with tragedy; their
new-found affection for each other will help them face an uncertain future.
It took only a single blast from a 12-bore sawn-off shotgun to kill the 6ft
5in biochemist. Known to all his friends as Spike, he died from severe wounds
to his upper chest. Here Pat Meenaghan and Denise Holt speak about the tragedy
that has brought them so close together.
DETECTIVE Chief Inspector Morse would have long since resolved it, but real
life isn't like that. The worst thing for Pat Meenaghan and Denise Holt is that
they might never know.
On Sunday they will attend mass, go to the cemetery, place flowers on the
grave, and wonder at the terrible twist of fate that has brought them together.
People witnessing this scene at St Thomas's in Stirling might think they are
mother and daughter.
The relationship they have developed is everything that Denise had hoped for
when Michael was alive and when they were planning marriage. But Pat and Denise
never met before Michael's funeral.
Now Pat thinks they could not be closer. Photographs of Denise's children are
displayed proudly on the wall of her living room, just above the shelf that
carries her son's bound doctorate thesis. ``She is just like a daughter to me.''
Pat didn't even know that Denise existed and that her only son was planning to
put his house in Oxford on the market so that he could move in with Denise,
already married twice and the mother of three children.
``Had he told me that he was going to marry a woman who had already been
married twice with three children, I would have shown him the door,'' said Mrs
Meenaghan. She might have grey hair, she might be a woman suffering from
angina, and she might now be widowed and on her own, but Pat Meenaghan is not a
woman to be trifled with.
Michael had warned Denise: ``Don't cross my mum. She would eat you alive.''
Nevertheless he had worked out a plan to break the news about his love for
Denise gently to his mother last Christmas. He also had it worked out that
within not many more weeks he would have prepared Denise's three children for a
new life. ``I'll talk them round and we will be married within six months,'' he
said.
The day before the murder had been special for Denise and Spike. It was the
anniversary of the first time they had made love.
Michael was a Guardian reader, proud of his Scottish working class background.
At the same time he was soppy. To him Denise was Maisie. It had begun as an
insult, but thereafter it became a pet name. On Valentine's day he had put a
message in the Guardian: ``Maisie - Will you love me until I am dead? -
Michael.''
That last night together he argued over a topical story that had made
headlines. He insisted it was perfectly all right for someone to use a shotgun
to protect his property.
They parted in their usual manner at three o'clock in the morning. Michael
closed his front door and each of them pressed hands against the glass pane. On
other times they pressed noses against the glass, more often than not with
Virus, the cat Denise had bought Michael for company, on his shoulder.
They were to meet in Birmingham at 8pm that night to attend a folk-rock gig in
a pub. She went shopping that afternoon but suddenly at 4.15pm felt ill. ``It
was as if I could not breathe. I had to get out of the shop. Fifteen minutes
later I felt better.''
Spike was shot just before 4.30pm.
Of course he didn't turn up at their meeting place that evening, so she went on
to the gig alone, thinking eventually he would turn up.
All evening she made frantic telephone calls. She knew perfectly well that if
his car had broken down he would get a message to her. ``I must have tried 15
times to get him on the phone. I even put a call through to his lab. I knew
something was wrong...... seriously wrong.'' So she headed for Oxford.
Denise added: ``I turned into the street and all I could see was the blazing
lights coming from his house. I knew then it was even more serious than my
worst nightmare...... Michael never put more than one light on in the house.
Then I saw the police van.''
The officer guarding the door would not let her past. He appeared shocked and
did not want to look into her eyes. ``There has been a terrible shooting,' he
said.
``Please don't tell me he is dead.''
Denise grasped his face between her hands, forcing him to look into her eyes,
and said: ``Let me breathe into him. Let me touch him. I can make him alive
again.''
``No you can't,'' the policeman said gently. Later Denise was to learn that
officer's name was Andrew.
Such is the nature of murder inquiries that Denise immediately became a suspect
and was taken to a police station for most of the night.
``You cannot imagine the horror,'' she said. ``At one moment you have been told
your fella has been murdered and then you are in this room whith a total
stranger who is dressed in white paper overalls to prevent contamination and
you are being swabbed about the face to see if there is powder residue.''
Eventually she was driven home to Birmingham, but the police investigation into
her life had just begun. They look at everything, bank statements, telephone
bills, correspondence, and they speak to everyone a suspect has been in contact
with, no matter the distress it might cause.
Although the investigation is now closed, and Denise has long since been
eliminated as a suspect, the police still retain her love letters in case they
might eventually prove to be evidence. She and Spike wrote three or four times
a week, even though they were seeing each other all the time. He sent flowers
and they spoke constantly on the telephone. ``My phone bill was #300 a
quarter,'' she said.
However, there was one letter the police did not get. ``That was the best
one...... `I want you as my wife...... mother to my children...... the first
thing I see in the morning...... the last thing at night......'.''
By this time Mrs Meenaghan was also in Oxford. She had been told of her son's
death by two Stirling policeman who came to her at 8am on Sunday.
She didn't believe it at first, but eventually was telling neighbours:
``Someone's killed my Michael. They have murdered my Michael.''
Despite the valium she still remembers being asked by Oxford police if she
would meet Denise. ``I wanted to know `Who is this Denise anyway?','' said Mrs
Meenaghan. There was no meeting between the two women in Oxford. They did not
meet until the night before the funeral, when Michael's body was taken into
church.
First Denise wrote to Pat Meenaghan. ``It was a lovely letter. I have it
here,'' says Pat. ``I never thought I would meet the lassie, but I did think it
was brave of her to write.''
Denise recalls: ``I had to let her know about our relationship. Then I
telephoned her. I could not go to the funeral without her knowing who I was and
there was no way I was not going.
``On the phone she gave me a right bollocking. She ranted a lot, but we spoke
for two hours. She was grief stricken, but I understood.''
Pat doesn't recall this. ``I don't remember the phone calls. I was not in this
world. I was just hollow inside.''
When Denise travelled north for the funeral she took with her the Caithness
Crystal won at Perth a few months earlier by a mixed volleyball team she and
Spike had played in.
``There were all these people I didn't know,'' said Denise. ``How could he be
the love of my life and I his and I didn't know them. They must have been
looking at me and saying: `Who is that?'.''
Denise remembers Pat and herself nodding at each other. Pat is sure she shook
Denise's hand. Later Denise was invited home for tea and sandwiches. ``It was
my fella's funeral,'' said Denise. ``I was not going to be a guest, so I went
into the kitchen and made tea.''
Next day her flowers to Michael responded to his Valentine's Day message in the
Guardian. ``Michael - Beyond death, Maisie.''
When Denise made it known that she would be returning to visit the grave in a
few week's time, Pat insisted that she stay with her. ``But don't come back
greetin','' she added.
``She was brilliant she did everything she could,'' said Denise. ``She showed
me his baby pictures and there he was in his dad's arms. That's how I imagine
them now.''
She visits his grave every two months or so, but tries not to look at his name
on the gravestone. ``That's something I have noticed,'' says Pat.
The two woman are constantly on the phone to each other. ``He has been dead for
a year, but my telephone bill is just as big,'' said Denise.
``At first I wanted to be with Pat because she was the closest thing to him.
Now I really love her.''
Detective Superintendent David Blair, a quietly spoken Ulsterman who has spent
most of his life in England and who has 30 years' experience with Thames Valley
Police behind him, was in charge of the case. He admitted: ``I don't know where
the answer lies.
``Serious crimes do go unresolved, but there are not many where you don't form
ideas on how it might have happened. Every member of my team to a man say they
don't know who it was and they don't know why.''
The investigation was energetically and enthusiastically pursued, but one by
one each lead was eliminated.
``We reached the stage we could not legitimately carry the investigation on,''
he said.
``I am tempted to think this might have been a one off job,'' he added. ``It
could be there was no intention to kill. A shotgun fired into a darkened room,
with only one shot fired, does not guarantee success.''
However, he still holds that if it been a professional hit the killer would
have gone to the front door and fired at point-blank range when his knock was
answered.
He does not rule out the drugged-up burglar scenario, whereby a crazed gunman
fired off a shot when disturbed. It did hold some water, given the
extraordinary circumstances of the case, he said. However, burglars do not
normally carry shotguns. ``With every theory in this case, there is something
to knock it down,'' Mr Blair adds.
In June he travelled to Birmingham and to Stirling to let Denise and Pat know
that the investigation was being wound down, and no longer would be pursued
actively.
So how does he feel?
``Disappointed,'' Mr Blair said before adding: ``All the more so because we
cannot tell his family and his loved ones the reason why. If nothing else, they
deserve to know that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
