<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Macfie threat to Waddell's reign</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Elspeth Burnside</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995501</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN'S Claire Waddell is set to face her first serious challenge of the
season when she defends the Scottish championship at Heriot-Watt University
next week.
The Stirling University student has had it all her own way on the domestic
front this season, but has had to settle for a share of the top seeding with
London-based Senga Macfie in the national event.
Waddell scored a shock win over world No.20 Macfie in last year's final, and
has since gone on to help Scotland win a bronze medal at this year's European
championship and maintain an unbeaten record at home.
Macfie, who also suffered a surprise defeat, from Alison Bowie, on her Scottish
championship debut two years ago, has had an up-and-down season on the world
circuit recently. But she did show form with a win over New Zealand's Phillipa
Beans in the Cyprus International last month, and is desperate to make it third
time lucky in Scotland.
Martin Heath, top seed in the men's event, gave world No.2 Rodney Eyles a scare
before going out of the Mahindra International Challenge in Bombay by 8-15,
15-11, 13-15, 15-12, 15-9.
In the same tournament, Peter Nicol, who will not be defending the Scottish
title, defeated Egyptian Ahmed Barada, a former Scottish Junior Open champion,
15-11, 10-15, 15-3, 11-15, 15-8.
ELSPETH BURNSIDE
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clever but unhelpful Blair miscalculates over tax pledge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995502</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of the great aims of devolution is to give Scotland a measure of modern,
accountable government; to remove, if you like, the democratic deficit. Yet if
democracy is to be brought to the governance of Scottish affairs it should be a
grown-up democracy, not a nappied affair which must grow whiskers before it can
be treated like an adult, nor one which cannot change its mind in the course of
time if circumstances warrant. Tony Blair's remarkable interview in this
newspaper appears to point to a vision of a Scottish Assembly which must seek a
mandate before each term for the revenue-raising powers which will make it
worth while. In the absolute sense there is nothing wrong with this. Any party
seeking the support of the electorate should be prepared to set out its views
and intentions as far as the latter can be ascertained in advance. In this Mr
Blair is returning to his familiar theme of the tax promises made by the Tory
Government and subsequently broken.
Yet he appears to wish to take this particular line of thinking further. He
seems intent on launching his party into the first election for a Scottish
Assembly with a manifesto which will not advocate a tax increase. Moreover, in
line with his detestation of promises made and broken, the logical inference of
this is that a Labour administration leading a Scottish Assembly and elected on
a no-tax-raising platform would not raise taxes during the term of the
Assembly, no matter what happens. We can sympathise with Mr Blair's intentions
here. Undoubtedly he wants to consign Michael Forsyth's ``Tartan Tax'' campaign
to the region of tabloid ghouls and hobgoblins which it should rightly inhabit,
yet in doing so he has indicated his unease with the success of Mr Forsyth's
propaganda, and in an important sense he has surrendered some of the initiative
to his opponent.
Other things will follow from Mr Blair's latest thoughts. If a Labour
administration is elected on the basis already described and leads, perhaps in
coalition, a Scottish Assembly it will find itself in hideous difficulties if a
need should arise suddenly to raise or lower taxes. This could be envisaged in
the context of a crisis in Scottish education which might necessitate urgent
revenue. Under Mr Blair's plan the only thing that the Labour administration
could do in these circumstances would be to fall on its sword, dissolve the
Assembly, and call a fresh election with a platform seeking raised (or in other
circumstances, lowered) taxes. This is certainly direct democracy, but so
direct that it would be painful. Presumably Mr Blair does not intend that the
Westminster Parliament should adopt these rules. How would Chancellor Brown
react if he had to call a General Election every time he wished to raise or
lower taxes?
At first glance Mr Blair is not trying to redraft the proposals of the
Constitutional Convention; he is saying merely that his party will behave in a
certain way. Yet the effect of this, given Labour's popularity in Scotland, is
effectively to alter the manner in which any Assembly will function. In this
respect his views are bound to be seen as taking the entire affair backwards,
and they will undoubtedly infuriate the many allies who worked with Labour on
the formation of the proposals for an Assembly. What Mr Blair is proposing is
certainly clever. He hopes it will demolish the ``Tartan Tax'' offensive; and
it will probably help him convince those English Labour MPs who harbour doubts
about devolution. He is entitled to do it because he commits nobody other than
his own party, yet it is disruptive and regressive and ultimately unhelpful.
</TEXT>
