<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Yes, there is working life after graduation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill Sinclair</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>training</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995503</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOMEWHERE out there, there must be an employer who can use my educational
qualifications and my willingness to work. If only someone would give me the
chance to show what I can do . . .
That's the theme which runs through the thoughts of every unemployed graduate.
And yes, out there, there are employers keen to find people who are well
qualified, are eager to work - and who already have relevant work experience.
This problem of matching people and jobs is being tackled with enthusiam,
commitment and a great deal of success by the Vista Graduate Gateway Programme.
Vista is the training department of Asset, which stands for Ardrossan,
Saltcoats, Stevenson Enterprise Trust, and it is supported by Enterprise
Ayrshire.
Based in Stevenson, it is open to all graduates - from HNC to PhD, and from
theology to astrophysics - and it now welcomes graduates from Glasgow as well
as those living in Ayrshire.
The secret of the scheme's 83% success rate lies in its specialist training
courses leading to 26-week job placements in the field of the graduate's
choice. This gives them the all-important work experience and a very real
chance to prove themselves in a business environment and enhance their
understanding of business philosophy and practice.
Senior training officer Irene Innes lays great store by the way Vista takes
graduates in one at a time and not as part of a course intake.
``We believe we offer a great deal to unemployed graduates at a low point in
their lives, and we are very conscious of the importance of dealing with them
as individuals,'' she says.
On the other hand, what draws many graduates to the programme is the
recognition that they are not alone in the struggle to find a suitable job and
the club-style companionship of others in a similar plight.
While placements are being sought and arranged, the graduates are offered
courses in four modules - management, quality control, self-investment, and
health and safety.
They are given guidance on career choices, the compilation of CVs, and inteview
techniques.
Mrs Innes says: ``When we started eight years ago it was quite tricky finding
companies to co-operate with placements. We have now broken that barrier and
companies are coming to me and asking to be kept in mind if a graduate wants to
work in their field.''
It was seeing her grandfather's name in an advertisement in The Herald that led
Karen Begg to her new job as an administration officer with Quarriers.
She is working on the James Shield Project, which last week opened a hostel for
homeless young people in the Gorbals. The project is named after a former Lord
Provost of Glasgow who, by chance, had the same name as her grandfather.
Karen, an honours Bachelor of Education graduate, had decided to diversify from
a teaching career and, realising the difficulty of finding another job, joined
Graduate Gateway.
She was successful in finding a placement with Craigie College where she gained
experience in administration and the European desk.
Karen says: ``I really enjoy working as a member of a team, and I'm certain I
would not have got this job without the placement experience.''
Sean Davey knew of Graduate Gateway because his older sister Angela, an English
graduate, found a job through Asset and is now working with the Scottish Office.
Having gained an HND in computing, Sean recognised that his lack of relevant
experience was a distinct disadvantage in finding a job and he was very keen to
obtain a work experience placement in the IT field.
He says he found the Gateway courses on management skills, health and safety,
and quality control most valuable, and he was delighted to be given a placement
with SAZTEC, a data capture company in Ardrossan.
Sean's computing skills matched the needs of the company and he was allocated
responsible tasks within the IT department. The outcome was the offer of a
full-time post, which he started on November 1.
Sean's methodical and realistic approach to his job search paid off and his
abilities are now being used to full effect.
Fiona Murray, an honours BSc graduate, was about to buy a property in Fife when
the company she worked for went out of business. On returning to her home base
in Irvine, she found it very difficult to find a new job and became very
demotivated.
``I was at the end of my tether and had decided to head south to take a job
pulling pints,'' she says. ``I was being told that I was over-qualified,
lacking experience, or too old at 27. If it hadn't been for Graduate Gateway, I
would have fallen through the net. It was my one and only chance of a proper
job.''
On joining the Gateway programme Fiona took time to talk through her career
options and decided to apply for a placement which would allow her to use her
knowledge of multimedia and which would also provide her with experience in
training.
She found such a placement with Ayrshire ITec. She proved to be an excellent
worker and the company did not want to lose her skills at the end of the
placement, so now she has a full-time job.
Fiona says: ``If a lot more graduates were aware of the Graduate Gateway
programme it would make the world a much better place for them.''
q For further information, telephone Irene Innes on 01294-468000.
</TEXT>
