<HEADLINE>Trust seeks more Japanese shares</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995504</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARTIN Currie's Scottish Eastern Investment Trust has borrowed 4.65 billion yen
(#30m) to buy more Japanese shares, particularly in the resurgent electrical
and retail sectors.
The two-year loan carries an interest rate of just over 1% and will help
Scottish Eastern to boost Japanese equities to 12% of its #790m investment
portfolio from 9% at present.
``This move is consistent with our positive view of the Japanese stock
market,'' said Martin Currie director Eric McAuslan.
``We are forecasting annual economic growth to reach 2.5% in the next fiscal
year and we look for big substantial growth from Japanese equities in 1996.''
The new loan raises Scottish Eastern's borrowings to 19% of net assets from
14%.
</TEXT>
