<DOCNO>GH951208-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man told `your wife is dying'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995506</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN who was told erroneously that his wife was dying of cancer, is now
demanding an explanation from the hospital that issued the prognosis.
Mr Alex MacMillan kept the harrowing news to himself for a fortnight, before
telling his two daughters. Two days later, he was told the prognosis had been a
mistake.
Directors of Hairmyres Hospital in East Kilbride say an inquiry will be held
into the family's claim that Mrs MacMillan, 44, was wrongly diagnosed as being
close to death.
Mr MacMillan, 44, told yesterday how he struggled to come to terms with the
news that his wife could be dead within three months.
He said he had yet to receive an explanation for the error.
``Janette underwent a life-saving operation three years ago after she was
diagnosed as having breast cancer,'' said Mr MacMillan.
``Recently though, she was suffering a new pain and an ovarian cyst was
diagnosed.
``She received treatment at Hairmyres and at Stobhill Hospital in Glasgow.
``I got a phone call asking that I go to Hairmyres. I was taken to an office
alone and told by a doctor that he believed the cancer had spread to her
stomach.
``He said they could operate but that, at worst, Janette only had about three
months to live.
``I was absolutely devastated.''
Following the news, Mr MacMillan, from Comely Bank, Hamilton, Lanarkshire,
tried to gather his thoughts.
After almost two weeks, he told daughters Sandra, 25, and Yvonne, 22.
``It was a terrible shock for them,'' he said.
``We decided not to tell Janette. How do you tell someone, even your wife, news
like that?''
Two days after Mr MacMillan told his daughters the prognosis, Stobhill Hospital
informed him that Mrs MacMillan was in the clear. The cyst was not malignant
and could be treated.
This diagnosis was confirmed later by Hairmyres Hospital.
Mr MacMillan, a foreman with Scottish Power, said: ``It was only then that I
told Janette what had been going on.
``At first she thought I was joking. But soon she realised it was no joke.''
Mrs MacMillan said: ``It wasn't as if I was prepared for anything like this to
happen because I thought I was in the clear. So when I was told about it, I
just went into shock.''
Now the family have asked the hospital for an explanation.
Mrs MacMillan is back at work in a clothing factory after hospital treatment.
Last night, the assistant director of administration at Hairmyres, Mr John
Gray, said an inquiry was under way.
``We have already had a meeting with Mr and Mrs MacMillan,'' Mr Gray said.
``This is clearly a very complex case.
``The investigation will examine from top to toe the circumstances surrounding
this. Once it is completed, we will contact the family with our findings.''
Hamilton MP George Robertson said: ``It is a very distressing story and I'm
looking into it.''
</TEXT>
