<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#55m scheme gets another chance Sports arena back at start</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995507</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW has rejoined the race for Millenium Commission millions in the hope of
resurrecting the plan for a #55m national indoor arena at Glasgow Green.
The city, having been ruled out of the first round of projects, was put on the
so-called B list but has been encouraged by a commission invitation to resubmit
plans which concentrate on the 12,000-capacity multi-purpose national indoor
stadium and concert centre as part of a #78m East End refurbishment programme.
Glasgow, UK city of architecture in 1999, has staged an international design
competition, and from eight short-listed entries two options have been chosen:
one by Arup Associates of London, the other by an Edinburgh company, RMJM. The
pair will pitch directly against one another if and when Millenium approval is
granted.
The two designs were selected by a panel chaired by Sir Norman Foster, and
included city councillors.
``The two schemes were very different in their approach and appearance,'' said
Sir Norman. ``But both address the problems of large-scale events in terms of
people movements, servicing, and performers, with each creating an identifiable
image from a distance on the skyline.''
The Millenium Commission's verdict is expected in January and the winning arena
design would then be announced in May. Glasgow is still awaiting Millenium news
on the Hampden Project, and for a development at Pacific Quay which includes
the establishment of a Science Museum.
The indoor stadium would be built at Fleshers' Haugh, on the site of the Fifty
Pitches whose links with the past would be preserved by the establishment of a
football centre of excellence.
``A tremendous amount of time and effort has gone into our resubmitted bid for
this truly world-class arena,'' said Mr Chris Purslow, Glasgow's city
architect. ``If the bid is successful, the proposals will see the regeneration
of an important site adjacent to Glasgow Green and the provision of top-class
facilities for international events.''
It would also be used as an entertainment and concert venue and have the
facility to provide managed workspace for arts and crafts, dance, sound
studios, and community space in response to local demand.
The overall project includes a watersport centre, upgraded walking and cycle
routes, and model boating centre. There would be a play village for families,
wheels area for go-karts, bikes, and skateboards, and an indoor soft-play area.
The parks will hold horticultural displays of international quality and there
is the promise of all-year-round colour, a scented garden, and thistle maze.
There will be replanting of 80% of tree stock, tree-lined boulevards, piazzas,
and fountains.
Councillor Colin McNicol, convener of the parks and recreation committee,
described the overall project as ``the most outstanding urban parkland renewal
initiative ever undertaken in Europe''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
