<DOCNO>GH951208-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Beef courses kept on Scots school dinners</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995508</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEEF is to remain on the menu for most Scottish school dinners, despite the
current concern over BSE.
The Scottish Local Authority Caterers' Association last night dissociated
itself from the views of its English counterpart, LACA, which called for
poultry substitutes to be used for hamburgers and sausages.
SLACA chairman, Mr Munro Anderson, said although the association was aware of
public concerns over bovine spongiform encephalopathy, it had not made any
recommendations to withdraw meat or meat-related dishes from menus.
His organisation represents all 12 regional and islands councils.
``Some local authority caterers are concerned that the English view is being
attributed to Scotland as well. This is not the case,'' Mr Anderson said.
The response was welcomed by the Meat and Livestock Commission.
Its general manager in Scotland, Mr Alistair Donaldson, said principal bovine
offals from the brain, tonsils, and spine had been destroyed since 1988.
Mr Donaldson called on scientists who had expressed misgivings to bring forward
evidence to the independent committee looking at BSE.
However, Hutcheson's Grammar School in Glasgow and Daniel Stewart's and
Melville College in Edinburgh yesterday joined the list of private schools
excluding hamburgers and sausages from their menus.
Further details also emerged yesterday of investigations into false
declarations on BSE cattle.
Farmers, hauliers, and dealers have to certify that cattle for sale have been
not on premises where BSE had been reported for the previous six years.
Strathclyde region is investigating six alleged contraventions of the Trade
Descriptions Act. Lothian region's trading standards office said it was
investigating seven such cases.
</TEXT>
