<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Was Braveheart more a case of patriot games?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robbie Dinwoodie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995509</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSIDER this. If the Scots were once 90-minute patriots, in the football
analogy coined by Jim Sillars in his memorably bitter sound-bite, have they
become 210-minute patriots in the wake of the Braveheart movie?
A political concentration span the length of a Hollywood film and a level of
commitment to match, from bravehearts to fainthearts - these have been the easy
accusations about the Scottish electorate following the peaks and troughs of
SNP support in recent months. But was there ever a Mel Gibson factor in
Scottish politics?
Labour has been on more than 50% support in 11 of our 12 System Three polls
this year and only once, in October, did it drop below. Its 46% rating then
coincided with the SNP surging to the psychologically important 30% level and
suddenly, for the first time since his assumption of power, Labour leader Tony
Blair appeared vulnerable.
But did that level of support relate to SNP popularity in its own right, or was
it fuelled by a perceived dip in belief in New Labour's seemingly inevitable
path to Westminster power? It happened, after all, in the wake of a period when
the press believed Mr Blair was ``wobbling'' on Scottish devolution and his
holiday in Italy seemed to have left Labour short of its customary iron
discipline.
In other words, do voters switch support to the SNP because they believe in
independence in Europe, or do they do so at times because they lose faith in
Labour's ability to oust the Conservatives after 16 years in office?
Certainly the SNP was on a spectacular high two months ago. The talk was of an
end to the Blair honeymoon, of having the Labour leader ``in its sights'', and
a confident belief in having cranked up support to a new level. Then the
16-point gap opened up to 29 points last month, and to 36 points this week.
Having hit 57% for the third time this year - a level bettered only once in 21
years of Herald polling when it hit 58% in April 1984 - Labour now appears to
be in an unassailable position. But is this based on its Scottish performance
and the popularity of its constitutional plans, or is it because of a growing
belief that southern voters will definitely propel Tony Blair to number 10?
The SNP has in the past ridiculed this ``one last chance'' approach by habitual
Labour voters, but it is difficult to dismiss. A couple of months ago, at the
time of the 16-point gap between Labour and the SNP, chatting to a friend and
veteran trade unionist who could be considered Labour to his bootstraps, I
asked how things stood.
``If Labour doesn't win the next General Election, or if it wins and fails to
deliver the Scottish parliament in full, as promised, I will tear up my card
and join the SNP,'' he replied.
At the level of a certain kind of party activist, Labour and SNP remain
anathema to each other, even although all political logic would dictate that
the overlap in their views is extraordinary. To use the old jibe, there are
indeed some ``tartan Tories'' in the SNP, but there are also some very
conservative politicians inside the Labour Party and some ultra-Unionists,
although they are keeping relatively quiet for the time being.
The SNP's Fergus Ewing and David McCarthy would certainly bill themselves as
pro-business and they got a hard time from their party's left at annual
conference. But one-time Labour left-winger Michael Connarty recently attacked
the SNP for its policy on opposing council house sales, a press release that
brought a double-take from this observer.
Labour condemned as ``opportunism'' the SNP motion in the Commons to lower VAT
on domestic fuel earlier this year, and then moved precisely the same motion in
the House last week.
If you accept the Conservative point that both Labour and the SNP are
effectively socialist parties, then on average in our polls this year something
like 77% of those prepared to state their opinion were socialists, while the
party of government can muster just 12% and the Liberal Democrats have bumped
along at under 10%.
If the gargantuan efforts of the Scottish Secretary over the past four months
do not begin to bear fruit soon, we may be forced to conclude that they never
will.
But ordinary voters don't see things in such clear ideological terms or reflect
such simple party demarcation lines. They are resistant to being corralled into
the limited and mutually exclusive ground of manifestos.
Some vote SNP but want devolution. There are Labour supporters who want
eventual independence. There are some Conservatives who are by no means
Unionists. Most Liberal Democrats probably want and understand the concept of
federation, but their party is too often doomed by its political subtlety,
making fine points in a rough world.
The Scottish political landscape is a place where there is a desire for greater
self-determination, for an expression of Scottishness. Michael Forsyth is
trying to tap into that, but his efforts may be too little, too late.
It is interesting to ponder what might have been achieved if his initiatives
had come at the time of the original Taking Stock proposals of his predecessor.
When he picks up his broadsword and lays into the ``tartan tax'' he is trying
to chop down devolution, but his subliminal message may actually be harming the
SNP.
For their part, the nationalists do not have much room to manoeuvre. The St
Andrew's day debate forced them to restate their position on independence in
Europe, and they spent the month churning out no fewer than four major policy
documents. Whether they strike out on the high road or the low road to
independence, it becomes increasingly clear that they are not entirely masters
of their own fate.
MR Blair dominates the British political scene as a Prime Minister in waiting.
If his inner circle continues ruthlessly to crush potentially damaging policy
debate, to ditch hostages to electoral fortune, and to sit in wait to ambush
the Government at the next election, there seems to be little that any of the
other parties can do about it.
If Labour does falter in the battle for middle England, the Tories will pounce,
but in that event the likely beneficiary north of the Border seems far more
likely to be the SNP. It could be argued that what both the Tories and SNP now
need to regain the political initiative is a Labour government, but don't
expect Messrs Forsyth or Salmond to admit that in public.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
