<DOCNO>GH951208-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Appeal unlikely in paper boy case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995510</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOME Secretary Michael Howard is ``minded not'' to refer the case of the
Bridgewater Four back to Court of Appeal but no final decision has been taken,
the Home Office said last night.
It said Mr Howard had notified the solicitors of the men of his ``provisional
conclusions'' and they now had opportunity to respond.
Michael Hickey, 33, Vincent Hickey, 41, and James Robinson, 61, have protested
their innocence since they were convicted in February 1979 of murdering
newspaper delivery boy Carl Bridgewater.
Carl, 13, was shot dead when he interrupted a burglary at Yew Tree Farm, near
Stourbridge, West Midlands, in 1978.
The confession of the fourth accused, Patrick Molloy, who was convicted of
manslaughter, was crucial to the convictions.
Molloy died in 1981, claiming he had been forced into making the confession.
The men's case was previously referred back to the Court of Appeal in 1987. The
court dismissed the appeal in March 1989.
A further request for another referral was rejected by the then Home Secretary,
Mr Kenneth Clarke, in February 1993. Mr Clarke said he had no doubts that the
convictions were safe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Crown criticised for errors in appeal against sentence</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995511</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE judges have severely criticised the Crown for placing inaccurate and
misleading information before them in support of a plea that a one-year
sentence imposed on a sex offender was too lenient.
The Advocate-depute who appeared at the Court of Criminal Appeal apologised for
the wrong information which had been placed before it by the Crown.
Lord Ross, the Lord Justice Clerk, stated that the mistakes were highly
regrettable.
He added: ``Whilst the court is obviously prepared to accept the apologies
offered by the Advocate-depute, it is to be hoped that the court is never asked
again by the Lord Advocate to consider a note of appeal at his instance which
is so inaccurate and misleading.''
The Crown appealed against three concurrent one-year sentences imposed by Lord
Morison on Alexander Ross, 39, who was found guilty after trial at the High
Court in Aberdeen on three charges of lewd and indecent behaviour towards two
girls aged four and six.
Ross, from Alness in Easter Ross, also had been charged with rape but that
charge was withdrawn by the Crown without any evidence being led.
The Lord Advocate claimed the one-year sentence was unduly lenient having
regard to the grossly indecent nature of the sexual abuse and the age of the
victims.
In his report to the appeal court, Lord Morison pointed out that the Crown's
grounds of appeal appeared to be based on the mistaken belief that three, not
two victims, had been involved and that there had been continuous and grossly
indecent abuse for 13 years, which was also untrue.
Lord Morison added: ``I consider it regrettable that Ross, who has been
subjected to the ordeal of a charge of rape in support of which the Crown led
no evidence, should now be subjected to a further period of uncertainty arising
from an appeal which appears to me to be based on an erroneous view of the
offences for which he was sentenced.''
The Lord Justice Clerk said Lord Morison had obviously attached considerable
weight to the fact that the accused had been subjected to the ordeal of a rape
charge in support of which no evidence had been led.
When Ross had been fully committed for trial in June 1994, the Crown petition
made no reference to rape and the first time he became aware that rape was
being alleged was when the indictment was served on him last May.
Statements had then been taken from both the alleged victim and her mother and
they had said nothing to support a charge of rape. A medical examination of the
child also showed nothing untoward.
Lord Ross added: ``In our opinion, when considering sentence in this case, the
trial judge was fully entitled to have regard to the fact that Ross had for a
time faced a very serious charge of raping a young child in respect of which
the Crown led no evidence at all.''
Looking at the indecency offences, the appeal court took the view that the
concurrent one-year sentences could not be described as unduly lenient.
The trial judge himself had observed that it might well have been suggested
that he should have made one of the sentences consecutive but the Lord Advocate
had not suggested that Lord Morison was wrong to make all the sentences
concurrent.
The appeal court refused the Crown appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dividend accelerates</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995512</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Chrysler Corporation, under pressure from billionaire Kirk Kerkorian to
share more of its cash with shareholders, said yesterday it had approved its
fifth dividend increase in two years.
Chrysler said its directors, at their regular monthly meeting, raised the
quarterly common stock dividend by 20% to 60 cents a share, up from 50 cents.
It is payable on January 12 of next year, to shareholders of record on December
15.
Chairman Robert Eaton also said the company had completed the first $1000m
share repurchase programme announced in December 1994 and was buying shares
under the second $1000m programme announced in September this year.
It expected to complete the second repurchase programme, subject to market
conditions, by the end of 1996.
Chrysler has increased its quarterly dividend by 300% from 15 cents a share in
December 1993. During 1995, Chrysler has returned about $1700m to shareholders
in higher dividends and share buy-backs.
``Being able to sustain our dividend throughout a business cycle is one of the
board's key decision factors in determining when an increase is merited and as
we look ahead, we feel this payout rate meets those criteria,'' Mr Eaton said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two held in drugs raid</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995513</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO 27-year-old men were detained by Strathclyde Police in the Anniesland area
of Glasgow following a major drugs operation yesterday.
Police recovered drugs with an estimated street value of #800,000 - about 100
kilos of cannabis and four kilos of a white powder thought to be amphetamine or
cocaine.
Meanwhile, Chief Constable Leslie Sharp is expected to give his verdict on the
force's 90-day Operation Eagle anti-drugs campaign at a Strathclyde Police
seminar in Glasgow today.
The campaign has seen a total of 6000 people arrested and more than 30,000
schoolchildren given anti-drugs awareness talks in an effort to stamp out the
drug trade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>GUS beats forecast with #237m profit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995514</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE RUN-UP to Christmas is the most important trading period for retailers, but
the signs are that Christmas cheer is slow in coming to the High Street with
consumers still careful with their spending.
This, coupled with rising raw material costs and the low level of inflation,
make it difficult for retailers to grow their profits significantly.
However, Great Universal Stores, the catalogue shopping, stores and finance
group, beat City expectations at the interim stage, with profits up 4.7% to
#237.5m. Sales and profits advanced in all its geographic territories. Despite
the encouraging performance, the group said that, given the volatile trading
background, ``the challenges ahead should not be underestimated''.
Within the operating divisions, the mail order shopping business suffered from
lower orders as a result of the very hot summer. Profits dipped by #2.8m to
#93.6m. New interactive methods of shopping are being monitored and tested.
Burberrys and Scotch House made higher profits in all its sectors and recorded
increased productivity in its products and manufacturing division following new
investment. Profit rose from #21.2m to #26.9m on sales up 21%.
The collection of golf wear has been well received and additional lines are to
be added. This high growth luxury consumer brand is viewed in the City as a
significant source of value for the group.
Overseas retailing also performed strongly, with improved sales and profits.
Elsewhere, property rental income rose by 6% to #31.5m. The portfolio consists
of 1065 properties, of which 80% are occupied by the retail trade, including
three shopping centres comprising 173 units. The occupancy level remains high
at 98.5%.
Profits from financial activities and information services grew by just under
#4m to #66.5m.
Lower interest receivable of #43.8m versus #46.3m, reflects the payment in
March of a special dividend of #301.7m. The group's balance sheet remains very
strong with a virtually ungeared balance sheet. There was positive underlying
cash flow from trading activities.
The sleepy secretive image of GUS could be changed in the not too distant
future. Lord Wolfson of Sunningdale is swapping his executive chairmanship of
Next for that of GUS, of which he is currently a non-executive director, after
the retirement of Lord Wolfson of Marylebone next September.
News of the move prompted speculation among some City analysts of a possible
future link between GUS and Next which has tended to outperform almost all its
retail rivals in recent years. In addition to its High Street outlets, Next
operates a very successful mail order business and has a younger more affluent
customer profile than GUS home shopping business.
GUS shares responded to the results and succession statement by jumping 18p to
632p after touching 648!sp earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Allied Irish pays #101m for Govett Group</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995515</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANOTHER shake-up in the world of fund management took place yesterday when
Allied Irish Bank bought the John Govett Group for #101m cash from the
long-established Govett &amp; Company.
They had tried to buy the Duff &amp; Phelps investment management business in the
US but ran into complex legal difficulties and counter claims. That depressed
the Govett share price and it has now decided that its activities in this
sphere would be better served under new ownership.
AIB is effectively buying 75% of the newly formed John Govett Holdings, with
management having 20% and Govett Oriental Investment Trust having the remaining
5%.
Part of the problem in selling off the division was how to retain the existing
management through incentives. The one-fifth stake should satisfy that
requirement.
John Govett manages #3000m of funds and has an outstanding record in the
emerging markets of the Far East. AIB is doing the deal very cheaply, paying
only 3.7% of funds under management and on a price earnings ratio of 10.7. That
is much less than Commerzbank paid for Jupiter Tyndall.
The rump of Govett, which is almost entirely US oriented, will continue under
the name of London Pacific Group, with #2900m of funds under management. Its
shares bounced 22p off the year's low to close at 242p, compared with a 1995
high of 377p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hargreaves wins award</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995516</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALISON HARGREAVES yesterday won a posthumous award from Cosmopolitan magazine
and American Express. The climber, from Belper, Derbyshire, died on K2 in the
Himalayas last summer after becoming the first woman to climb Everest
unsupported without additional oxygen.
Overall winner of the Achievements Awards was barrister Dinah Rose, who
represented police officer Alison Halford in her discrimination case against
the Chief Constable of Merseyside, and fought for women in the armed services
who were dismissed for becoming pregnant.
The awards recognise outstanding achievements by women under 35. Among other
winners were Glasgow saxophonist Gail McArthur in the performing arts category,
and Lyn McNicol, managing director and editor of Bigwig Publications, Glasgow,
for media.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Officer fined for indecent exposure</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995517</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POLICEMAN was fined #750 yesterday for behaving indecently in front of school
children aged between seven and 11.
Perth Sheriff Court heard that Constable Brian Murphy, 24, of Tayside Police,
posed on his doorstep nude and sometimes in bra and panties.
In evidence, Murphy admitted that he twice ``flashed'' at his then live-in
fiancee as she left the house in the morning. He denied targeting children.
Rejecting his evidence, Sheriff John McInnes found him guilty of indecently
exposing himself on various occasions last April and May as well as causing
fear and alarm and disturbing the peace by appearing in women's underclothes
during the same period.
Sheriff McInnes said the children who gave evidence - mainly girls - were
credible witnesses.
Allowing Murphy two months to pay the fine, the sheriff said he accepted that
any lasting harm to the children ``is probably likely to be slight, if that''.
Murphy, previously an army bandsman, joined the police three years ago and had
been at Pitlochry since November of last year.
He was on counter duty at Pitlochry police station when a mother walked in to
report that her two daughters had seen a man behaving indecently outside a
house.
Murphy retorted: ``That's my house. It cannot be.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Johnston cleared to buy Linney</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995518</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHNSTON Press yesterday received Government clearance to buy the W&amp;J Linney
group of local newspapers in the Midlands.
The Department of Trade and Industry (DTI) said the Edinburgh-based newspaper
group could go ahead with the #20m purchase. Linney owns 11 titles in the
Mansfield and Worksop areas of Nottinghamshire and Derbyshire. Nine are free
publications and two are paid for.
The DTI was able to nod through the acquisition without a reference to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission because the newspapers concerned have a daily
paid-for circulation of less that 50,000.
Johnston Press, which owns 81 other local publications, mostly in Yorkshire and
Derbyshire, agreed to purchase the Linney group on November 13.
n Ashanti, the mining group split off from Lonrho, yesterday made an #80m
agreed takeover bid for Cluff Resources. After the deal, worth 105p a share,
Ashanti claimed it would be the biggest gold mining and exploration group in
Africa below the Sahara. Ashanti launched the bid after buying a 26.6% stake in
Cluff from Hutchison Whampoa at 105p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NEWS DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995519</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Immigrants in
lorry held
A LORRY driver was arrested yesterday when Customs officers in Dover found 25
illegal immigrants in his vehicle which had travelled from Calais.
The 24 men of Turkish and Chinese origin and one Chinese woman were in a
specially built compartment in a hired 7.5-tonne Mercedes.
Mirren in ad
PRIME Suspect star Helen Mirren has signed a #100,000-plus deal for her first
television ad, for Virgin Atlantic airline.
Guilty plea
A BOY of 14 yesterday admitted the manslaughter of a schoolmate at his trial at
Cardiff Crown Court. Ashley Stevens, 14, died four days after the attack in
May. Sentencing has been adjourned for a week.
Crime inquiry
AN inquiry is under way into allegations that sensitive information was leaked
from the National Criminal Intelligence Service.
Consumer revival
RETAIL sales volumes last month rose by the biggest amount since spring,
according to an industry survey.
Cliffhanger
CORONATION Street celebrates 35 years tonight with an hour-long episode
expected to draw a huge audience. Strict secrecy surrounded filming of three
alternative endings to the cliffhanger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Matron claims unfair dismissal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995520</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORMER matron of a nursing home which was at the centre of allegations
concerning mistreatment of patients has lodged a claim for unfair dismissal.
Mrs Margaret Walker, of Stonedyke Crescent, Carluke, claims she was dismissed
unfairly from Orchard House Nursing Home in Crossford, Lanarkshire. Her claim
is expected to be heard by a Glasgow tribunal in January.
The home was the subject of an investigation by Lanarkshire Health Board
earlier this year which made certain recommendations about its future running.
Mrs Walker was matron at the home, owned by Raymond and Margaret Baigent, for
more than six years.
A television documentary earlier this year claimed to expose controversial
standards of care for the elderly.
Last year, nurse Adele Bryson took her constructive dismissal claim against the
home to a tribunal. She resigned, claiming her authority had been undermined,
when Mrs Walker ordered staff to clean a patient's room.
However, the tribunal ruled she had no grounds to consider herself unfairly
dismissed as she was involving herself in matters which were nothing to do with
her.
At the tribunal, Ms Bryson claimed no action was taken when she alleged a
resident had been sexually harassed by a male employee and on another occasion
when a nurse allegedly hit a patient.
She also claimed that staff had to provide toiletries for residents.
Mrs Walker's unfair dismissal claim is scheduled to be heard on January 11 and
12.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Growth is on menu</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995521</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE #527m takeover by Greenalls of Boddington has placed the pubs to hotels
group in an ideal position for future growth, said chairman and chief executive
Andrew Thomas.
He added that the Boddingtons purchase was a major step in the evolution of
Greenalls, which now runs the UK's biggest independent pub chain.
Shares in the Warrington based group fell 6p to 534p despite pre-tax profits
rising from #74.8 to #101m in line with City expectations. The total dividend
payout goes up from 13.1p to 14.2p.
Boddingtons brought in not only 458 good quality pubs, also leisure hotels and
the UK's biggest independent drinks wholesale business.
A close review of its pubs operations had led the group to sell 69 pubs as well
as a number of other properties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Risk-free society pure pie in the sky</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Julie Davidson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995522</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE other evening I heard a woman make an astonishing statement on the Nine o'
Clock News. She has decided to keep her children off school because somewhere
in her neighbourhood (although not in the school) there has been a meningitis
death. ``It was one death too many,'' said this mother, slick with the sound
bite which even the most amateur television commentator has learned to perfect.
``It should never have happened.''
It should never have happened: the meningitis virus, its sometimes fatal
consequences, the outrageous anarchy of infectious disease should never have
happened. The authorities should never have let it happen. Someone is to blame.
In that woman's petulant voice I heard the ultimate surrender to the dependency
culture.
Cradle-to-grave care is the least of our expectations. What we demand, these
days, is a risk-free environment and we expect ``the authorities'' to provide
it. The authorities, meantime, are hoist with their own petard.
In their diverse political, bureaucratic, and scientific manifestations they
are the authors of a mad manifesto which offers to protect us from everything.
They have encouraged the giddy idea that none of life's natural hazards can be
left to chance. They have aspired to be masters of an imperfect universe and
the consequences of their prophylactic zeal crosses the spectrum from the
persecution of Humphrey Errington to the panic over meat pies and hamburgers.
Once, the task of public health officials was to introduce the standards of
good housewifery to the catering and food production industries. Today they
bring the criteria of the hypochondriac, whose ability to assess risk is
crippled by neurosis. From the necessary introduction of simple, sensible
directives on health, hygiene, and safety we have reached a stage where
environmental health officers prohibit restaurateurs from serving soft-boiled
eggs without first warning customers they risk salmonella poisoning.
This is the mindset which has almost ruined Humphrey Errington, who was able to
show, with the help of a gifted legal team and some disinterested expert
evidence, that the type of listeria found in batches of Lanark Blue is very
rarely associated with disease. The bug-hunters of Clydesdale District Council
seem to have been hunting the wrong bug, which didn't stop them pursuing it, in
the view of the sheriff who found the cheese innocent, in a ``combative and
confrontational manner''.
But the bug-hunters are more messenger than mastermind and the messengers
aren't the only ones who should be shot. Media melodrama, not new evidence, has
fed the latest frenzy over beef, BSE, and the food chain. Against Government
advice schools and caterering groups have been stampeded into eliminating an
important source of protein and minerals from their menus, some of which may be
nutritionally defective at the best of times.
I'm the last person in the world to place childlike trust in the soundness of
government advice. I believe, too, that there are good reasons for avoiding
processed pies, sausages, and beefburgers of the mass-produced supermarket
variety. They don't taste nice and they're full of chemicals.
But I have some sympathy for the Government's no-win position on BSE. Its
scientists can't prove a negative; they can't prove that there is no
transmitted link between mad cow disease and its neurologically devastating
human version, any more than they can prove, at the moment, that there is one.
When you can't prove a negative you can't slap a cast-iron guarantee on the
rumps of the nation's cattle and pronounce beef safe. You can only affirm your
belief that it's safe, and that hint of qualification is enough to feed the
media appetite for sensation and the public appetite for alarm.
Their latest bout of shared hysteria began to mount when the news broke that
four cattle farmers had died of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease. World in Action
simmered the doubts and don't-knows of the scientific community, and the Sunday
Times stirred this stew of speculative reporting by taking the orders of a
random bunch of scientists, half of whom had gone off meat products.
One or two journalists did try to balance this diet of conjecture with some
facts. In the Times, Simon Jenkins pointed out that in the same year that four
farmers died of CJD 46 non-farmers also died of the disease, and some of them
were vegetarian; that European countries which have had no BSE-infected cattle
have recorded just as many cases of CJD as Britain; and that most experts
accept that the incidence of CJD has been more or less constant for years.
But more important than the facts, which are admittedly incomplete, is the
perception. Here we detect the importunacy, the sheer bloody impertinence of
another risk which has had the temerity to defile the sterile landscape of our
risk-free environment.
Public-health policies, scientific and medical advances have had unaccountable
benefits. Generations of parents live free of nightmares which haunted their
own parents. Our mistake is to imagine that the elimination of some diseases
leads progressively to the elimination of all; the culture of viruses and
bacteria is every bit as robust, inventive, and adaptable as our own.
But the more we believe in the pristine possibility of a risk-free environment
the more we surrender our own capacity for assessing risk; and the more we look
for someone to point the finger at and say, ``It shouldn't have happened.''
There is, surely, a middle ground to be found between the passive dependants on
Huxley's brave new world and the defiant Savage, who chose the right to be
unhappy over the right to be comfortable - who claimed God, poetry, danger,
freedom, goodness, and sin along with ``the right to catch typhoid''.
Until we have more information about BSE I've found the middle ground in the
premises of my butcher, who knows the provenance of all his beef and makes his
own succulent Cambridge sausages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jack McLean</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995523</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TELL me about virtual reality, because I don't understand anything about it at
all. A couple of years back Lesley Riddoch of the BBC, and now back there,
joined a Scottish newspaper. A fortnight before she went to that place in North
Bridge, Edinburgh, she wrote for this blatt and claimed that she had no belief
in any sort of new technology and in fact composed whatever she did on an old
stand-up typewriter. Once pitched into the glittering full-time world of print
journalism she learned new technology in seconds, the way one does when you get
to be a deputy executive editor or whatever title takes a newspaper's fancy.
It is then, with an array of Jean Muir dresses and word-processing terminals,
that one gets to grasp the significance of how useful new technology is,
especially the usefulness of a dashed good salary. That is a reality, the
salary. At the Scotsman, Lesley's situation turned out to be merely virtual and
she ended up leaving. For the best bit about virtual reality is that it isn't
reality at all. It is nearly reality. It is almost reality. It could just be
reality. But it isn't reality.
The truly wonderful thing about all technology is when it works and is useful,
like the wheel, or the spinning jenny, or the steam engine. When it makes
changes, just for the better like. Forty years ago, when I was a boy of 12, I
heard all about the new things which could only create misery such as
unemployment throughout the world. We had visionaries then too. Later, in the
1960s, Harold Wilson went on about the new order of things. Anthony Wedgwood
Benn went on so much about the white-hot heat of technology that he burnt
himself out with the white-hot heat of it.
But today we have even more advances on Benn. A Mr Leeson was so hellbent on
virtual reality in Singapore that his reality cost his bank millions. For that
is the problem with virtual reality, isn't it? That it isn't virtual at all. It
is a chimera. In fact, to use rather a rude word, virtual reality is nothing
other, really, than something like a wank: it is not the real thing at all,
though it might do at a pinch.
I am sorry - no I'm not - about a rude word if readers object to it. Frankly
most sensible people would object to the deleterious results of new technology
in the past century or so since the Industrial Revolution and particularly in
the past decade or so, than would object to the vernacular for onanism.
Virtual reality, in the guise of television for instance, has had the effect of
an especially brutal reality. Fred West was especially addicted to virtual
anything except decency. That collection of royal strumpets are horribly fond
of such realities as a quarter of a million quids worth of ice and the
virtualness of drooping and coy glances to cameras while visiting the realities
of dying people. If anybody out there is barking enough to give any money at
all to a Princess of Wales Hospice when the adultress who allows the charity
concerned to bear her name spends more on her pants than it costs to keep an
old and dying person for a week, then you have only virtual reality to blame.
And just this week we discover that calculators are to be banned for
11-year-olds in their maths exams because the aids weren't good for them. In
fact they allowed the young persons to know nothing and learn less. Because it
was virtual reality and its very concept. Technology can do it all for you and
you don't have to think about it, old son. As it happens, calculators could
very well have helped me to pass my arithmetic tests. What they couldn't have
done was help me at all to count, which rather, well, counts. Spell-checks in
computers can tell you how to spell words properly but they can't tell you why
they are spelled so.
There is a band called Boys Own, from Ireland, who have a record out now, a
repro of the old Cat Stevens's song Mathew and Son. I seem to remember that the
B-side was a major smash and was called Moonshadow. Wet, Wet, Wet are another
musical combo. They brought out an old Troggs number. Twenty years back there
was a group called Mud which recorded a wheen of Buddy Holly songs. None of the
foregoing was as good as the original.
A wee while back Kirsty McColl recorded a Kinks song, Days. She was great at
it. I will tell you why. She was singing with reality, and nothing bloody
virtual about it. Kirsty is an accomplished singer-songwriter who has all the
reality of talent and a background (her dad was, of course, Ewan McColl, the
folk-singer), and her talent is virtue and not virtual. Sounds a bit
old-fashioned that. Right.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Strenuous efforts are being made to secure overseas contracts and open up more markets GEC's shares push up on results</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995524</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RETAILERS last month saw the largest rise in the volume of sales since April,
according to the CBI's Distributive Trades Survey.
The CBI said the underlying three-month trend suggested that sales volumes
remained on an upward path. But shopkeepers still regarded the level of sales
as below average for the time of year, though to their least extent for six
months.
``As we enter the critical pre-Christmas period, there are genuine signs of a
turn-round in retailers' fortunes,'' said Alastair Eperon, chairman of the CBI
Distributive Trades Survey Panel.
The survey follows data showing a near 13% increase in new car sales in
November and figures earlier in the week suggesting that the housing market may
be poised to recover after the fourth consecutive monthly rise in prices.
It is likely to be viewed in the City as weakening the argument for an early
interest rate cut to boost growth.
However, Mr Eperon considered the absence of a cut would restrict the recovery.
He said: ``Unless there is a cut in interest rates, we won't see a revival in
consumer confidence that the Chancellor and everyone is looking for.''
Ideally retailers would like a cut following the regular monthly meeting of the
Chancellor and the Bank of England Governor next Wednesday, as this would be in
time for the Christmas sales rush.
But Governor Eddie George is likely call for caution, pointing to the CBI
survey finding that price increases last month were the highest since May 1993,
with the trend expected to continue in December.
Mr Eperon said that intense competition would limit the extent of price rises
for shoppers.
The survey showed that most retailing sectors experienced some growth in sales
compared with a year ago.
The largest increases came in booksellers and stationers followed by grocers
and clothing retailers, while chemists, confectioners, furniture and carpet
stores saw the largest reductions in sales growth. Only specialist food
retailers saw an actual reduction in sales.
According to the survey, 50% of retailers reported that sales were up last
month compared with November 1994 while 27% said they were down.
INTERIM results from GEC pushed the shares up 12.5p to 314p, despite being
towards the lower end of expectations. This was because extra development costs
had been charged to defence profits.
Profits were 6% higher at #402m in the six months to September, helped by a
contribution from VSEL and a #13m rise in interest income to #83m. The interim
dividend is raised 5% to 3.1p.
Group net cash fell by #223m to #1200m, reflecting the VSEL acquisition. Cash
held in joint-ventures was also lower, down #194m to #1280m.
Electronic systems, the defence division which includes the key GEC-Marconi
business, was only marginally ahead at #80m, reflecting the development
provisions.
The defence interests have been increased by VSEL, which added a
submarine-building facility to the existing Yarrow yard, where heavy
redundancies are threatened. Finance director David Newlands said that both
yards needed new customers to flesh out current and expected orders.
The recent order for Yarrow's Clyde yard of three offshore patrol vessels from
Brunei had helped and he added: ``There are several orders in the UK we hope to
win, but we have to supplement these with exports.''
VSEL and other acquisitions boosted the division's order book by 22% to #6090m.
The development provisions relate to a number of large defence contracts on
which negotiations have yet to be concluded. Analysts believe the provisions
may be recouped in the contract terms.
The contribution from the GEC-Alsthom power systems operation dipped slightly
to #76m as margins were affected by competition. Its order book also fell a
little. However, group orders rose 15% to #13.8bn.
Telecommunications profits were ahead at #62m against #54m and office equipment
and printing was up sharply to #22m.
GEC points out that it is making strenuous efforts to win more business
overseas and to open up new markets for its products. Over 70% of sales are
outside the UK and exports from the UK amount to 17% of turnover, which was
only marginally up on balance at #4886m. But the UK remains the most important
profit centre, generating almost half total profits.
The group sees good opportunities in the Middle East and the fast-growing
Asia-Pacific region. It is one of the players in Britain's export successes in
the region where the UK has a trade surplus.
``The South-east Asian markets are the ones that are strong and we are still
putting a tremendous amount of effort in there,'' said Mr Newlands.
</TEXT>
