<HEADLINE>Research into food retailing loses its sparkle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Tom Shields</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974995525</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT must be the chill winds of puritanism sweeping through the House of Commons
now that Lord Nolan and his committee have decreed strict rules on what our MPs
may or may not accept in the course of their duties.
Safeway, the supermarket people, had a festive reception for MPs who turned up,
as they do, to find out how things are going in the world of food retailing. As
they left, after their research into the above-mentioned subject, each MP was
offered a Safeway goodie bag.
In previous years this bag contained a substantial selection of Safeway's
finest produce. (The Safeway cava Spanish sparkling wine, we notice by the way,
is on offer again this year at the astonishingly attractive price of #3.99 a
bottle. We mention this not to tout for free samples but as a service to
readers.)
But this year it was a poor harvest for the MPs. The bag contained nothing more
than a tin of baked beans, Safeway's own brand.
q ON the same subject, we notice Asda is offering a boxed set of matched tie
and boxer shorts. Look out, girls, for a certain pretty pathetic chat-up line
at the office party.
State of emergency
OUR heart goes out to the folk of the South of England as they try to cope with
a bit of snow. It is obviously emergency stations - the London Evening Standard
reported ``snowdrifts three inches deep''. Or as the Diary's London office
tells us: ``We're heel-deep in snow but we hope to get by without calling out
the Hampstead mountain rescue team.''
Foreign accent
TALES from the Foreign Office: The scene is a church in Vienna (yes, Austria -
The Herald Diary spans the globe) where the British ambassador is visiting a
church bazaar. The ambassador overhears an ex-pat Brit holding a conversation
and joins in with the words: ``I didn't know you spoke Hungarian.'' The ex-pat
wasn't. He is Welsh and was speaking English. In a Welsh accent, as the Welsh
do. We tell you this only because it speaks volumes about his knowledge of both
the country next to Austria and the country next to England.
Mad Max
THE Times obituary of American sodjer General Maxwell Thurman tells us he was
known as Mad Max and his ``style of command could be aggressive in the
extreme''. He was responsible, although not personally, for the deaths of
thousands of Panamanians when he was sent in to sort out that chap Noriega. The
obit ends ``Maxwell Thurman leaves no survivors''. You bet.
Pilgrims' progress
THE queue of supernumerary Wise Men lengthens outside the stable at Bethlehem.
To explain, we asked readers as part of their Christmas homework to nominate
people in the public eye to join the three kings in their homage to the baby
Jesus and to suggest what gift they might bring.
In return we offered gifts of bottles of Langs Supreme whisky and the Langs
first-footing kit. The kit consists of a miniature, a daud of shortbread, a
lump of coal, a pinch of salt, and the words of Auld Lang Syne - in short
everything you need fora perfect Hogmanay except a phone message to say your
in-laws' car has broken down and they can't make it to your New Year party.
John Brown of East Kilbride nominates the Rev Ian Paisley who would bring a
mobile phone with free connection to the Orange network. Billy Nimmo of
Stewarton thinks that Mystic Meg could arrive bearing a lottery ticket and
offering to read the newborn's star signs.
Bill Hunter of Uddingston thinks that the Duchess of York might turn up. She
wouldn't bring a gift but would offer the services of her lady-in-waiting, Jane
Dunne-Butler, to keep an eye on the gold, frankincense and myrrh.
Michael Bruce of Millbrix Avenue in Glasgow says that no pilgrimmage to the
stable would be the same without Jim McLean of Dundee United, bearing an S form
for the lad to sign. Mr McLean would beat Rangers to this promising signing
because the Ibrox scout was too busy asking Joseph what school he had the boy
down for.
Swan song
BEING such a jolly lot, Strathclyde region councillors are wont to get together
around Christmas time and have a bit of a sing-along. Some of us thought that
they did this all year the round, but never mind.
Strathclyde's tribunes will gather for their last-ever Christmas sing-along at
the end of this month and it is a fund-raiser for charity. And which good cause
has been chosen by the regional councillors who will suffer feelings of loss
when Strathclyde closes in April? The Cruse Bereavement Counselling Group.
Ys decision
FOR those of you whose imagination on the Christmas-present front is limited,
can we suggest you buy a loved one a pair of underpants or a vest. The
difference is that these particular items are very artistic. (Not that the St
Michael variety aren't, to let you understand.)
They are to be found framed at the Christmas exhibition at the Glasgow Print
Studio. They are the work of one Morna Simpson who specialises in multi-media
art which can consist of a bit of painting, sculpture, and a bit of fabric.
Morna's multi-media underwear comes in a touch more expensive than M&amp;S at #170
each for the semmit and drawers.
</TEXT>
