<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The eternal light of Ol' Blue Eyes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Douglas Thompson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995526</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN THE beginning there was the life. Now, the marketing. Sinatra at 80 is not
just a fine excuse for a lavish worldwide birthday party but for looking back -
His Way - through a library of books and compilations of his work. It involves
fans in a massive investment of time and money.
Just one collection, the extraordinary Frank Sinatra: The Complete Reprise
Studio Recordings, requires 24-hours non-stop to listen to it all. The
suggested retail price is $499. Overflowing with 450 songs the set is the most
lavish and revealing of all the albums to be released to celebrate Tuesday's
landmark birthday.
It is a mark of the devotion of Sinatra fans that such an expensive item -
certainly for most Christmas stockings - is selling briskly in America. Then
again, Sinatra is the most American of creations. Where else could that skinny
kid from Hoboken, New Jersey, go on to be the most acclaimed singer ever in pop
music? He became the consummate balladeer, saloon singer and big band vocalist
who dazzled with the sophistication of his phrasing but still gave intimacy and
warmth to his music. There were highs and lows but Sinatra was always Sinatra.
Mix in the rainbow of rumours, every one more colourful than the next, of a
horse's head in a movie producer's bed (supposedly to win his Oscar winning
role as Maggio in From Here to Eternity) and Mafia connections, of booze and
broads and feuds, of a Runyonesque life with sharp edges, and we get some
understanding of why Sinatra, at 80, has caused such a fanfare.
How, you wonder, did he get this far after all the years of indulgence but, of
course, that's all part of the legend of Ol' Blue Eyes.
His eldest daughter Nancy is now 55 and her book Frank Sinatra, An American
Legend (Virgin Books, #25) is structured around a couple of decades of talking
to her father and compiling a unique set of photographs. Of his three children
(Frank Junior is 51, Tina 47) she is the closest - literally.
They live less than a mile from each other in Beverly Hills and talk almost
every day. Sinatra has not given an interview in 20 years. As I recall it was
to a writer from Esquire magazine. The interview was to take place before a
Sinatra concert in California. The Esquire man arrived early for his meeting.
Even the public relations people had public relations people. Then, the great
man strolled in and the interview began with Sinatra smiling and saying: ``Hey,
buddy, nice to see you.'' That's also how it ended.
So, to describe Nancy Sinatra as her father's mouthpiece is accurate. He has
never confronted the allegations including Mob links and cruelty to women in
Kitty Kelley's 1986 best-selling attack His Way. He tried to stop publication
but that only added to the notoriety and put on sales.
His daughter sees her book as having ``taken up the gauntlet''. She says her
father who in recent public appearances has seemed confused and lost is pleased
that she is fighting in his corner.
``I wanted to make a straight record, tell the truth about my father's life. I
know he's been aching to do it but to get into a pissing contest with that
woman would have just sold more books and wouldn't accomplish anything. There
isn't anything in my book that isn't true. If I can't prove it I take it out.
If I just print the fluffy stuff, the benefits, the times he helped people's
suffering, it would be a whitewash, and what would be the point of that?''
So she confronts the Mafia and the misogyny. Of course, her father worked for
gangsters in nightclubs and Las Vegas - as did every other entertainer. Women?
She doesn't like the word ``womaniser'' but admits it fits. Kitty Kelley's
collection of half a century of Sinatra stories she dismisses giving as an
example: ``There's a story about my father being sued for breach of promise in
the early days yet nobody ever mentions that the woman turned out to have been
already married. What upsets me about these stories is once they are out there
they get endlessly repeated.''
Despite this if you turn to books by others, most recently Shirley MacLaine's
Thank Your Lucky Stars, you get a picture of Sinatra as a bully, of a man who
liked to hang out with mobsters and who, latterly, would enjoy to drink
expensive wine and then harangue the hoodlums at his table. Nancy Sinatra's
truth does not have to be questioned - just the perception of it.
It's a good, intriguing catalogue - a historical item for Sinatra devotees - of
the life and times of Sinatra. You just feel his FBI files - started in 1941 by
J Edgar Hoover who believed Ol' Blue Eyes was a Red, a Communist - would be
even more intriguing.
Nancy Sinatra says she's seen the files: ``They're just allegations that prove
nothing.'' One allegation was that he acted as a ``bagman'' delivering a
suitcase of money to Mafia kingpin ``Lucky'' Luciano in Havana.
That was yesterday. Today Nancy Sinatra says her father still misses
performing. ``He is still physically strong enough to do it. His health is
quite good. He does have this problem with a pinched nerve in his neck which
affects his facial expression. A couple of times he has been photographed in
that kind of pain which is unfortunate.''
He still enjoys a drink but now it's a cocktail before dinner that usually is
never finished. He does get through his glass of vintage red wine with the
meal. He gave up smoking 10 years ago but is back on the Camels again. ``I'm
nearly 80, so what the hell?'' his daughter quotes him but adds: ``He takes a
couple of puffs outside, never inside the house, and I wonder if he really
enjoys it.''
Surprisingly, she says her father is not as rich as we might think. ``He's
given most of it away over the years. I'm not a princess and I'm not an
heiress. He didn't set up trust funds for my brother, sister and me. He figured
we'd handle things on our own and instead gave it to people who were in need of
it. He took very good care of my mother always, still does.''
She says she cried for a week when her father married Barbara Marx in 1976. She
wanted him to remarry her mother Nancy. ``I will always wish that my parents
had remarried. It was more than a child's wild fantasy. At one time it became a
probability because they were spending a lot of time together just prior to
Barbara and Dad becoming engaged.''
Barbara Marx, now 65, turned out to be the longest serving wife of the man so
classically dubbed St Francis of Assisi with a shoulder holster. The
entertainer who is part myth, monster and marvel now suffers from
microangiopathy of the brain which springs sudden attacks of dizziness,
confusion and often long periods of memory loss. His wife has supported him
through it.
He can still be bad mannered, bad tempered and bad news but those around the
self-styled ``saloon singer'' believe he should put his feet up. Nancy and Tina
- who produced a memorable television biography of her father - sincerely want
him to stop appearing in public.
Today's image is of a man who has lost it. He's collapsed on stage, he's
forgotten the lines of some of his most famous songs. His daughters do not wish
him to continue to be a mumbling embarrassment.
They feel his fans want to remember him as the legend who went from bobbysoxers
to broads, who met The Mob and The Kennedys, who fought feuds, enjoyed insults
and indulged in boozy, brawling behaviour. As the man who when he played Las
Vegas the neon billboards just proclaimed ``He's Here''. For gamblers the
Nevada town was where luck and Sinatra competed for absolute deity.
``Frank is an old man now and most of the people around him are concerned about
his health,'' said a close associate before adding: ``Barbara felt that having
engagements and recordings kept him active - gave him something to get out of
bed for. But now he's 80 - and showing it - they just want him happy and
content.''
Family friends and associates paint a curious picture of Sinatra today. ``He's
mellowed,'' says one. That is countered by another: ``He's a real mean
bastard.'' And you must recall that in the swinging days some of his close
friends called him The Monster.
Sinatra has always been acutely aware of his mortality. Many of his family from
his mother Dolly to friends like Sammy Davis Junior, Peter Lawford, songwriters
Sammy Cahn and Jimmy Van Huesen with whom he used to have regular Monday night
poker games, and Jackie Kennedy Onassis whom he wanted to marry have gone. When
he gave charity lectures his closing line was always: ``I hope you all live to
be 400-years-old and the last voice you hear is mine.''
``Frank is now obsessed with dying - with it all ending,'' I was told by a
Sinatra watcher. Sinatra himself tells Nancy in her book: ``You gotta love
living, baby. Dying's a pain in the arse.''
Before he sold up in Palm Springs estate he kept a lighted Christmas tree at
the front of what he called ``The Compound'' 365 days a year explaining: ``An
extra Christmas never hurt anybody.''
A close friend explained today's Sinatra: ``He's had a rough, tough life and
you are talking a classic burning the candle at both ends personality. We just
want him to take care of himself - to enjoy the September of his days. He's
sung about them often enough.
``But he does have an opinion on how he wants to run his life - and let's
everyone know it.
``He enjoys staying home now. He likes to have familiar things and people
around him. It's strange but I think he gets a little scared with strangers and
strange places. It's hard to imagine but that's how it is. He is now a man of
routine. He likes his comforts and his place.''
Our perception of him is as a breaker of hearts and legs but there is the
saintly side - he's given more than $250m to charity. Today he doesn't even
bother wearing someone else's hair - the toupees are still shampooed every
evening - and Hawaiian shirts which just about disguise the girth.
The overwhelming image from talking to those who know Sinatra at 80 is that he
is a cranky, conservative old man who lives remembering old scores and even
recalling to start new ones. There have been many long, hot days of egomania
but he has never sought sympathy. If anything it was his voice which has aged
gracefully. But he can no longer with ease fly people to the moon or invite
luck to be a lady this or that particular night.
Over the years the myths have multiplied and how much is fact or fascinating
fiction only he knows. One thing is certain and that's that there would require
much polish - more than Nancy Sinatra has provided - to wipe away the tarnish.
Barbara Sinatra has been working at it since she became his fourth wife on July
12, 1976. It's not been easy. She was 44 when she married Sinatra. A former Las
Vegas showgirl and former wife of Marx brother Zeppo and the single mother of a
grown up son from a teenaged married life has been tough and then pleasantly
indulgent. She was not some ingenue on long, shapely legs. She knew what she
wanted from being Mrs Francis Albert Sinatra.
She mellowed him faster than a crate of his favourite Jack Daniels bourbon. She
advised. She controlled. She talked him out of playing a Mafia Don in Godfather
3.
Her influence has been much more than any other of Sinatra's women including
the love of his life Ava Gardner, his first wife Nancy, Mia Farrow and lovers
like Lauren Bacall, Natalie Wood, Juliet Prowse and Gloria Vanderbilt. Nancy
Sinatra says: ``There has been so much garbage written about my father it is
time to turn it around. When you consider what he has done he deserves better
treatment than he has received.'' But that's a daughter talking.
Most of us would accept Sinatra as an extraordinary mix of heel and hero. There
are the stories of constant, callous womanising, his heartless treatment of his
first wife Nancy when she was in hospital after giving birth to Frank Junior,
insulting behaviour to Natalie Wood during their affair, his arranged abortion
for Elizabeth Taylor, cruelty to Mia Farrow, his affair with Lauren Bacall as
Humphrey Bogart lay dying of cancer, and his subsequent six-year campaign of
silence against her when she told the world they were engaged.
And of the third Nancy in his life - Nancy Reagan - of whom he said before she
even scented the White House: ``A dope with fat ankles who could never make it
as an actress.''
Despite the lurid tales he has for decades been on record and film one of the
century's most popular entertainers.
The image today is of an 80-year-old man who fervently believed he could call
as well as sing any tune.
And as Sinatra-mania soars to a crescendo he probably still does.
The world's favourite crooner turns 80 on Tuesday but, as Douglas Thompson
explains, even an older, mellow Frank Sinatra has maintained an everlasting
romance with his fans
</TEXT>
