<HEADLINE>Bursary switch angers Cosla</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995527</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BITTER attack was launched yesterday on Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth
after he confirmed that responsibility for awarding further education student
bursaries was being transferred from councils to colleges in April.
Councillor Rosemary McKenna, president of the Convention of Scottish Local
Authorities, said she would no longer believe anything Mr Forsyth said about
consultation until she saw it happening.
``We can only say that the Secretary of State speaks with forked tongue,'' she
said.
Mr Forsyth agreed last month to consult on the future of bursary disbursements
after Cosla expressed its concern about his plans. However, Mrs McKenna said
Cosla had heard nothing more until yesterday, when the Scottish Office
confirmed that the transfer was going ahead.
The 43 colleges have been removed from local government control and Mr Forsyth
said that adding bursaries to their other services would enable them to
``deliver an attractive, integrated approach to students''.
The resources which central Government will allocate to local government in
1996-7 will be reduced by about #50m - the value of bursaries.
</TEXT>
