<HEADLINE>Icy weather sends oil prices higher</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995529</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORLD oil prices continued to rise yesterday, pushed higher by icy weather
across Europe and also due to hit the United States.
North Sea Brent crude, the world oil-price benchmark, hit a five-month high of
$17.75 a barrel on the London futures market, before slipping later as traders
pocketed profits from the rise. By London closing, Brent had softened to $17.58.
``We've had a bit of a shock over the last few days (with the weather) and it's
given oil a very healthy helping hand,'' said Alistair Harris of London brokers
Mees Pierson.
Private US forecaster Weather Services Corp said cold weather would lift
heating demand well above normal levels in the key energy-consuming northeast
and midwest United States early next week, and in Europe over the weekend.
``My only worry is we're going up so sharply before the cold weather actually
begins (in the US),'' said Ahmed al-Awa of London brokers Prudential-Bache.
The resurgent threat of an oil workers' strike in Venezuela, a key supplier to
the US, gave further support to prices, traders said.
Talks between workers and state oil company Petroleos de Venezuela (PDVSA) on
pay broke off on Wednesday without reaching an agreement and union leaders have
now renewed strike calls.
Oil's rise came in the teeth of record world oil output in November shown in
monthly data released yesterday by the Paris-based International Energy Agency.
The IEA said a recovery in Mexican production after October's hurricane damage
together with increases from the North Sea and elsewhere, pushed world oil
supply up by 1.41 million barrels per day in November to a record 71.7 million
bpd.
</TEXT>
