<HEADLINE>Wife says MP told her `I have changed'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995530</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORY MP David Ashby's wife told the High Court in London yesterday of an
occasion in which she was in no doubt that he was admitting to her that he was
homosexual.
Mrs Silvana Ashby, who separated from the MP in 1993, said their sex life had
not been satisfactory, and his indifference had progressed to verbal and
physical abuse.
When Mr Ashby returned from America in 1992, where he had visited his
homosexual brother, Brian, and his partner, he said he could not stand to stay
with her any more.
When he told her that October that he would be moving out when his new flat was
ready, she insisted he tell her why. ``He said `I have got to tell you
something. I have changed.' He started to cry.''
Asked what he meant, he said: ``I had an encounter many years ago. Then I put
it out of my mind, and now I can't.''
She also started to cry, put her arms round him, and asked what she could do.
``I said: `If you have changed once, you can change again'. He said: `It is not
as easy as that'.''
Mrs Ashby said: ``I was in no doubt that he was telling me he was homosexual.''
Mr Ashby, 55, is claiming damages over allegations that he shared a double bed
with a man friend during a holiday in Goa at the end of 1993.
Times Newspapers and former Sunday Times editor Andrew Neil deny libel. They
accept that Mr Ashby did not holiday with a man in Goa, but assert that he was,
and is, having an affair with 32-year-old Dr Ciaran Kilduff.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
