<DOCNO>GH951208-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gascoigne is now a liability Luxury Rangers cannot afford</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995531</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PAUL Gascoigne arrived in Glasgow making it clear he admired and respected
Rangers' manager Walter Smith, but words are cheap especially in professional
football where the glib comment and blatant lie are common currency. So far as
I can see Gascoigne, a troubled soul it has to be said, has done nothing to
help his manager or his club, whose disapppointing Champions' League campaign
ended in failure.
Of course, if you regard increases in the sales of club merchandise as the most
important measure of a footballer's worth then Gascoigne probably has been a
success already. There is little doubt either that his presence has helped
create interest and sell tickets, but it is important to remember it isn't
enough for a footballer merely to be there. No matter how many strips, posters
or T-shirts are sold players must give something back on the pitch.
Despite what appears to be the common belief in some boardrooms, there is more
to football than paying out transfer fees on ``big names.'' Surely there has to
be some kind of return because the only thing that matters is performances on
the pitch, and no matter who wears the strips the patience of fans grows thin
when players who arrive, usually after their over-blown reputations, fail to
carry their weight.
Gascoigne is such a player. He has played well only sporadically and even those
supporters who were content to go along with Smith, who insisted Gascoigne
required time to regain full fitness after the various injury problems which
have dogged his career, are questioning football's John McEnroe.
Rangers' most controversial player and McEnroe were similar in that neither
could control his emotions yet each was blessed with sporting genius. McEnroe,
however, was able to demonstrate his superior skills more often than Gascoigne
and that is the most damning truth about the footballer.
Despite chairman David Murray's apparent backing for the player, Gascoigne
simply cannot be relied upon to perform at or near his best on a regular basis
and to my mind that makes him a  liability to a club which longs to operate
among the elite. He is a luxury they can't afford.
In recent premier division matches the midfield player has looked good, playing
with vision and thought way beyond just about everyone else. Also, in the first
half of the Champions' League match against Borussia Dortmund the other night
he threatened to have a great influence on the midfield, but it is at these
very times, moments when we begin to believe in the real Gascoigne, that he
loses it.
Having already been booked for a first-half foul on Andreas Moller the Rangers
player felt aggrieved when Spanish referee Manuel Diaz Vega didn't award a
penalty, apparently for handball, to Rangers. Gascoigne's mouth went into
overdrive.
The referee had no option but to send him off for the first time in his Rangers
career even if it was suggested afterwards Diaz Vega had forgotten he had
already booked Gascoigne. The story from Dortmund goes that the official would
have decided against brandishing a second yellow card if he had remembered
about the earlier punishment, but the fact is that the Spaniard did what some
referees in Scotland should have done long ago.
Gascoigne faces an automatic one-game ban when Rangers next play in Europe, but
he could face a stiffer penalty because he was also booked in one of the games
against Steaua Bucharest. ``The case will be considered by the control and
disciplinary committee on January 11 and it is possible the ban will be more
than one match,'' said a UEFA committee member.
Although Smith has spoken to Gascoigne about the dismissal and the player's
failure to curb his temper he would not say what action, if any, the club will
take, but the manager must be at his wit's end. Fining a player of Gascoigne's
wealth wouldn't mean a great deal and even if it was decided to put him under
house arrest for a few weeks there would be no guarantees. The extremely
fragile nature of Gascoigne's temperament and the complexities which must exist
within the mind of someone in command of so much talent and at the same time
stupidity make him unpredictable and volatile.
Rangers might find that changing SFA policy would be easier than changing
Gascoigne, who appears destined to be torn between greatness and disgrace. It
is a pity, but so far he has been more trouble than he is worth to the Ibrox
club and the Scottish game in general.
There is no substitute for skill, but when it is contained within an enigma
surrounded by question marks the chances are it will all end in tears. Rangers
might have to release Gascoigne just as Lazio did and we must fear the worst
for the player, who will sit out his club's next two premier division matches
because of suspension.
Rangers, in the meantime, could learn from their humbling experience in the
Champions' League and it is still Smith's intention to introduce a couple of
new players, Mikkel Beck and Jardel, but the notion is to move soon so that the
newcomers would have almost half a season in which to bed into the Ibrox
set-up. Then, and provided Smith's side win their eighth successive
championship, Rangers might be better equipped next time around.
</TEXT>
