<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH development side, managed by former Scotland and British Lions
wing-threequarter Roger Baird and coached by Glasgow Academicals' New Zealand
coach Kevin Greene, is to be created to bridge the gap between under-21 level
and the A-team set-up, writes Derek Douglas.
The new squad, which will be created early next year, will have its first
representative outing against New South Wales at Netherdale on February 11.
Baird has been appointed manager and chairman of selectors with George Blackie,
on the SRU general committee, as convener. Greene will be assisted by
Boroughmuir coach Henry Edwards, who will look after the forwards. National
squad co-ordinator Roy Laidlaw will assist with technical administration.
The development squad will initially number more than 21 players and the SRU
plan to have a warm-up game before the NSW fixture.
Yesterday, SRU director of rugby Jim Telfer said: ``The development squad will
provide players with a further bridge to make that all-important transition in
fitness, technique, and commitment between under-age, club, and district rugby
and the higher standards needed at international level.
``It will also act as a means of encouraging talented players to remain in the
game, by providing them with both first-class training and incentive - and one
clear encouragement is the prospect of significant fixtures both home and away,
giving our emerging players additional exposure to top-flight rugby,'' he said.
q FORMER All Black Colin Meads has been sacked as manager of New Zealand, who
have named Ross Cooper and Gordon Hunter as selectors alongside new coach John
Hart.
One of the newly chosen pair will become assistant coach to Hart, who was named
as successor to Laurie Mains yesterday.
Meads is replaced by Mike Banks, a hotelier who has been a member of the New
Zealand Rugby Football Union council for only two years. Banks was a full back
for the Manawatu provincial team in the late 1970s.
</TEXT>
