<HEADLINE>Students set for the season's first big test Good cup run will cap University centenary</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995533</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE road to Hampden begins in earnest tomorrow when the first round of the
Tennents Scottish Cup gets underway, and bringing an intellectual touch to the
competition this year are the boys from Glasgow University.
It is more likely that they will display a budding Bamber Gascoigne rather than
a Paul when they take on East of Scotland side Spartans in Glasgow in the first
round proper, but they do take their football seriously.
And, as this is the university football club's centenary year, they aim to make
it extra special with a decent cup run.
Mind you, tradition is all against that happening. It is 20 years since the
students last appeared in the competition proper. They did survive the first
round by virtue of a bye, but, in the second round after holding Albion Rovers
to a 1-1 draw at Cliftonhill, they went down by the only goal of the game in
the replay.
A bye also shot them into the second round in the 1970-71 season, but they lost
2-1 to Clachnacuddin in Inverness.
Two years before that, they did manage to get into the hat with the big boys
again, having been given a bye, then winning a second round preliminary tie
against St Cuthbert Wanderers. In the first round proper, they were paired with
Kilmarnock at Rugby Park and lost 6-0.
But, here they are again, as hopeful as ever of making their mark, if not an
impact.
Said manager Donnie Ferguson: ``The club was formed in 1877, but was defunct in
the 1880s and was not re-formed until 1895. That's why we celebrate our
centenary this year.
``Our big problem in the cup is that the qualifying section starts when the
students are still on holiday, but this year, they came back from all parts to
play. That brought us our success in getting through to this first round.''
For two of the players, defeat will mean the last time they turn out for the
side. The players are all students, and when they leave university, they leave
the team.
Defenders Robbie Mitchell and Steve Duffy, who have both started work, are
allowed to continue for the cup run as they were involved in the earlier ties.
Meantime, Eamonn Bannon will have a double interest in tomorrow's first round.
The former Hearts and Dundee United winger will be in the Stenhousemuir side
which faces Arbroath in the opening round, but he will also want to know the
result of the tie between Glasgow University and Spartans as soon as he comes
off the pitch.
Spartans manager Sam Lynch explained: ``After Eamonn left Hearts, he came along
to our training sessions. Originally, it was to keep himself ticking over, but
he soon got involved in doing a bit of coaching. He is very thoughtful about
the game, and his help is appreciated.''
Spartans, from the East of Scotland League, include former Hibernian and
Partick Thistle striker Paul McGovern and central defender Mark Thomson, who
had a spell with Meadowbank.
Added Lynch: ``We are looking forward to the visit to     Glasgow. The
incentive for both teams is to get through to meet East fife in the next round.
``We have watched University, and they are a good side. It will be a fairly
open game.''
q COVENTRY City manager Ron Atkinson will have to play a waiting game if he
wants to sign Dave McPherson from Hearts.
Atkinson has been in touch with the Tynecastle side over the future of
McPherson but the former Scotland defender is out of action until Christmas
because of a groin injury.
Coventry's defence has been leaking goals at an alarming rate recently and
Atkinson wants a new man in place before tomorrow's clash with Blackburn Rovers
at Highfield Road.
But with McPherson sidelined, he will now have to decide whether to hang fire
until McPherson is fit, or look elsewhere.
</TEXT>
