<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995534</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE English and Welsh unions will receive their clubs' blueprint of the way
ahead for club rugby following a meeting in Bristol yesterday.
Three representatives from each of the limited companies set up to serve the
interests of the 12 clubs in the Heineken League first division and 10 Courage
League clubs have thrashed out plans for the future competitive structure of
non-representative rugby.
The Welsh delegates will report back to their clubs at a meeting next week and
are expected to present their plans to the WRU before Christmas.
In a joint statement, the groups said: ``Representatives of First Division
Rugby Limited and English First Division Rugby Limited had a very wide-ranging,
constructive meeting in Bristol today and will be seeking approval next week
from all their fellow representatives for the domestic, Anglo-Welsh, and
European rugby structure discussed at the meeting.''
Among their list of demands to the governing bodies will be a greater share of
TV and sponsorship deals and bigger representation on decision-making bodies.
q RUGBY league is set to become faster and more attractive as a result of four
rule changes which will come into force from Monday in all Rugby Football
League matches.
The changes, which have been given the go-ahead by the Rugby League Council,
are: No striking at the play-the-ball; the ball must be played backwards at the
play-the-ball; scrums will be taken 20 metres from touch instead of 10; the
scoring team will restart play after a score.
RFL chief executive Maurice Lindsay said: ``Our aim is to make the game of
rugby league as exciting and thrilling as possible for our supporters. We
believe that these new moves will do exactly that.
``The two new play-the-ball rules tidy up this area of the game, while the 20m
scrum opens up a wide range of attacking options and the change in the restart
of play will ensure excitement right up to the final hooter.''
Played yesterday
Bank of Scotland Scottish Schools Cup. First round - Queen Victoria 23,
Galashiels Academy 10; Edinburgh Academy 20, Gordonstoun 24.
