<HEADLINE>Funds pensioned off overseas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALEX FALCONER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995535</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are about 20 million contributors, pensioners, and deferred members in UK
pension schemes. Very few give the administration of their schemes much thought.
Like most other people, when I started paying contributions my concerns were
confined to the additional income after retirement, which would make old age
more bearable. As a shop steward at Rosyth Dockyard in 1983, I became involved
in the development of Labour's Alternative Economic Strategy manifesto. Within
the manifesto was a proposal that those who contributed to the scheme should
become more involved in its operations and investment policies.
My interest was rekindled on reading an article in the Financial Times in March
1990. Among the mass of figures and jargon, something stood out. Between 1979
and 1989, the percentage of pension funds invested overseas had risen from 6%
to 24%. The European Federation for Retirement Provision estimates that by 1993
this had risen to 31.2%. To that can be added about 8% which is invested in
other European Union member states. Or, in other words, with up to #500bn now
in the funds' coffers, nearly #200bn of pension fund assets are overseas.
What would that money do if it was invested in Britain?
Two years ago, I published a pamphlet entitled ``So whose pension funds are
they, anyway?'' This looked at the issues of investment policy and
accountability to members. Earlier this year, we began to update that leaflet,
and decided to look at the involvement of pension funds in privatised companies.
Now we have published a new pamphlet - ``Global Village Economics'' - which
ties in the operation of the financial institutions to the European Union's
approach to unemployment, and global trade and capital movement. It contains
the results of a study of UK pension funds, including the top 50 by market
value, and all the local authority funds. It is, I believe, the first to look
at how much money the various funds have invested in privatised industries.
I am not opposed to money being invested overseas, although I would prefer it
if such investments were influenced by considerations such as workers getting
decent pay and conditions, the environment not being degraded, fair trade, and
human rights.
The problem is that, individually and as a nation, we have very little control
of this money. It could ruin us, and perhaps the European Union too, or it
could lead our economy to recovery. While Westminster politicians are
scrambling around for a billion or two with which to perform economic miracles,
pension funds have all that money invested abroad.
Even the money which remains here in the UK is not being used in the best
long-term interests of the British people. Look at the role of the funds in the
British Gas debacle, and the way financial institutions have lobbied to push up
water bills. Profits are more important than service, delivery, and public
opinion. That's the way the system is set up.
Local authority funds are particularly significant, because I believe that
their accountability should extend not only to the members of the scheme, but
also to the public. While there are restrictions on the operation of pension
funds, such as investing for the best return regardless of any other
consideration, there is no legal bar to publicising how funds are invested.
Perhaps a wider knowledge of their activities will bring demands for changes in
how they are administered.
UK pension funds are major shareholders in former public utilities, although
this is not immediately obvious from annual reports of the privatised
companies. Financial institutions are probably majority shareholders in most of
the privatised sector. Individual shareholders are a shrinking minority.
The survey results suggest that local authority funds have #4.5bn invested in
privatised companies, and that the total for all funds is over #40bn. Such
companies account for up to 12% of pension funds' investment, with over #9bn in
various electricity companies, about #6.5bn in BP, over #6bn in BT, nearly #5bn
in British Gas, and about #4.5bn in water companies.
Just think about that the next time you hear a report of a massive pay rise or
share-options deal for a privatised company executive or chairperson. Or the
next time a water company announces massive profits after cutting off consumers.
The pamphlet also examines the growth of European Union unemployment (now more
than 20 million people), proposals to tackle this with a European recovery
plan, and the problems which such a plan would face because of the freedom of
capital movement enjoyed by pension funds and other financial institutions.
Such programmes could be fatally undermined by the lack of democratic control
of the financial institutions. There should be a radical rethink of our
economic structures to counter this.
Other problems also have a bearing on our ability to tackle unemployment.
Maastricht's convergence criteria cannot be met without disastrous economic
consequences. France is now experiencing the pain which this will involve.
Maastricht demands severe cutbacks in the welfare state.
Gatt ignores social and environmental issues, and severely diminishes the
ability of the EU's member states to control their own economies. Agreements
similar to Gatt are now being sought on foreign direct investment. However,
even Germany, the economic powerhouse of Europe, is now experiencing problems
with investment moving overseas. Social and environmental clauses should be
incorporated into any new international economic agreement.
Next year's Inter Governmental Conference would be a superb opportunity for all
this to be debated, but I must admit to being pessimistic about the chances of
this happening. They will probably end up debating the Conservative Party's
anti-social tendencies once again.
Labour should not fall into this trap. We must develop an alternative to this
mad system of unfettered capitalism. If that means formulating policy which
extends accountability of these funds to people then we should not shy away
from it. It may, however, prove too much like common ownership for some
sections of the party.
n.Alex Falconer is MEP for Mid Scotland and Fife.
</TEXT>
