<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995536</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRUST the bar treasurer to hit the jackpot when a drinks prize is up for grabs!
As the race for Herald Selector Rugby's prizes intensifies, Jock Henderson,
from Crailing, near Jedburgh, has captured the November prize of #500 and a
case of champagne by just a single point - the narrowest winning margin to date
in the competition.
The chase for the overall prize of a trip for two to New Zealand, to see
Scotland play the All Blacks, is even closer. The leading two contenders are
absolutely deadlocked, according to the organisers, Scottish Rugby magazine.
Mr Henderson, a Jed-Forest supporter, who looks after the bar finances at
Riverside, might have won more conclusively but for injuries, notably to
Heriot's regular kicker, Cameron Glasgow, and his own club's international
scrum half, Gary Armstrong.
Armstrong's absence also curtailed the potential of Jock's other selection from
his own club - Ronnie Kirkpatrick, who normally feeds off Armstrong to telling
effect. This season, Jed's two flankers have been the more profitable back row
men.
Ironically, eight Jed players reached double figures during November.
Like his father before him, Jock, an accountant, played for the club for the
best part of 20 years: ``though with no distinction - I was a rather slow
front-row forward,'' he confesses. His winning team for November was:
Gavin Hastings (Watsonians); Kenny Logan (Stirling County), Scott Hastings
(Watsonians), Graham Shiel (Melrose), Cammy Glasgow (Heriot's); George
Breckenridge (GHK), Gary Armstrong (Jed-Forest); Peter Wright (Boroughmuir),
Kevin McKenzie (Stirling County), Alan Kittle (Stewart's-Melville, now
Watsonians), Stewart Campbell (Dundee HS FP), Jeremy Richardson (Edinburgh
Academicals), Bruce Ward (Currie), Ronnie Kirkpatrick (Jed-Forest), Murray
Wallace (GHK).
Selectors of last month's 10 leading teams were:
J Henderson (Jedburgh) 218 points; 2, D Harvey (Kilmacolm) 217; 3 equal, C
Lyall (Pollockshields) and R Harvey (Bearsden) both 211; 5 equal, A Peel
(Alloa) and J Scott (Irvine) both 207; 7, R Henry (Helmsdale), 205; 8, E
Donaldson (Balerno), 203; 9 equal, I McNair (Perth) and J Niven (Dumbarton)
both 202.
Neither Mr Henderson, nor any of the contending teams or the November award, is
in the immediate running for outright victory, but the stage is set for a
nail-biting conclusion when the final postponed matches are played a week on
Saturday.
At the end of November the overall lead was shared by Mr D MacGregor
(Lochgoilhead) and Mr N Anderson (Edinburgh), on 711 points. Ally Donaldson,
the Currie stand-off who heads Selector Rugby's points table, has his own
personal team in sixth place, four points behind that of his wife, Elaine. Her
eighth place in the November rankings was achieved with a different XV from
that chasing the overall prize. Just 40 points cover the leading 10 contenders:
1 equal, D MacGregor (Lochgoilhead) and N Anderson (Edinburgh) 711; 3, K
Murdoch (Troon) 700; 4, W Kinross (Tillicoultry) 692; 5, E Donaldson (Balerno)
684; 6, A Donaldson (Balerno) 680; 7, D B McNicol (Stenhousemuir) 675; 8, M
Liddle (Tillicoultry) 673; 9 equal, D Beckwith (Troon) and L Greer (Glasgow)
671.
