<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NEW LABOUR and the NEW UNION</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alf Young, Economics Editor, Benedict Brogan, Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>the tony blair interview</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995537</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was a visibly confident Tony Blair who set out the task facing Labour in the
run-up to the next election: to counter Tory ``lies'' about devolution and
speak the truth of a New Union for Britain built on a Scottish parliament in
Edinburgh with tax-raising powers.
Although he made clear Labour will not tamper with the standard rate of tax in
Scotland - and will say so in its manifesto for the new parliament - there will
be no dilution of Labour's commitment to home rule. Devolution as envisaged by
the Constitutional Convention was a logical solution to the problem -
acknowledged by Michael Forsyth - that change to the way Scotland is governed
is necessary.
In a detailed interview, in which he spoke with ease on both the principle and
the complexities of devolution, the Labour leader said the party would defend
its corner with vigour against Tory propaganda. The briefing folder prepared by
his staff remained unopened on the coffee table as Tony Blair described his
personal, uncluttered vision of constitutional reform, and called on voters -
and the business community - to believe Labour policy rather than Tory lies.
Michael Forsyth, by his words and St Andrew's Day reforms, had conceded the
argument that change is necessary, he said. Labour offered the best solution
for making accountable the Scottish Office, with its 15,000 civil servants
providing services across nine Government departments, run by
Westminster-controlled politicians.
``The purpose of devolution is to get from a situation in which you have a
Scottish Office and a vast bureaucracy around it that isn't directly
accountable to the situation where local services are delivered by a body that
is directly accountable,'' he said.
The Scottish Secretary has lost the argument and admitted the need for change,
he said. ``He has been forced to admit that the status quo no longer holds. I
think that was a strategic move of enormous importance because from that moment
on the issue is no longer whether there's change but what type of change.'' And
on that question, as on others, the public will recognise that the Tories are
``disastrously wrong for Scotland''.
But with Mr Forsyth and Tory Central Office gearing up their campaign to
preserve the Union against change, Tony Blair understands that it remains up to
Labour to make the case for devolution and the Convention's plan for a Scottish
parliament.
``What we do from now is we counter the lies, we speak the truth, we make the
case, and we make it not just to the ordinary citizens of Scotland who get a
better democratic deal, but to business to show how they will get a better deal
for business.''
On the detailed workings of a Scottish parliament, Mr Blair appears to accept
the risks of strains between Edinburgh and Westminster as an unavoidable - and
above all manageable - by-product of reform. Having to arbitrate between a
Scottish parliament demanding the scope to pay for its ambitions, and a
Chancellor Gordon Brown struggling to impose restraint on the public finances,
is clearly tomorrow's problem.
``There can always be tensions between different parts of constitutional
government,'' he said. It all boils down to a process of negotiation, like the
annual debate with the Treasury over Scottish Office funding. ``I can't really
believe these things are insuperable or beyond the wit of individuals to
resolve, in the same way that they have, of course, to be resolved now.''
On the timing for implementation of a Sottish parliament, he had no answer.
There is a difference of opinion developing between various Scottish Labour
politicians: some believe it can be done quickly, arguing that once the
legislation is in place the parliament could take over the running of the
Scottish Office within a year. Others see several years of hard legislative
slog just to get the change on the books, and even longer to prepare the
parliament.
It would be foolish to announce a date for when the first ``order, order'' will
echo over Calton Hill, he said, ``but it is a priority, we believe in it. I
really don't think there can be any doubt that we believe in it.''
Any suspicion that might exist that Mr Blair has not engaged intellectually
with the question of Scotland's future was dispelled by the clarity with which
he addressed the issue. Those around him say he has gone out of his way to
inform himself, and to open the debate within the party to take in not just his
Scottish colleagues but those south of the Border as well.
Although he has shown courage in allowing Shadow Scottish Secretary George
Robertson to define the policy unhindered, it is clear he is now a driving
force behind it.
But he was also sufficiently aware of the dangers posed to any English
politician entering the closed, labyrinthine world of Scottish politics to
tread carefully. ``One of the things that is always curious when you discuss
this, is that the slightest word or nuance is taken as meaning far more than it
ever should. The Labour Party commitment is clear, that we will legislate in
the first year of a Labour government.''
The new slogan was unveiled at the end. We had been joined in his office
beneath Big Ben by Alastair Campbell, Mr Blair's redoubtable press secretary,
who slipped a note to his leader. A smile crossed his face and moments later
came: ``I believe it is, if you like, New Labour, New Union.'' We chuckled at
first, but the potency was obvious.
``There is a New Union that can help bind the United Kingdom together against
the forces of destruction, those for separatism, which would be a disaster for
Scotland, and do nothing, no change, which would increasingly play into the
hand of those that want separation. A New Union is what Scotland and what
Britain needs for a new century.''
Turning the screw on 'lie machine'.
MR Blair returned repeatedly to what he described as the Tory lie machine and
the work of its chief propagandist, Michael Forsyth. But he admitted the
``tartan tax'' label had had an effect, and promised Labour would ``come out of
its corner fighting'' on the issue.
The ``tartan tax'', the Scottish Secretary's claim that a vote for devolution
means a vote for a 3p increase in income tax, was a myth designed to terrorise
the voters.
``It is rubbish, absolute utter rubbish,'' he said. ``The Tory lie that should
be nailed is this idea that the Scottish parliament means that your taxes go
up. It means nothing of the sort. Taxes only go up if people vote for it, and
that's up to Scots. That's the essence of devolution.''
The Labour leader rejected any suggestion that Labour was vulnerable on the
issue. By declaring that Labour would not include a tax increase in its first
manifesto for a Scottish parliament, he moved to cut off Mr Forsyth's most
potent campaign weapon.
``The fact is there has been a huge campaign of disinformation that requires to
be corrected, and it's part of our job. The longer this debate goes on the
better for us,'' he said, adding: ``I would concede that the moment this type
of lie is stated there is a need to counter it very strongly.''
The Tories have visibly moved up a gear since the leadership election and the
summer reshuffle.
The double act of Deputy Prime Minister Michael Heseltine and party chairman
Brian Mawhinney has imposed a tougher, more brutal approach to the day-to-day
of Westminister politics.
With Labour on 57% in Scotland, both parties know that the only way for the
party to go is down. A long, nasty General Election campaign has begun.
``This Government is desperate. They have shut down the business of government.
What you have in its place is a Conservative party propaganda machine. All the
forces of government are used to that end,'' Mr Blair said.
Revelations that Central Office had used Home Office files to discredit asylum
seekers, and that the Government was imposing an inquiry into an opt-out debate
in his Sedgefield constituency, were proof of how government has been abandoned
in favour of politics.
The same was true in Scotland. ``The way that Mr Forsyth operates in Scotland,
he's not a Government Minister, he's a propagandist for the Conservative Party
and that propaganda is designed primarily to get up and running the same
machine that was in existence before the last election. I call it the Tory lie
machine.''
In 1992 the Tories took on devolution and Labour was ill-equipped to counter
the attack. This the party has seen it coming and is prepared.
On the ``tartan tax'', as on the wider question of devolution, Mr Blair is
obviously confident: ``I think it's a very good idea, when you have a good
argument, to show a bit of backbone and get it across.
``I think we should come out of our corner fighting.''
Labour's campaign organisation is more efficient than it was in 1992, and
capable of taking the fight to the Tories. But for the Tories too high a
reliance on ``the lie'' could have disastrous consequences, Mr Blair suggested.
``They are taking a very big risk with what they're doing, because, if they
lose the next election and there is a Labour government, the gap between the
lies they told and the reality is going to be used against them for a very long
period.''
Serving the community
MR Blair is dismissive of the suggestion that he could alienate business
leaders if Labour carries through its promise to start dismantling large areas
of the quango state, where many of these same people serve.
The Labour leader insists they can still be involved, through advisory bodies
and committees.
He said: ``They can be involved directly making representations. And they can,
if they wish, offer themselves for election.'' He also reserves the right to
retain certain appointed bodies, on which business people could serve.
Advocate of change courts business
MR Blair's confidence that he can persuade the business community to give
Labour a fair hearing is undented by talk of firms quitting a devolved Scotland
in droves or the reported power struggle within CBI Scotland over its recent
agnostic line on constitutional change.
On the CBI manoeuvres, he says ``I hope they're not just playing politics with
us. We know the Conservative Party will be very active and it will have certain
supporters in business. What I find with the Conservative Party nowadays is
that it tends to behave a bit like an opposition.''
On Wednesday evening the Labour leader spoke to an overflow meeting of the
CBI's London region. There, he says, he found ``massive support'' for the
creation of one strategic authority to govern London. ``They have seen the
consequences of a whole lot of small unitary authorities being unable to deal
with big strategic problems.''
And he believes that is part of a wider process. ``I'm bound to say that the
CBI at UK level have actually made movement towards greater regional government
in England, precisely because they recognise the strength of the arguments for
bodies with whom business can properly do business.''
Demonstrating relaxed assurance, Mr Blair went on to set out his own approach
to persuading business Labour means what it says. ``I want to move beyond the
stage where I'm simply reassuring business that it isn't going to be damaged by
Labour. That reassurance is important because of the past, because of the
historical feelings of business and because, to be blunt about it, the Labour
Party went through a stage in the late seventies and early eighties when some
of its attitudes and some of its people were anti-business. It was wrong and
foolish. And we were right to change it.''
According to Mr Blair, what business and government now need to agree are the
``key public interest objectives'' they can achieve by working together. He
lists education and skills, infrastructure, harnessing new technology,
developing the regions and the inner cities, and playing a leading role in
Europe.
``These are all areas where Labour has a lot to offer business. I would say a
great deal more to offer than a Conservative Party that has this ideological
split between those who believe there is a role for government and those who
believe there isn't.''
The Labour leader is keen to emphasise those areas of public/private
collaboration which successfully generate major projects. ``The place I'll be
speaking in in Edinburgh (the new International Conference Centre) is a perfect
example. These things are now part and parcel of everyday life.''
As the party's City spokesman Alistair Darling found recently at an investment
bankers' dinner in Edinburgh, Labour's intention to sign up for the social
chapter of the Maastricht Treaty and its commitment to a national minimum wage
generates even more heat among some sections of the business community than a
tax-raising Scottish parliament.
In his own meetings with business people, Mr Blair has felt some of that same
heat. But, again, given a year or more before the next election, he is
confident a rational case for both can be sold, even to the business community.
``The Tories say the minimum wage is going to lose millions of jobs. That
signing up for the social chapter means no one will ever come to Britain again.
Let's deal in facts,'' says the Labour leader. ``Japan, the United States, and
every other country in Europe has a minimum wage. The issue is what level it's
to be set at.''
So what will that final rate be? The #4.15 an hour some unions are advocating?
Or a lower figure? Can he even offer the formula which will be used? The Labour
Party, he points out, deliberately changed its minimum wage policy to ensure
the rate would only be set after consultation with business and industry.
``We want to make sure it is introduced in such a way that it does not have an
adverse effect,'' he adds.
``My answer to those who say: Why won't you tell us the level it'll be set at,
is this: the very thing we're offering you is what you should be asking for.
Namely the chance to have an influence in the process of setting it.''
Business, he believes, is ignoring the positive benefits minimum wage
legislation could bring. It would, he argues, help legitimate businesses fight
against unfair competition from firms paying extremely low levels of pay. It
would also help the Exchequer, and could reduce the tax burden on everyone.
``We are currently spending in this country upwards of #2500m subsidising low
pay through the benefits system.
`` As part of a new benefit, welfare package a minimum wage is a very sensible
element and it's being used as such by other countries.
On the social chapter, the Labour leader is again at pains to dispel what he
believes are Tory myths. ``The Tory lie machine says the social chapter is a
huge raft of detailed social legislation which comes in holus bolus if you sign
up. It is not. It is a set of principles.''
He points to one of the first pieces of legislation initiated under the chapter
provisions - the parental leave directive. ``In my view, the idea that this is
some appalling thing that no business can ever contemplate is wrong. Most
sensible businesses are trying to do something like this already.''
There is, he argues, no inconsistency between having decent minimum standards
at the workplace and an efficient economy.
Pledge on the cost of an Assembly
``TAXES only go up if the people vote for them,'' the leader of the opposition
insisted yesterday, on the eve of his meeting business tour of Scotland.
``There will be no tax raised at all unless the party goes into an election
promising it and succeeds. We have no plans to do that, never mind anyone
else.''
Tony Blair and his senior colleagues are well aware of the political damage
being inflicted on the Labour case for devolution by Michael Forsyth's tartan
tax campaign of recent months.
There have been clear rumblings of discontent among some in the Scottish
business community about the disincentive effects of having higher rates of
personal taxation in Scotland. Having set out his stall, promoting Labour as
the real pro-business party, Blair needs to counter that tartan tax assault.
On the eve of the latest Blair visit to Edinburgh, Glasgow, and Stirling, there
were reports of a revolt within the Scottish CBI to get the organisation to
adopt a more overtly anti-home rule - and, by implication, anti-Labour -
stance. Just as in the 1992 election, Labour tax plans are threatening to
rebound on the party.
Mr Blair's solution, repeated several times in an exclusive extended interview
with The Herald, is to subject the Scottish parliament's discretionary power to
raise or lower basic rate income tax by up to 3p in the pound to a democratic
mandate at each Assembly election.
He is not, he insists, issuing some new constitutional prescription for a home
rule parliament in Edinburgh. ``I'm simply saying that the idea that, if you
have a Scottish parliament, the taxes go up 3p . . .is rubbish, it's absolute
and utter rubbish.
``We would accept as a political obligation that, if we intended to raise tax,
we would say so when we fought the election.''
Mr Blair is sticking to an old Labour theme that devolution is about making
government in Scotland and its attendant bureaucracy more accountable to the
democratic process. Why, he asks, is it wrong to give an Edinburgh Assembly
some tax discretion, when local councils raise some of their revenue through
council tax? He argues that, once established, an Assembly would be good for
Scottish business.
But he will also use his Scottish tour to drive home this new message that
Labour is responsible on tax and will only use the Edinburgh Assembly's tax
powers with the electorate's prior consent. That pledge, given the reluctance
of the electorate to vote for higher taxes, could mean putting the Assembly's
discretionary taxation power on a very back burner over a very low heat.
On the cost of the proposed Assembly - another major issue for some Scottish
businesses who see that cost being passed on to them - Mr Blair is emphatic
that the Assembly will have no power to raise corporate taxes.
``As for the cost, the budget for a Scottish parliament will come out of the
existing Scottish budget. The bureaucracy is there. We have 15,000 civil
servants in Scotland, covering nine different government departments. I think
any rational debate about this leads inevitably to the conclusion that there
should be substantial change. The only question then is whether we have the
best proposals and I think we have,'' he says.
``I understand the concerns businesses will have because businesses on the
whole in my experience of them don't much like change. All I ask them to do is
look at the facts, not the myths peddled by the Conservatives. I believe they
have a lot to gain from Scottish devolution in terms of more accountable
government and one strategic body where a lot of their economic concerns can be
dealt with.''
</TEXT>
