<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Animal lobby lives to fight on</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KIRSTY SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995538</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was one of the most horrific cases of cruelty animal inspectors had ever
come across. Shot five times with an air rifle and used as a football by the
two youths who had picked it up, the hedgehog was eventually thrown on to a
bonfire to die. It was discovered severely burned and injured but still alive
the following day, when it was put down by a vet.
The Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals tried to prosecute
but was forced to withdraw the charges, because, under British law at the
moment, it is not an offence to commit acts of appalling cruelty against many
wild mammals.
Now there are fresh hopes that legislation could be in place next year to
outlaw such practices after Labour announced it plans to reintroduce the Wild
Mammals (Protection) Bill.
The Bill, originally championed by Dumbarton MP John McFall, was earlier
dropped on a technicality after a constant stream of amendments, complaints,
and delays. Animal campaigners say it was effectively sabotaged.
In its original form, the Bill was designed to outlaw all hunting with hounds
or the snaring of wild mammals. Following pressure from the bloodsports lobby,
it was eventually watered down to making it a criminal offence to
``intentionally and cruelly kick, beat, nail or otherwise impale, burn, crush
or drown any wild animal.'' It was approved by the Commons by 253 votes to nil
last March and a variety of amendments were applied when it went through the
House of Lords. Earlier this month, however, Ministers refused to give it the
couple of seconds it needed and it ran out of time.
Yesterday Alan Meale, Labour MP for Mansfield, announced that he was to
re-introduce the Bill after winning parliamentary time at No.2 on the private
members ballot.
However, field sports officials say Mr Meale wants to push ahead with the Bill
as it stood before the Lords' amendments and they are implacably opposed to it
in that form.
British Field Sports Society spokeswoman Janet George said the wording of the
Bill left the way open for prosecution of farmers and sportsmen going about
their regular business. For example, a gardener using a mole trap might be
prosecuted or a farmer burning stubble and animals caught in the stubble could
be prosecuted.
``We were happy with the way that it came back to the Commons with all the
amendments agreed from all sides in the House of Lords,'' said Ms George. ``The
fact that Mr Meale has refused to use that amended version indicates something
more than a desire to bring in an animal welfare measure.''
Mr McFall said yesterday he was delighted that the Bill would be pushed forward
again but had been disgusted at its failure last time round.
``The frustrations were immense, because we managed to get it through the
Commons, the Lords, and back to the Commons and it needed two seconds of
parliamentary time but the leader of the House Tony Newton didn't allow it. I
had an opportunity to put it forward next year as what is called a back to the
chair Bill, however, I felt that it could still be hijacked by opponents,
therefore, when Alan Meale came up as No.2 in the private members ballot, it
was a golden opportunity.''
Mr McFall said he thinks the Bill had been tripped up initially ``because I
think that some people in the hunting fraternity are implicitly opposed to
providing any protection for wild mammals, just in case it gets to them.
Frankly that's a situation that is inexplicable to almost everyone.
``If we find people voting against this, I think not only their political but
their personal reputation will be at stake, because my Bill did clear the House
of Commons unanimously and this is it coming back in the same form.''
At the headquarters of the RSPCA, spokeswoman Sue Atkinson said they were
delighted that the Bill was being given a second chance.
``This time I think it stands a really good chance, we are very optimistic that
it will get enough time to go through. It really is a disgraceful situation at
the moment. If you had a pet fox and you kicked it, you could be prosecuted,
but you could kick a wild fox to death if you wanted to and it's still
completely legal.
``If we get calls our staff are often forced to say to someone who has a gang
kicking a rabbit to death outside their door, there's nothing we can do.''
Apart from the hedgehog mentioned earlier, the RSPCA were also powerless to act
in the case of a Muntjac deer which was attacked by four dogs which had been
set on it by a man and a boy. A woman passerby took the seriously injured
animal to a vet where it was put down, but, although she provided a clear
description of the man and his car registration number, no action could be
taken.
In a separate incident, six youths in Merseyside battered a wild rabbit to
death in front of witnesses, who testified that they had seen the thugs
throwing a coat over the screaming animal and kicking and beating it with
sticks. Veterinary reports showed the rabbit died after its skull was totally
crushed. The RSPCA did secure a conviction initially but it was quashed after
an appeal to the High Court.
</TEXT>
