<DOCID>GH951208-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lottery threat to Trust plans</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM WHARTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>arena</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995539</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN Lord Wheatley produced his report following the disaster at Ibrox Stadium
in 1971, it was apparent that there was an urgent need to implement a wide
range of spectator safety measures at our football grounds. Authorities and
individual football clubs acknowledged the need for this work and appealed to
Government for help in meeting the financial implications.
The Football Grounds Improvement Trust was formed in 1975, following the launch
of the Spot-the-Ball competition, as an initiative by the pools companies, led
by Littlewoods, and the then Football League secretary, Alan Hardaker. With a
budget of less than #300,000 per annum in the first few years, the initial
grants were, of necessity, of modest amounts.
The first major grant to come to Scotland was to Dumbarton FC towards the cost
of building the facility which to this day is the main grandstand, housing the
spectating area, changing facilities, offices, and boardroom of the club.
One of the last public acts of Alan Hardaker was to open this stand, and a
plaque commemorating the event can be seen when entering the building. Hardaker
died suddenly shortly afterwards, and one of my first tasks as a newly
appointed trustee, in 1979, was to plead the Dumbarton case as no formal offer
of grant had been made. Eventually the merits of the argument succeeded, but it
was a fair old battle.
Scotland had not been represented on the Trust at its formation, but the shrewd
League President, Tom Lauchlan, and Greenock Morton boss, Hal Stewart, had the
foresight to see the potential, and campaigned for direct representation.
The Trust blossomed, income rose to more than #6million per annum, and the
percentage of grant support rose to 75%. Following the disasters at Bradford
and Hillsbrough, the Government appointed Lord Justice Taylor to head an
inquiry into safety and the standard of provisions for spectators.
The Taylor Report, as the final document became known, produced the most
far-reaching and stringent standards ever demanded for sports grounds, not only
in this country, but worldwide.
The implementation of Taylor necessitated major funding, and again Government
helped by providing a rebate in the pools' betting duty. In an agreement with
the pools companies, the Football Trust was charged with the responsibility of
structuring a grant-aid scheme to assist clubs to meet Taylor and encourage the
building of new stadia throughout the country.
Eight new grounds have been built: three in Scotland - Stirling Albion, Clyde
(at Cumbernauld) and Livingston - and five in England - Middlesbrough,
Millwall, Northampton, Chester, and the impressive Huddersfield Stadium which
has just won the RIBA award as the best new building of the year.
Several new grounds are planned, notably Falkirk, Clydebank, East Fife,
Hamilton, Airdrieonians and Inverness in Scotland, and Sunderland, Southampton,
Bolton, Reading, and Oxford in England.
Substantial support has been extended to Scotland's national stadium extending
to more than #10million to date. Some #23 million has been awarded in grants to
projects in Scotland, costing in excess of #82million. Almost all grounds in
the premier division have built new stands, grant aided by the Football Trust.
The introduction of closed circuit television (CCTV) surveillance equipment at
grounds - pioneered and largely funded by the Trust - has proven the single,
most important measure in the campaign against football hooliganism in Scotland.
The Trust has now provided support for the upgrading of systems and the total
grant aid made available for CCTV at Scottish clubs now runs at more than
#1million. Support has also been extended to the development of women's
football in Scotland.
The future is clouded due to the serious impact on the funds transferring to
the Trust from the pools companies.
The introduction of the National Lottery, and its domination of the long-odds
betting market, has had a serious effect of the Trust's income. The pools are
the game's largest source of external funding (around #45million a year) and
football has been the country's largest lottery loser by far.
Almost all the Trust's resources depend on the prosperity of the pools
companies and on the generosity of the Government. The 35% decline in our
income has forced a reassessment of grant aid policy. Future efforts must be
concentrated on the core activities of Taylor-related work and in helping areas
ineligible for lottery funding.
Football needs the pools to be able to compete successfully against the
lottery, and trustees are supporting all steps to ensure that fair competition
is secured.
It is essential that income is sufficient to implement Taylor throughout the
leagues and that the Trust can continue to make its vital contribution to
Scottish football at every level.
</TEXT>
