<FLAG>business comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974995540</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BLUE Circle is yet another major company rueing the heady days of the 1980s
when diversification from mundane core activities was all the rage.
In this case, the cement giant bought both Armitage Shanks and Birmid Qualcast
and then went on an ill-fated European tour three years ago - the Celius
heating business in France, bought for #206m was not its most sage acquisition.
In September, chief executive Keith Orrell-Jones said that there would be a
fundamental review of the activity, named ``creation of cost effective centres
of excellence'' although the hit will be a #55m charge against this year's
profits.
The plan is to produce in the lowest cost territory for the particular product,
which means Potterton boilers will remain in the UK while oil fired boilers
will be concentrated in France.
Certainly something had to be done. In the first half, the division made losses
of #1m on turnover of #290m and capital employed totalling some #600m.
The bathrooms side has been a somewhat happier story although that is carrying
an #8m exceptional charge for its reorganisation. It is good, high margin stuff
which will benefit even more from the #40m to be spent over the next three
years.
Finance director James Loudon dismissed a suggestion that all this was simply
the sprucing up of the two activities prior to a flotation. He said that the
costs savings next year would be #25m, a sizable improvement on the current
year's likely group pre-tax outturn expected to be around #270m. The write-down
of #63m in all will be substantially met by a #55m profit on a landfill sale.
BCI has partially met City demands for the heating division, but it should
think again on a sale as its performance in cement has been faultless and why
dilute that.
</TEXT>
