<HEADLINE>Club or districts debate takes another twist Stirling County president calls summit of top sides</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995541</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nowhere man: Swansea's Flowers is caught by two Castres defenders during the
European Cup quarter-final tie which turned ugly.
THE top 10 clubs in Scotland are to stage a summit meeting in an effort to
thrash out a consensus on whether clubs or districts will represent Scotland in
next year's European Cup competition.
The initiative for the meeting - to take place at Meggetland on Wednesday - has
come from defending champions Stirling County who have made no secret of the
fact that they back clubs in the European tournament which is currently
underway but which awaits the appearance of representatives from Scotland and
England next season.
The tournament, which will climax in a final at Cardiff Arms Park on January 7,
has been backed by ITV and sponsors Heineken to the tune of #20m for the first
three years.
The 12 teams taking part this season are each expected to bank at least
#100,000 on top of their gate receipts.
It is against that backdrop, with ambitious sides viewing the Euro cash as a
means of bankrolling their future in the professional game, that some clubs are
contesting the Scottish Rugby Union stance that district sides should represent
Scotland.
Coincidentally, this week Stirling County have been awarded #236,000 from the
national lottery to part finance a major ground development at Bridgehaugh. The
cash will be used to construct a sports hall, gymnasium, and upgrade
floodlighting. The project forms part of a wider #900,000 scheme that includes
refurbishment and extension to stand facilities.
The drive for club representation, although currently spearheaded by Stirling
County, is also backed by Watsonians and Melrose whose director of rugby Keith
Robertson delivered a pro-clubs presentation to a meeting of the South District
earlier this week. Others are still undecided but some are vehemently opposed.
SRU director of rugby Jim Telfer is a staunch advocate of the district route,
for the reason that he considers that only district combines would be strong
enough to compete. The fear, too, is that if three, or perhaps four, Scottish
clubs flew the saltire in Europe then they would act as a magnet for the
country's top players, creating an imbalance in the domestic game.
Stirling County president Bill Gibson has invited fellow presidents from
Melrose, Watsonians, Boroughmuir, Hawick, Heriot's FP, Edinburgh Academicals,
and Gala, plus promoted Jed-Forest and Currie, to the meeting which represents
a powerful caucus but it is by no means certain that the pro-clubs lobby will
prove victorious.
In any event the final decision rests not with them but with the SRU general
committee which will reach a decision once final fixture dates for next
season's are known.
Yesterday, Gibson said: ``The European situation has to be sorted out, and
soon. What we don't want is for the SRU to spring a decision on us without
notice.
``The game is changing dramatically and we have, for instance, sponsors to
consider and we have to know the way ahead quickly. I can see the reasons for
the SRU wanting districts in Europe but it is quite obvious to everybody that
the district championship isn't working just now.
``If the SRU has something to put in its place then they should be telling us
about it now. We want it to be clubs in Europe and others agree with us.
Hopefully, we can make a case for it with the other top clubs in Scotland but,
above all, we have to get clear guidance on what is happening on Europe and,
just as important, with what the league set-up next season is going to be.
``With sponsors to think of we can't wait for a decision until the SRU agm and
it is encumbent on the SRU to consult the clubs that will be most affected -
and that must be the top 10 clubs in the country - before they reach any
decision,'' he said.
</TEXT>
