<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hosie's worst fears realised after Swansea battle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995542</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FRENCH side Castres are facing a ban from the European Cup tournament after
their quarter-final with Swansea on Tuesday night when Scottish referee Chuck
Muir and touch-judges Andrew Clift and Rob Dickson were forced to call for
police protection, writes Derek Douglas.
The SRU is now awaiting a report from Muir and yesterday Scottish International
Board representative Alan Hosie said that the affair would be raised as a
matter of urgency with the tournament organisers.
Hosie, a former international referee, added that the scenes which disfigured
the Swansea game - won 22-10 by the Welshmen - appeared to be a sad vindication
of the fears he had voiced when the game turned professional three months ago.
``I'm on record as saying that the mix of money and the physical contact
aspects of rugby were a recipe for trouble. It frightened me then and it
frightens me now. I hope it turns out that my voice in the wilderness was a
stupid one but, one assumes, that the Castres players were being paid win
bonuses on Tuesday night. There was a lot at stake financially and initial
reports seem to indicate that mayhem ruled,'' he said.
Yesterday, Muir was maintaining a discrete silence other than to confirm that
he would be submitting a report to the SRU. However, eye witnesses spoke of
appalling scenes as players fought with each other and a Frenchman was sent off.
Later, Muir and his Scottish touch-judges were escorted off the pitch by police
and the constabularly was on hand, too, outside the officials' dressing-room
and at the after-match reception.
The European tournament, which is run under the banner of the Five Nations'
committee, but operated for tax purposes from Dublin under the stewardship of
IRFU administrators Tom Kiernan and Ken Reid, is in its first season and due to
be expanded next year with teams from Scotland and England taking part.
</TEXT>
