<DOCNO>GH951208-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Duncan back on the ball</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995543</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNCAN Ferguson repaid the faith shown in him by both his club and his adoring
fans with two second-half goals in Everton Reserves' 5-0 victory over Newcastle
Reserves last night.
The 23-year-old striker showed no ill-effects following his absence from
football including a 44-day spell at Barlinnie Prison and proved he has worked
hard to maintain and rebuild his fitness.
Despite the sub-zero temperature, 10,432 spectators were at Goodison Park for
his return to action, in a blue shirt. He was given a rapturous welcome by the
fans, accompanied by a rapidly assembled band of pipes and drums, for the
Pontins' League fixture.
Ferguson looked sharp in his first outing since August. After Vinnie Samways
scored twice and Mark Grugel added a third, it was Ferguson's first goal three
minutes after the interval that warmed the home crowd. Showing neat control
after collecting a cross from the right, Ferguson fired low into the corner of
the net from the edge of the area and calmly received the applause of his team
mates.
Ferguson, proving his stamina has been unaffected, scored his second seven
minutes from time. Manager Joe Royle must be tempted to pitch him into Monday's
live Sky fixture against West Ham United.
</TEXT>
