<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Juppe misses Franco-German summit to deal with escalating crisis at home Mediator called in to break strikes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PAUL TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995544</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris, Thursday
FRENCH Prime Minister Alain Juppe moved to break the deadlock in a crippling
14-day rail strike by naming a mediator today as hundreds of thousands of
public service strikers marched to demand an end to welfare reforms.
The strike has swelled into the worst labour crisis in a decade involving
electricity, gas, post, and telephone workers, and spread today to most of the
nation's one million teachers and some Air France and Air Inter state airline
staff.
Juppe cancelled plans to attend a Franco-German summit and chaired emergency
ministerial talks before appointing veteran economist Jean Matteoli, head of
the consultative Economic and Social Council, to mediate in the SNCF state
railway dispute.
``The government is putting in place everywhere the means for a real
consultation with all trade unions and professional organisations. The Prime
Minister has asked ministers to report to him on progress in this work at the
end of this week,'' government spokesman Alain Lamassoure told reporters.
However he again refused to use the term ``negotiations'', saying Labour
Minister Jacques Barrot would hold ``far-reaching discussions'' with trade
union leaders from Saturday.
Nor did he respond to an appeal by a key strike leader, Marc Blondel of Force
Ouvriere, for personal talks with Juppe instead of ``phoney consultations''
with junior ministers.
Rail unions said they would meet Matteoli but reaffirmed their demands that the
state contract, a government plan to streamline the heavily indebted railways,
must be dropped before they will return to work.
Juppe's office earlier denied rumours on German financial markets that the
premier had resigned in the crisis over austerity plans to prepare France for
European monetary union.
Civil Service Minister Dominique Perben said: ``The actual principle of reform
is absolutely non-negotiable.''
His ministry provided statistical proof that the strike was gaining ground. It
said 36.7% of the 2.2 million civil servants were on strike, compared to only
10% on Tuesday.
Snow and plunging temperatures in the Paris region added to the misery of
hundreds of thousands who walked to work or joined traffic jams that clogged a
total 210 miles of approach roads to the capital.
The transport mayhem intensified when stoppages by firefighters and Air France
and Air Inter cabin staff restricted flights at the two Paris airports, while
stoppages by some air traffic controllers added to the disruption.
Incoming flights were delayed by up to 90 minutes and departures by two to
three hours.
In Calais, striking railmen stopped Channel Tunnel trains to London and
Brussels for three hours by occupying a signal box.
Huge crowds joined protest marches in provincial cities, with some
demonstrators hanging or burning effigies of Juppe. Police said 40,000 turned
out in Toulouse, 35,000 in Bordeaux and Rouen, 30,000 in Marseilles and
Grenoble, 20,000 in Nice, 15,000 in Le Mans, Nantes, and Lyons.
In Paris, a crowd estimated by police at 16,000 and up to 60,000 by the
organisers marched through the Latin Quarter - a symbolic rallying point since
the May 1968 student-worker revolt - past the National Assembly, where MPs were
debating a law allowing Juppe to impose key welfare reforms by decree.
The Bank of France, some of whose staff joined the strike, gave the government
a small boost by shaving its key interest rate by 0.10% to 4.7%.
The unions, however, resisted efforts by Juppe to drive a wedge between rival
labour leaders and separate the health overhaul from the rail reform and the
issue of public service pensions.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
