<HEADLINE>Big changes on the way for Footsie</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995546</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN &amp; Colonial, the world's first investment trust, will finally ascend to
the FTSE 100 index later this month.
It will be the only conventional investment trust represented in the top
flight, which is already home to venture capital group 3i.
London-based Foreign &amp; Colonial's move into the Footsie is part of one of the
largest shake-ups of the Footsie since the index was established in 1984.
The first of the changes, decided by the FTSE Actuaries UK Indices Committee,
will occur on Monday.
Troubled international trading group Inchcape, which has slipped to 131st in
the UK market capitalisation league, will be replaced by the newly-floated
National Grid.
The power transmission group will be about the 50th-largest Footsie constituent.
A week later, printing, paper and packaging group Arjo Wiggins Appleton,
currency printer De La Rue, speciality retailer Sears, London Electricity, and
Midlands Electricity will be relegated to the FTSE Mid-250 index.
They will be replaced by Foreign &amp; Colonial, glass company Pilkington, the
revitalised Burton retailing group, catalogue stores group Argos, and
specialist engineering company Smiths Industries.
The changes find two former spin-offs from BAT Industries going in opposite
directions. Argos is on the way up, while Anglo-French company Arjo Wiggins
Appleton, which has plants in Aberdeen and Fort William, falls into the Mid-250.
Investment trusts are not a common sight in the top 100, with previous member
Globe Investment Trust having been taken over by the Coal Board pension fund.
Founded in 1868, Foreign &amp; Colonial is now an #1800m fund. It is somewhat
unusual in that it is more than 50%-owned by private shareholders.
Michael Hart, who has served the ``international general'' investment trust for
41 years and been its manager since 1969, has seen Foreign &amp; Colonial's efforts
to reach the Footsie delayed by the raft of privatisations in recent years.
He said yesterday: ``Obviously we are very pleased. It is something we had been
hoping would happen eventually.
The move into the Footsie should have a positive impact on Foreign &amp; Colonial's
share price because the stock will find its way into the portfolios of index
tracking funds.
Mr Hart said: ``The fact that we are now in the Footsie means that a lot more
people are going to have to take note of us. The index trackers are obviously
going to be interested and that certainly has implications for the share
price.''
He added that Foreign &amp; Colonial's objective back in 1868, to give the small
investor the same advantages as the large capitalist, remained the same 127
years later.
Inchcape's move into the Mid-250 will displace Renfrew-based engineering group
Howden, now a lowly 413th in the market capitalisation league.
Other changes at the bottom end of the Mid-250 will see the departure of
Glasgow-registered clothing group William Baird.
Shares in those companies exiting the Footsie were generally weaker, while the
prospective entrants hardened. Argos added 10p to 571p, with Inchcape off 6p on
211p.
q Expro, the offshore services group, has won over #5m of new contracts to
gather data from offshore wells in the North Sea.
The Reading-based company signed a three-year contract with Elf Enterprise
Caledonia and a two-year contract with Kerr McGee Oil to test offshore wells
and gather data from instruments lowered into them.
Expro's main operational base in the UK is in Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
