<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Charity undergoes a quiet revolution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>alison daniels</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995547</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FROM the road Quarrier's Village, once the Orphan Homes of Scotland, looks
unscathed by the years. The spire of Mount Zion church, the children's
cathedral, dominates the dip in the land west of Bridge of Weir. The stone
villas that once housed more than 30,000 destitute orphans from across Scotland
stand in pristine condition. The very air seems to have a tranquil, timeless
quality.
But walk through the village built in 1871 by William Quarrier, child beggar
from Greenock turned successful businessman and social pioneer, and the private
cars parked outside the former children's cottages are testimony to a dramatic
revision in this famous West of Scotland charity's ethos and approach.
Many of the homes that sheltered children under the care of a house mother and
father have been sold to private buyers along with some of the surrounding
land. Apart from a nationally renowned Epilepsy Centre, which provides
accommodation for up to 100 people, there are only two residential homes and a
respite centre for people with learning disabilities left in this
picture-postcard haven, 12 miles away from the problems of Glasgow.
But a century and a quarter later William Quarrier's vision of social justice
has not been dissipated with the orphans whose numbers dwindled in the 1970s
and 80s from a peak in the 1930s, but been reshaped and refocused.
Over the past three years Quarrier's has been in the process of a quiet
revolution. Tomorrow it launches what it hopes will be a high-profile,
year-long, fundraising campaign including numerous sponsored events, a Pro-am
golf match and the creation of a William Quarrier rose to mark its 125th
anniversary in 1996. At a dignitary-studded lunch in the centre of Glasgow its
chairman, Sir Graham Hills, will appeal for #250,000 to plough into new
homeless projects in Glasgow and signal the start of a renewed effort to raise
public awareness of the charity and redefine its image.
Strolling along the broad avenues which curve through the village the charity's
director, Gerald Lee, acknowledges that the process of change is a painful one
for an institution with an obvious pride in its past. Unlike organisations like
Barnardo's he says the charity was slow to embrace the changes in childcare in
the 1970s which saw the creation of small, specialist homes and community based
care for those disadvantaged groups falling through the statutory social work
net. In the 1980s Quarrier's found itself with its head buried in the sand.
Lee joined Quarrier's three years ago with a social services background and a
zeal to provide the best professional care possible. As he talked about the
charity's projects, which range from a support service to people with
disabilities in Glasgow's Drumchapel housing scheme to a residential school for
children with serious behavioural problems, he said the reality is that
charities must operate like businesses, competing both for public, private, and
now lottery funding as well as local authority sanction to run services.
With residents in the charity's projects described as ``discerning services
users'', there has been considerable effort made to introduce staff development
programmes and improve the level of expertise. Lee says with the advent of care
in the community Quarrier's faces the dual challenge of working with the
statutory authorities to plug the gaps as well as fighting to set its own
agenda.
It is a challenge that Lee says is now being met. While other agencies have
found that the ``community'' is not all it is cracked up to be - one recent
study describing the not-in-my-backyard culture as one characterised by
hostility and in some cases violence - Lee says Quarrier's community based
projects have escaped such resentment. He points to the award-winning Larkfield
Family Centre in Greenock which offers family and child-care support and the
rural youth project in Argyll, both of which have attracted only praise.
However, the main thrust of Quarrier's work this year has been in the
homelessness field taking the organisation full circle and back tackling the
problems on the streets of Glasgow. Last Friday the organisation opened a
long-stay housing project in the South Side of Glasgow to accommodate 39 young
people aged between 18 and 25 for up to two years. Based in a converted church
leased from the city council, the James Shield project allows residents to live
independently but offers 24-hour advice and support if needed.
In February Quarrier's also took over the running of Glasgow City Council's
Stopover project after urban aid funding ran out. The project has an open-door
policy providing emergency accommodation for those deemed too problematic by
other hostels in the city. Lee is keen to hold it up as an example of
Quarrier's future direction.
It is hard to find fault. Yesterday the Pollokshaws Road hostel witnessed its
usual comings and goings. A guy with a rucksack left with his mate and a
confident ``see ya''. A girl arrived at the door with a small shiny green
rucksack and a couple of carrier bags in her arms saying she has an
appointment. If she's lucky she might get a place. The hostel could be filled
three times over with 73% of referrals having to be turned down on grounds of
space.
Answering questions in a polite, quiet voice, David Steele, 23, describes the
series of traumatic circumstances which led him to an 11-week stay at the
hostel. In May he left his home in Kilmarnock after his father died. Initially
he went to live with his older sister but she has now gone to Manchester
leaving David to drift to Glasgow. He tells of a night in a city centre hostel
which left him feeling frightened ``because of the drugs''.
He misses his father and would like, one day, his own house, but he is full of
praise for his ``keyworker'' who sorted out a more permanent home. Glad to feel
safe and having made some friends he has just moved 100 yards down the road to
his own self-catering room in the James Shield project.
He is a Quarrier's success. Others leave Stopover to a more uncertain future
but the project's leader, Ian Hughes, is clear that the charity's approach is
one of the better solutions to the city's homeless problem, offering safety to
some of the most vulnerable young people.
</TEXT>
