<DOCNO>GH951208-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chief Minister primed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995548</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHIEF Minister goes in the pursuit of big money at Cheltenham tomorrow when he
takes on some of the finest hurdlers in the country in the #35,000 Bonusphoto
Bula Hurdle.
His participation was confirmed yesterday by Invergowrie trainer Tom Dyer after
it was learned that the favourite, Large Action, runner-up in the Champion
Hurdle and last year's winner of the Bula, had suffered a serious leg injury
and will not run again this season.
``We were intending to run the Chief anyway because he is in great form at
present, but the unfortunate injury to Oliver Sherwood's star, makes it even
more necessary that we should get involved,'' he explained.
Chief Minister has already earned #11,000 this season by taking on top company.
He was third to Lonesome Train, giving loads of weight, in a valuable handicap
at Cheltenham in mid-November and two weeks later finished a half-length second
to Padre Mio in the Grade Two #30,000 Fighting Fifth Hurdle at Newcastle, when
15-8 favourite.
Tomorrow, he races against Atours, Mysilv, and Mole Board, who all ran in the
Champion Hurdle, and Morley Street, the 1991 champion, who is making a comeback
from ``retirement''.
``He is in such good fettle just now we must try him against those guys.
"We realise that Mysilv and Atours will be difficult to beat but we are
definitely not going to Cheltenham to be last,'' said the Invergowrie trainer.
``My horse is improving and he will give them all a race.''
Front-running Mysilv is guaranteed to set a strong pace and if Chief Minister
comes with his normal late burst it could be between the Scottish horse and the
fast-finishing Atours.
Jockey Peter Hobbs will be partnering Chief Minister for the last time as he
retires in January. Dyer has not yet decided on a replacement.
Owned by Berwick businessman Graham Shiel, the son of Rainbow Quest has won
more than #47,000 in hurdle races and gave Dyer his biggest successs in May
when successful in the Swinton Hurdle at Haydock, beating Eurolink The Lad by
three lengths.
</TEXT>
