<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SFA set a new code for fines</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995549</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish FA has unveiled a new approach in the hope that managers will be
involved less in after-match comments which lead them into trouble. And
although two premier division managers have been fined, they do not need to
take out the cheque books just yet. The fines have been suspended subject to
the managers not committing the same type of offence over the next 12 months.
Raith Rovers manager Jimmy Nicholl has been fined #400 by the general purposes
committee because of his criticism of Celtic after a match between the clubs on
August 31. Motherwell's Alex McLeish has been fined #100 because he criticised
the referee after the meeting with Falkirk on September 23. In addition McLeish
was also censured because of his after-match comments about the referee who
took charge of the European tie against Mypa.
Kilmarnock`s Alex Totten was severely censured because of comments following
the match against Rangers on August 26, and Airdrie's Alex MacDonald was also
censured for his comments following a match against Dundee on October 28.
Players warned were:
Peter Grant (Celtic) for criticism of Raith Rovers (after game on August 31); a
second appearance meant a censure for criticism of the referee against Hearts
(September 23). Wayne Foster (Partick Thistle) for after match comments v
Hearts (September 16)
q THE SFA yesterday received an appeal from Dumbarton against the five-match
ban imposed on keeper Ian McFarlane who was given two red cards for the one
incident involving Airdrie striker Jim McIntyre. It means that McFarlane will
have to sit out eight matches.
Meanwhile, McFarlane is now free to play while the appeal is heard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>US points way for Compass</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995550</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOOD service and private healthcare group Compass turned in a robust
performance in the year to October, helped by better-than-expected trading in
its US operations.
Profits in the US business rose by 23%, benefiting from a combination of
factors including the elimination of loss-making contracts and improved cost
control.
UK catering profits rose by 13.5% to #32.5m and margins improved to 7.1%
despite a move into lower margin publiic sector catering.
The group's portfolio of UK foodservice brands, some owned and others
franchised, includes Burger King, Pizza Hut, Upper Crust and Cafe Select,
operating within UK railway stations. Its UK catering businesses include
Travellers Fare, primarily at UK railway stations and Letheby &amp; Christopher,
the social, sporting and corporate caterer.
Profits also rose in Europe, but margins were squeezed. This was because of a
large contract renewal in Norway at slightly reduced margins and the full-year
impact of two small acquisitions operating at lower margins.
Given the strong growth potential in its catering operations worldwide, it is
not surprising that Compass has decided to sell its healthcare business. This
consists of 15 acute care private hospitals and two nursing homes mostly in
southern England, making Compass the UK's fourth largest provider of acute care.
No figures were disclosed for the healthcare business' performance, but in 1994
it increased profits by 10% to #14.4m, with turnover up by a similar amount to
#66.7m. Negotiations are taking place on the sale of the business, which
increased its annual sales and profits and is expected to fetch around #180m.
The proceeds will be used to make bolt-on acquisitions, although Compass is
already the largest European-owned catering group and the third largest
foodservice group in the world.
Commenting on the full year performance Compass' chief executive Francis MacKay
said he had great confidence in being able to achieve continued growth. The
confident trading statement saw Compass shares add 4!sp to 450!sp.
