<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dons' free offer for fans' loyalty</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995552</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN will hand their supporters an early Christmas present with free
entrance to Pittodrie when their abandoned game against Kilmarnock is replayed
next Wednesday night. A power cut forced the police to call off the fixture
after 57 minutes at Pittodrie on Wednesday night.
The sides were level at 1-1 so neither team suffers and Aberdeen have decided
there should be no financial penalty either. Chairman Ian Donald said:
``Despite the fact that Wednesday's power failure was totally out of the club's
control, we feel that the additional game offers the club the opportunity to
thank the fans for the tremendous support they have shown over past few
months.''
Kilmarnock's board of directors already have agreed to pay for their
supporters' bus fares for the long trek in midweek.
Meanwhile, Aberdeen defender Brian Irvine will complete a miraculous recovery
tomorrow when he starts his first game for Aberdeen since his multiple
sclerosis was diagnosed seven months ago.
The defender will return against Motherwell at Pittodrie to prove he has won a
fight against the odds. Irvine came off the bench on Wednesday night against
Kilmarnock to replace John Inglis, but the floodlight failure limited his
appearance to a matter of seconds.
Dutch keeper Theo Snelders is fit to return against Motherwell, but striker
Scott Booth is again out.
Manager Roy Aitken said yesterday: ``Brian has waited patiently for his chance
which looks as if it will come on Saturday. Inglis has damaged a hamstring, and
I'm sure Brian will relish the opportunity to complete his comeback.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>European final set for Ibrox</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995553</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IBROX has been chosen to host this season's European Cup-winners' Cup final on
May 8, according to an unconfirmed report by the the Italian news agency ANSA.
The last European final to be staged in Scotland was Dundee United v
Gothenburg, a UEFA Cup two-legged final in 1987, and the last time Scotland was
used for a neutral-venue European final was the 1976 European Cup, when Bayern
Munich beat St Etienne of France at Hampden Park.
Ibrox is on an approved UEFA list of 16 possible venues for major finals. Work
is currently under way on seating the corners of the stand to take the capacity
to above 50,000. That work is scheduled to be completed by the end of the
season.
The Dutch city of Rotterdam is reported to be the back-up host venue for the
final.
ANSA also reported that UEFA had decided on Rome's Olympic Stadium as the
location for the European Cup final on May 22.
UEFA have not yet officially confirmed the venues. Both decisions would be
subject to ratification by UEFA's executive committee when it meets in
Birmingham next Friday.
q MARK McGhee's appointment as Wolves' manager could be delayed while the storm
over his controversial departure from Leicester yesterday blows itself out.
McGhee went to ground after he angered Leicester by rejecting a huge increase
in salary and walked out along with No.2 Colin Lee and coach Mike Hickman. The
silence from Molineux was deafening and Wolves may delay an announcement until
after Sunday's trip to Luton.
``If he goes to Wolves I hope they get relegated,'' said Leicester captain
Steve Walsh. ``All the players are upset. They want to prove to Mark that what
he's done is wrong. We feel that what's happened is a disgrace.''
McGhee turned down a king's ransom, apparently for Wolves' gold. Leicester
chairman Martin George even questioned his own sanity after offering to
catapult McGhee into the ranks of England's top five best-paid managers.
The 38-year-old Scot is believed to have been offered an extra #1000 a week to
stay at Filbert Street.
George applied for a High Court injunction in an attempt to stop Brian Little
joining Aston Villa a year ago. Now another court battle looms.
q THE European Court of Justice will announce their final decision on the
Jean-Marc Bosman transfer system case in Brussels next Friday, according to a
court official.
The transfer market faces collapse if the court follows the recommendation in
September by one of their chief legal advisers, court advocate general Carl
Otto Lenz, that they should declare the system and its limits on foreign
players illegal.
Such a verdict could wipe fortunes off the value of big name clubs like
Manchester United and Liverpool, rendering their star assets worthless, while
ruining smaller ones.
Belgian Bosman argues professional footballers in European Union countries are
entitled to the same freedom of movement enjoyed by other workers. His case
started in 1990 when a transfer from Belgium's FC Liege to Dunkirk in France
was blocked by Liege.
Yesterday's results
Premier Reserve League - Hearts 5, Rangers 1.
BP Youth Cup - Partick Thistle 0, Aberdeen 2 (Derek Young, Darren Young).
</TEXT>
