<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Injured Sampras forced to pull out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995554</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WIMBLEDON champion Pete Sampras pulled out of the Grand Slam Cup in Munich last
night because of a knee injury - dashing German fans' hopes of a final showdown
between the American world No.1 and local hero Boris Becker.
Sampras, who was forced to withdraw from his quarter-final against Goran
Ivanisevic today because of a knee injury, will now need intensive treatment to
be fit for next month's Australian Open.
``Today, I woke up and I could not stretch the knee,'' said Sampras. ``I have
just had a test and there is fluid behind the knee.
``I'll go home to try to rest, recover, and do all I can to get fit. I didn't
want the year to end like this.''
Becker, who won the ATP Tour world championship last month, now has a superb
chance to pick up the most lucrative prize in the game.
Playing just 10 minutes' drive from his Munich home, the German had few
problems reaching the semi-finals, cruising past Zimbabwe's Byron Black.
Becker clinched the first-set tie-break 7-1 thanks to some superb serving, and
with an early break in the second set, raced to victory in 76 minutes by 7-6,
6-1.
He will now face America's Todd Martin, who reached the last four after Andrei
Medvedev retired hurt from their quarter-final with the score at 6-3, 3-6, 4-0,
in favour of the American.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Four held hostage in bank</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995555</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MUNICH: A woman customer escaped unhurt from an armed man who was holding three
other people hostage in a Munich bank yesterday.
A police spokesman said the hostage taker had broken off negotiations. ``We are
now at a critical moment,'' he said.
The man had earlier released one captive who had heart trouble, but demanded
DM4m (#1.8m) for the safe return of the others.
Police said the man, who was believed to be armed with a handgun, was also
demanding a car in return for the hostages' release. Officers sealed off the
area and surrounded the building in Munich city centre.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Top-class restaurant with a French flavour</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill McLean</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995556</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LA Bonne Auberge, the bar and brasserie on the ground floor of Glasgow's newly
opened Holiday Inn Garden Court Hotel has much to offer end of the year
revellers with Christmas in the offing and New Year not far behind. There is a
three courses, coffee and mints lunch and dinner menu for #15.95 from Monday
December 11 until Sunday, December 24. There is also a slap-up five-course
dinner with a glass of champagne to bring in the New Year for #39.95 on
Hogmanay.
A special room rate of #25 per person, sharing, inclusive of full Scottish
breakfast is available on that celebratory occasion. The complete Hogmanay and
after experience inclusive of dinner, bed and breakfast can be booked for
#61.50 per head. Telephone 0141 427 4706 for reservations.
Maurice Taylor is no stranger to the culinary arts, having toiled at the Tour
d'Argent in Paris as the duck waiter, a pressing task. His love of good food is
reflected in his choice of head chef Gerard Sharkey to take charge of the
kitchen brigade. The brigadier Gerard has worked in some of the city's top
restaurants and hotels and has won three gold medals, one silver, and one
bronze in national competitions.
The philosophy behind La Bonne Auberge is quite simply to offer diners with a
cosmopolitan taste the opportunity to sample authentic French dishes at
reasonable prices in truly European surroundings. To this end the menu offers
starters such as French onion soup scented with port and terrine of roast ham
and chicken on a celeriac and snow pea salad with honey and ginger dressing and
main courses such as sauteed wood pigeon with creamed spinach in a light pastry
case on red wine essence and char-grilled calf liver with mustard and garlic
sauce plus polenta and rosemary.
The wine list is moderately priced and carefully selected with the old and the
new worlds represented. France, Germany, Italy and Spain vie with Australia,
California, Chile, New Zealand and South Africa for thirst attention. Nautilus
Cuvee Marlboro, a brut sparkler from the Antipodes, is well worth a try.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gingrich affairs sent to counsel</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995557</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Thursday
THE House Ethics Committee has recommended the appointment of a special counsel
to look into the dealings of the Speaker, Newt Gingrich.
He was charged with violating the rules in nine matters, but only one is to be
referred to the counsel. The Speaker claims this amounts to vindication.
The committee vindicated him on three questions, found that he had violated the
rules in three others but recommended that no action be taken, and declined to
consider the other two.
The counsel will consider the allegation that Mr Gingrich used money
contributed to a political action committee called GOPAC to subsidise a course
he tought at a small college in Georgia. That would amount to diverting
political money to his personal use.
The independent counsel may decide that his remit is too narrow, and ask the
House to expand it to cover other matters.
That is what happened to an earlier Speaker, Jim Wright. He was eventually
forced to resign after Newt Gingrich, then a relatively junior back bencher,
persuaded the House to appoint a special counsel to look into a book deal. He
widened his investigation and eventually brought the Speaker down.
The matters on which Mr was cleared included his acceptance of a #3m book
advance from HarperCollins. The committee said this had the appearance of
selling his office for money but, because he renounced the advance when a
public outcry ensued, the appearance never became real.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New hotel has continental style</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill McLean</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995558</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Holiday Inn Garden Court at 161 West Nile Street is Glasgow's newest hotel.
Situated diagonally across from the city's Royal Concert Hall and within sight
of the Pavilion, it opened its doors at the beginning of the week in the heart
of aptly entitled Theatreland, giving the famous Holiday Inn name back to the
West of Scotland.
Owner/entrepreneur Maurice Taylor, who rose from being a summer night porter at
Turnberry to become a well-known local millionaire hotelier, is the man
responsible for the #4m, 80-bedroom, prestige project franchise operation which
brings twenty-first century standards to the world of today.
By skilful use of advance technology, the new Glasgow hotel is the first
Holiday Inn in Britain to have an interface with the corporate headquarters in
Atlanta, Georgia, via a satellite link in the car park.
At any one time the state of room availability is known throughout the network.
Internally, staff - at the touch of a button - can communicate information or
see problems as soon as they arise on a television monitor, leading to better
and more efficient service.
General manager Tony Wright is the ideal person to have in charge. He has
abundant experience of the hotel trade, has travelled extensively abroad
picking up management tips along the way and, most important, has worked for
Holiday Inns in the UK.
A year ago he was senior duty manager at the Holiday Inn, Heathrow, and before
coming to Glasgow was at the world's first Holiday Inn Garden Court in
Warrington. His help during the planning stages has proved invaluable.
It is no secret that Maurice Taylor is a Francophile with an eye for good
design. From the outside the Holiday Inn Garden Court, with its blond sandstone
facade, imposing clock tower and royal blue canopies above every ground floor
window, looks continental.
It would not be out of place on the Rue de Rivoli, but is built in fact on the
site of the nineteenth-century Bell's Quarry.
Through the hotel doors there is very much an Auld Alliance feel to the stylish
open-plan interior. Mr Taylor, Ron McCulloch, and his senior designer Claire
Kinna, have effected a European fin de siecle look in keeping with Glasgow's
art nouveau past.
The top of the reception desk is covered in black Ballachulish slate, a
technicolor, Tiffany-style cupola catches the eye in the entrance hall, and
metal work in the manner of Belgium's Victor Horta by Andy Scott contributes to
the imaginative EC concept.
Scottish firms and craftsmen were used wherever possible. Balfour Beattie,
Paisley, were the main contractors who brought the hotel in ahead of time - it
was not due to open until the New Year.
The principle architects were Glasgow's Cobban &amp; Lironi, furniture was
specially commissioned from Robert Morris Furnishings, of Castlemilk, and all
toilet pods were manufactured by Farquhar of Huntly, Aberdeenshire. Toilet pods
are essential to fast-track building where all bathroom and toilet facilities
come ready assembled in one piece.
In keeping with today's health-conscious trends, the top floor is the only
designated smoking floor. The remaining three are smoke free, with smoke
detectors and fire alarms in every room. All rooms are furnished and fitted to
Holiday Inn's exacting standards, including wall-hanging frames for unfolded
executive suit carriers and a special socket for laptop PC users.
Every room is equipped with trouser presses and hairdryers but rooms on the
third floor contain irons and ironing boards as well - a must for business
travellers.
Limed green oak and rag-rubbed aquamarine wallpaper have been used to pleasing
effect.
Direct dial telephones, remote control colour televisions with satellite and
in-house movies, and tea and coffee making facilities are standard. There is
only one price per room. The accommodation tarriff is #58.75 for a single,
double or twin room, with a #45 Friday to Sunday weekend rate inclusive of full
Scottish breakfasts.
There are facilities for the disabled. To cater for the important small
conference, commercial presentation and seminar market, the ground floor
Montmartre and Pigalle eating rooms are available, complete with Holiday Inn's
custom designed survival kits for organisers who may have left something
essential at home.
Prices for daily delegates are based on a minimum of 10 persons.
La Bonne Auberge brasserie and bar is a revival of Maurice Taylor's first wine
bar and restaurant which he opened in 1975 in the Park area of town.
From that period, the original metal sculpture of a Sommelier bearing a goblet
filled tray and the French Tricolour stand invitingly at the entrance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Irish girl goes to White House</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974995559</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WASHINGTON: Catherine Hamill, the nine-year-old who won President Bill
Clinton's heart during his visit to Northern Ireland last week, received a
red-carpet welcome to the White House last night, where she joined him in
lighting the Christmas tree.
Catherine moved the president by speaking in Belfast of the death her father in
the troubles. However when asked how she liked being in the limelight, she
said: ``I'm sick of it,'' adding that she was keen to go back to school.
Army kills Hutus
BUJUMBURA: Twenty-six people were killed when the Tutsi-led army attacked rebel
Hutu strongholds in Bujumbura, the capital of Burundi, on Wednesday. More than
100,000 people have died in ethnic violence in the past two years in Burundi,
whose volatile ethnic make-up is similar to that which led to civil war and
genocide in neighbouring Rwanda.
Mubarak wins
CAIRO: The Egyptian ruling party won an overwhelming parliamentary majority in
violent and dirty elections in which at least 28 people were killed and armed
thugs roamed the countryside. The National Democratic Party of President Hosni
Mubarak won 317 of the 444 seats at stake in the two rounds of voting, which
opposition parties claim were rigged.
Plane crashes
MOSCOW: The search resumes today for a Russian plane which crashed with 97
people on board while flying from Sakhalin Island to the far eastern town of
Khabarovsk. It disappeared from radar screens on Wednesday, reviving concern
about air safety in the former Soviet Union.
Leader to speak
ATHENS: Ailing Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou will be able to speak
for the first time in 11 days after a tracheotomy operation, his spokesman
said. Papandreou, 76, who has been in hospital since November 20 with lung and
kidney failure, has been kept alive on life-support systems. His ability to
speak will influence calls to elect a new leader.
Peak crumbles
PLYMOUTH: Rocks began to tumble from the rumbling volcano on the Caribbean
island of Montserrat yesterday and residents were warned to stay out of danger
zones. Last week some 4000 residents were evacuated as the growing lava dome
threatened rock slides and lava flows.
Polls policed
MOSCOW: Thousands of armed police will fan out across cities in Russia next
week at the start of a huge security operation to prevent violence disrupting
the December 17 election. Security has been stepped up because of the Chechen
confict and an upsurge in bombings, hijacks, and contract killings.
Blast kills 10
GENEVA: At least 10 people, including two United Nations guards, were killed
and 30 injured yesterday when a fuel tanker exploded in northern Iraq. The two
dead guards, a Pole and a Filipino, were helping to patrol Kurdish areas.
Tigers' plan
COLOMBO: Sri Lanka's Tamil Tiger rebels, defeated in their northern rebel base
of Jaffna, said they now planned to attack army-held areas in the north and
east.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
