<HEADLINE>Russell inspires another recovery</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995560</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JACK Russell found himself back in the old routine as England's leading batsmen
again surrendered their wickets all too easily. On Monday, Russell kept Mike
Atherton company for four-and-a-half hours while the second Test was saved
against the odds.
And yesterday, the Gloucestershire wicketkeeper breathed new life into another
England innings that was disintegrating though lack of care and attention.
Three hours of diligence on a slow, low pitch brought 45 unbeaten runs which
led the tourists to a more respectable 263 for eight against Boland.
With Atherton resting after his Johannesburg heroics, the opening pairing of
Alec Stewart and Robin Smith made a useful start before they and England's top
order were prised out.
Stewart, Smith, Graham Thorpe, Graeme Hick, and Mike Watkinson all made decent
starts but were then out. In fact, the only front-line batsman who failed to
reach double figures was, almost inevitably, John Crawley,who looks certain to
replace Mark Ramprakash when the Test series resumes in Durban next week.
