<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stargazers rejoice as Galileo phones home from Jupiter</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995561</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Pasadena, Thursday
A PROBE from the spacecraft Galileo successfully entered the atmosphere of the
planet Jupiter today to embark on a journey to the beginning of time.
The Galileo control room burst into joyful clapping as a technician yelled:
``We got it'', confirming that Galileo had linked up with the space probe as it
entered the Jovian atmosphere.
The announcement was followed by cries of ``All right''.
Torrance Johnson, a scientist who has been with the project since it started in
1977, said: ``This is a fantastic achievement just in the complexity of the
engineering; the probe flying on its own, slamming itself into the atmosphere,
protecting itself with its heat shield, and then phoning home.''
Johnson called it a ``major step closer to the beginning of time''.
Jupiter contains the same gases as the Sun and scientists hope data sent by the
probe to its mother ship will help them to learn how the solar system began and
subsequently evolved.
After a 2.3-billion-mile journey, the unmanned probe was the first space
vehicle to enter the giant planet's turbulent atmosphere.
For 75 minutes, Galileo will transmit data back to Earth which should vastly
increase our knowledge about one of the strangest places in the solar system.
Mission controllers had to manoeuvre the cone-shaped, 746lb probe into
Jupiter's atmosphere at exactly the right angle.
If they had failed, the craft would have been bounced into oblivion or
destroyed in a fireball.
Atmospheric physicist Professor Fred Taylor, head of the only British
scientific team involved in the #1bn mission, was watching events closely. He
is waiting to receive information from the spacecraft relayed to Oxford
University from the mission control centre in Pasadena, California.
Professor Taylor said: ``Jupiter is a closed book at the moment. Galileo should
tell us much more than we have been able to learn from telescopes and other
spacecraft that have flown past the planet.''
Professor Taylor will be studying Jupiter's strange atmospheric bands and the
giant red spot which can be seen from the Earth.
He will also be looking at the 300mph Jovian winds, as well as the planet's
raging hurricanes - some of them bigger than the Earth - and terrifying
lightning storms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kohl and Chirac warn Britain</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995562</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Baden-Baden, Thursday
GERMAN Chancellor Helmut Kohl and French President Jacques Chirac warned today
that individual European Union members should not be allowed to block others on
the path to further integration.
In a letter to the EU summit next week in Madrid, the two said their countries
remained committed to forming a single EU currency ``according to the agreed
timetable and the meeting of the agreed criteria''.
The letter, issued at the end of their six-monthly summit, said: ``We want all
members to be able to take equal part in the progress of European integration
in the expanded Union.
``But the occasional problems of a partner in keeping pace should not be
allowed to limit the Union's capacity to act and make progress.''
Germany and France, whose summmits often set the tone for further EU policy,
therefore wanted a clause written into the EU treaty saying groups of members
could agree to further integration ``within the institutional framework of the
Union''.
The letter, a clear signal to countries like Britain which have opposed many
suggestions from Bonn and Paris for further integration, also listed four goals
for the Intergovernmental Conference opening next year to review the Maastricht
Treaty.
They were a better co-ordinated EU foreign and security policy, common
guidelines on asylum and immigration, introduction of qualified majority voting
in the EU, and a greater role for the European and national parliaments in
communty decision-making.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stately progress of monolith</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995563</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARKET fears that major provisions would hit GEC's results proved unfounded and
analysts were generally satisfied with the figures. Not that the trading
position is exercising minds at present.
GEC is such a monolith and its businesses deal in such long, long timescales
that it takes a lot to shift it from its stately progress.
What interests the market is the management succession. At the end of the
1993/94 financial year, Lord Weinstock, the legendary managing director,
announced he was extending his tenure by two years. So far, no likely successor
has emerged but it is clear that chairman Lord Prior is considering a
short-list and that an announcement will be made next spring.
Assuming someone of sufficient stature is appointed, Lord Weinstock's successor
is likely to take quite a different view of the business. The group has never
captured the imagination of the City which sees it as worthy,
ultra-conservatively managed and dull.
Shareholders can await the outcome with equanimity. The prospect of change will
maintain interest in the shares which are worth their current level on trading
grounds alone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ROADSHOW The new Rover 200 What's a nice grille like you doing in a place like this?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>ROAD TESTS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995564</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROVER has provided a few surprises in its new 200, writes ROSS FINLAY. While
the previous model shared the same platform as the 400, from now on each of the
two ranges has its own individual base. As a result, the 200 is smaller than
some people were expecting; and Rover is quite open about the fact that, as
with several of its cars, this one is in the showrooms at a premium price.
Well-rounded three- or five-door bodywork gives the new model a deliberately
sporting appearance, and continues the theme of using a ``family'' grille at
the front. This looks really good on the 800, but as the cars are scaled down
the grille is less able to play a strong part in the styling. On the 200, it is
all but overwhelmed by the air intake under the bumper.
Rover's exterior finish is among the best in the industry, and the 200 is
another model with a well-presented interior. The company takes great pains
over its trim patterns and materials. Velour upholstery is used in some
versions, while leather is an option at the top of the range.
On the mechanical front, the 200 has an unexpectedly wide choice of engines.
There are four types of the K-series unit, from 8-valve and 16-valve versions
of the 1.4-litre, to a 16-valve 1.6 and - available later - the 1.8-litre VVC
which was first used in the MGF. Rover is also pushing its own series turbo
diesel engine, which is available in the 200, either in 105bhp form with
electronic control, an intercooler and exhaust gas recirculation, or in a
simpler and lower-cost specification giving 86bhp.
Whatever the power unit installed, all the 200 models have advanced engine
mounting systems as part of the campaign against noise and vibration. The
suspension design is also sophisticated, and the intention is to present this
as an enthusiastic driver's car, with good stability at high cornering speeds.
Appearing when it does, the 200 raises questions about whether its design was
influenced by Honda or by BMW. The answer, firmly given, is neither. It was
planned without any Honda input or mechanical parts, and the project was
already well under way when the company changed ownership.
All 12 versions of the new car can be ordered now, although availability of the
various models is a phased-in affair. Prices start at #9995 for the three-door
214i. The top-rated petrol version is the five-door 216SLi at #13,895. Turbo
diesel prices go from #10,495 to #13,295, while the VVC-engined 200vi, for
later delivery, is expected to cost around #15,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unigate disposes of its 29% stake in Nutricia for #332m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995565</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNIGATE has sold its 29% stake in the Nutricia baby foods business in Holland
for #332m and a touch above its expectations when the intention to sell was
announced on November 15.
The deal was done through a bookbuilding exercise organised by SBC Warburg and
ABN AMRO Hoare Govett. They sold the stock to institutions at 120 guilders
compared with the 117 guilders after the offer announcement.
Unigate now has some #200m net cash which will almost certainly be used to make
acquisitions under the guiding hand of Ian Martin.
Mr Martin became chairman earlier this year, having previously worked for Grand
Metropolitan where he excelled in aquisitions such as Pillsbury which brought
Burger King into the group. There were also some disposals.
His Glenisla corporate finance company helped organise the Kohlberg, Kravis
Roberts #205m purchase of the Reed Regional Newspapers and it is believed that
Dundee-born Mr Martin is now looking to acquire a prestige, quality title.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Baby of an old family</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995566</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE latest Rover is the baby of a long, distinguished line. For, as well as
being the repository of a remarkable number of dormant marque names - Austin,
Morris, Riley, Wolseley, Standard, Triumph and the rest - Rover was very nearly
the pioneering British car manufacturer.
John Starley, maker of Rover cycles, built the first car in Coventry, later the
heartland of the British motor industry. Although it was a three-wheeled
electric affair rather than a four-wheeled petrol design, it was neater than
many of the square-rigged efforts then seen on the Continent. Thanks to the
stuffiness of the British authorities, Starley took his car to Deauville in
France for testing. It managed about eight miles per hour, very fair going for
1888, but he decided not to put it into production. His real interest was in
Rover cycles. Three years after his death in 1901, Starley and Co decided to
make the move into cars, and transferred the Rover name to them.
Early Rover cars were small ones of six or eight horsepower, though a 20hp job
won the 1907 Tourist Trophy. By the start of the Thirties, Rover was building
cars like the Light Six Sportsman's Saloon which hit the headlines by beating
the famous Blue Train from St Raphael to Calais.
Rover later specialised in distinguished-looking saloons. Then came an
astonishing diversion into gas turbine power, when Rover-BRM turbine cars raced
at Le Mans, although they needed drivers like Graham Hill to deal with the
colossal throttle lag.
And yet another surprise move followed - into rallying . . . first with the
Three-litre, better known as a government chauffeurs' car, then with a team of
too-hard-to-tune 2000s.
After a series of mergers in the Sixties, Rover found itself a minor component
of British Leyland. Under that regime, its individuality was crushed. It must
amuse old Solihull hands that when the modern, much better organised group
decided to rechristen itself, it chose the marque with the Norse galley badge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hendry, Higgins in Open semi-finals</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995567</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORLD champion Stephen Hendry completed his fifteenth successive victory in a
ranking tournament last night, reaching the semi-finals of the German Open in
Frankfurt with a 5-3 win against Rod Lawler.
Hendry, who has lost only one match this season, in the semi-finals of the
Thailand Open, took a 4-1 lead with breaks of 85, 67 and 51 - but still had a
fight on his hands.
Lawler narrowed the gap to 4-3 with runs of 44 and 77, but while Hendry
continued to give him chances, the 24-year-old world No.40 failed to force the
decider.
Hendry will meet Ken Doherty or Mark Bennett for a place in the final.
John Higgins earlier had booked his place in the semi-finals with a 5-4 victory
over Darren Morgan. The 20-year-old world No.11, now provisionally No.2 behind
Hendry, coasted to a 3-1 interval lead, helped by breaks of 82, 60 and 44. But
Morgan gradually warmed up to pinch the fifth frame on the black.
Higgins won the next and, with a 4-2 advantage, appeared set for a semi-final
showdown tomorrow with Alan McManus or David Roe. But Morgan fought back to 4-4
with breaks of 103 and 75. Morgan, though, missed a vital long blue in the
final frame and his opponent cleared up with 43.
q THE Belgian Masters, scheduled for next week, has been cancelled after
last-minute talks failed to bring about a compromise, following the omission of
two players in the top eight, James Wattana and Alan McManus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Champion of championships decelerates</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995568</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AT THE recent Scottish rally championship awards night, while David Gillanders
collected the main trophy as the 1995 champion, John Fife retired after 15
years as the championship co-ordinator, having helped to guide the 40-year-old
series through some of its finest seasons.
He will continue to report on events and contribute to the development of the
sport through the Scottish Motorsport Federation.
A true enthusiast who manages to conceal a businesslike and thoughtful approach
behind ebullient and sometimes pyrotechnic behaviour, John Fife drifted into
rallying almost by accident. His first competitions were grass-track races with
a Riley 1.5-engined Austin Metropolitan, of which people still ask: ``A what?''
Seeing the light, he moved on to an Austin-Healey 100/4 and later a 3000. With
these he started speed hill climbing and circuit racing, taking part in the
last climb at Rest and be Thankful and being blown off into the weeds by an AC
Cobra at Croft.
However, working with Shell and later with White Horse, he spent part of the
1970s involved with the oil company's sponsorship of the Scottish rally
championship, then helping to promote the works-supported White Horse team with
which Waugh's Avenger won its class in the British championship.
He started co-driving in rallies during that time, in a Colt Lancer driven by
his friend John Cleland, very much in the spotlight as winner of this year's
British Touring Car Championship. They also shared a course-opening car on one
rally in the Borders.
John Fife has admired three Scottish champions above all others - Drew
Gallacher, whose confidence and control at the wheel of the Wylies Escort meant
``there was nobody to touch him''; Ken Wood, who stayed faithful to BL
products, rallying at first a Mini and then a Triumph Dolomite Sprint, before
winning championships in three different cars, a Triumph TR7 V8, a Rover 3500,
and a Metro 6R4; and . . .
John's third driving hero is someone he knew in the days before the lad had his
own licence, when they were both part of a group which took trials bikes to an
unofficial off-road site near Braidwood.
John pretended he had persuaded his own bike up a steep banking. The youngster
decided to tackle it too. Despite some spoof Fife advice about technique, he
displayed incredible balance, and throttle control, forcing his bike to the top
of a banking which John had never actually got near to climbing.
Seeing this, John told himself: ``That kid's something special''. And so Colin
McRae, Scotland's first World Rally Champion, has turned out to be.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Attila's now a Saint</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995569</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ST JOHNSTONE yesterday paid Austrians FC Tirol #100,000 for midfield man Attila
Sekerleoglu, and manager Paul Sturrock wants to splash out another six-figure
fee on Coventry City winger, Leigh Jenkinson, in time to make it a double debut
in the Tayside derby with Dundee United at McDiarmid Park tomorrow.
Sturrock went straight from signing the Austrian into fresh talks with
Jenkinson and Saints hope that part of the twin signing will be completed
today. The Perth manager admits bringing in foreigners - Sekerleoglu is
believed to be the first Austrian to arrive in Scottish football - is always a
gamble. But he believes this one will pay handsome dividends.
The new Saint admitted he knows little about Scottish football, despite having
played for Austria Vienna against Hearts in a European tie several years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Serbs unmoved by threats over missing pilots</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KURT SCHORK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995570</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YUGOSLAVIA today rebuffed warnings by France of possible retaliation unless two
French pilots downed by Bosnian Serbs three months ago were freed, calling the
threats unacceptable and counterproductive.
The Foreign Ministry in Belgrade was responding to yesterday's warning by
French President Jacques Chirac to Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic that he
would ``draw all the appropriate conclusions'' if the two were not freed
rapidly.
However French officials made clear the fate of the pilots would not affect
next Thursday's signing in Paris of the Bosnia peace deal agreed in Dayton,
Ohio, in which Milosevic will be taking part.
Advance units of Nato troops who will enforce the deal are already in Bosnia to
prepare for the arrival of 60,000 due to pour in once the deal is signed.
And European and north American foreign ministers were meeting in Budapest
today to approve a plan for elections in Bosnia, a crucial pillar of the peace
deal dividing the country into Muslim-Croat and Serb halves.
Earlier today France hinted it might strike at the captors of the airmen shot
down during Nato air strikes against Bosnian Serbs in August, though giving no
direct indication that it knew who was holding them or where they were.
``The pilots must be freed immediately. If they are not, the consequences . . .
will strike those who are responsible for their detention and those who have
not respected their commitments,'' said Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques
Rummelhardt.
French Foreign Ministry sources said the word ``strike'' was a veiled threat of
force aimed partly at Milosevic, who has said he felt a personal responsibility
for the two airmen.
The Yugoslav Foreign Ministry issued a statement rejecting ``all tendentious
interpretations of the incident involving the two French pilots and attempts to
misuse it in order to exert pressure on, and make threats against, the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia''.
``The fact that efforts so far have not yielded the expected results do not in
any way bring into question Yugoslavia's sincere interest and readiness to
clear up this case,'' the ministry said.
The last official word on the pilots was on October 18, when Bosnian Serb
leader Radovan Karadzic said they had been captured and taken to hospital but
were later kidnapped by an unknown group, an explanation French officials
described as ``grotesque''.
Nato staged three abortive rescue missions for the two in September.
The French magazine VSD reported today that French secret services had located
the two near the Bosnian Serb headquarters at Pale, near Sarajevo, in a private
property owned by an officer close to Bosnian Serb army commander General Ratko
Mladic.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Title defence date for McCracken</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995571</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BIRMINGHAM'S Robert McCracken will make a first defence of his Commonwealth
middleweight title against Worcester's Paul Busby next month.
Unbeaten McCracken, who won the vacant crown by beating Canada's Fitzgerald
Bruney last month, will face Busby at the Aston Villa Leisure Centre on January
31.
Telford's European middleweight champion, Richie Woodhall, will make a defence
of his title on the same bill, but his opponent is not yet known.
Woodhall's manager Mickey Duff currently is in talks with German champion
Salvador Yanez, Russian title-holder Alexander Zaitsey, and French champion
Hassine Cherifi.
Duff said: ``This will be a great night of boxing with both Robert and Richie
on the bill.
``I'm sure that we will not have any trouble selling out the show and I hope to
be able to announce soon who Richie will be fighting.''
q FORMER British super-featherweight champion Floyd Havard will restore his
links with promoter Frank Warren in a deal that could see him once again fight
for a world crown.
The 30-year-old Swansea fighter launched his professional career a decade ago
under Warren's guidance and fought for the IBF title last year.
He was beaten in six rounds by Puerto Rican John-John Molina in Cardiff but
hopes that a new seven-fight agreement with Warren will carry him to a world
title shot next summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cash plus player deal likely Wieghorst poised for move to Celtic</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995572</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC, who are beginning to sense they could finally end Rangers' domination
of the premier division championship, were believed to have had talks yesterday
with Morten Wieghorst, who has not hidden his desire to take his career on to a
higher level.
Dundee manager Jim Duffy confirmed last night: ``There has been an inquiry from
Parkhead today for the player. At this stage it hasn't gone any further and we
will have to see what develops.''
The Danish internationalist has been operating with Dundee on a month-to-month
basis while hoping to secure a transfer and the prospect of a move to Celtic is
bound to excite him.
It is my understanding that Celtic, who were linked with another of Dundee's
players, Neil McCann, might offer a cash sum plus one of their emerging
players. A transfer fee and a new player represents a powerful lure to Dundee's
Jim Duffy, who has known for some time he would not be able to hold on to
Wieghorst.
The 24-year-old midfield player, who signed from Lyngby three years ago for
#220,000, is regarded as one of the most composed and gifted footballers
currently playing outside the premier division, but it just might be that Burns
has in mind a different role for the 6ft 3in player. Celtic already possess the
top division's most fluently effective midfield with players like Paul McStay,
John Collins, Peter Grant, and Phil O'Donnell, and Wieghorst might be deployed
in a deeper role at Celtic Park.
Celtic have missed the composure of Brian O'Neil, who has been unavailable
because of injury for a considerable period, originally a midfield player
himself who was dropped back and started to emerge as an influential defender.
Wieghorst is not the fastest midfield performer and Burns, who yesterday helped
launch a Christmas video for fans, ``The Celtic A-Z'', might just have
identified the potential value in having him play central defence.
The transfer may hinge on where Wieghorst believes he can best be utilised, but
Celtic offer a major opportunity and greater exposure which could only benefit
his international career.
Burns' side are pressing Rangers, who could lose the services briefly of Alan
McLaren who has been summoned to appear before the SFA, in pursuit of the title
and hope to make up further ground tomorrow when they play Hibernian at Easter
Road. The Edinburgh side will be without the suspended Michael O'Neill, but
Mickey Weir is ready to resume active duty.
Hibs have had serious problems because of injuries and suspensions this season
and manager, Alex Miller, suffered again yesterday when he learned strker
Gareth Evans will miss the Boxing Day game against Partick Thistle because of a
one-match ban. Evans was booked in a reserve game against Motherwell at Easter
Road last week and he has gone over the disciplinary threshold.
Another striker, Kevin Harper, has a shoulder injury and defenders Graham
Mitchell, Willie Miller, and David Farrell also are casualties.
McLaren and Aberdeen's Billy Dodds are to face the SFA's disciplinary committee
in the new year to discuss their parts in an incident during a recent match at
Ibrox. The committee have already suspended John Brown and Paul Gascoigne for
their behaviour during the same match, parts of which became the subjects of a
police investigation.
McLaren and Dodds were not dealt with because the disciplinary committee were
informed they had been cautioned by the police, but the case was subsequently
dropped. ``We await confirmation from the procurator fiscal's office and when
that is received we will call the two players in, probably to the next arranged
meeting of the committee on January 22,'' said an SFA spokesman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Babes in the Magic Wood, Paisley Arts Centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995573</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEAVING Paisley, ears still tingling with the sound of weans laughing and
cheering, and telling each other what the best bits were ..... and Ofpants -
the official pantomime watchdog - stayed strangely silent. A sneaky squint at
the checklist - curiouser and curiouser...... It was blank. No ticks, no
crosses. No coded hieroglyphs in the margins. Nary a comment. Nothing.
Surely Ofpants couldn't have been indifferent to Babes in the Magic Wood? PACE
hadn't, somehow, gone beyond the pale of panto by daring to do away with the
old Robin Hood and Maid Marion scenario that so often loses babes - and
audiences - in Sherwood Forest? Had they?
A weird sound, a kind of snough - part snuffle, part cough - suggested
something had got up Ofpants' nose. Deep sighs. What was it with the watchdog?
Finally, a kind of broken muttering. ``That tiny stage ..... so much
imagination! Fresh jokes. Fresh JOKES.''
Something suspiciously like a tear glistened in that habitually
hard-to-hoodwink eye. In truth, Ofpants had been left speechless by Babes in
the Magic Wood. And for all the very best reasons.
Without recourse to big bucks or big names, this home-grown show - written and
directed by David Wallace, who also straps on a bustle and plays Dame -
celebrates all the brashness, warmth, hilarity, and conflict of traditional
panto in a way that is wholeheartedly gleeful and yet touchingly innocent.
And my, but it involves absolutely everybody. The garrulous, helpful hawkeye in
the audience quickly becomes a regular part of the action while, on-stage,
dozens of on-the-ball members of Paisley Youth Theatre sing, dance, and speak
up as cheery residents of Toytown or spooky tree people from the evil Queen's
domain.
Wallace, meanwhile, and his professional team of five add their own special
stamp - delivering discernible characters, not just punchlines. A sudden
movement caught my attention - Ofpants was scribbling this line. ``Paisley's
panto takes the biscuit - and that's official.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ballet dancer charged after backstage row</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995574</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MALE dancer with Scottish Ballet has been charged in connection with an
alleged behind-the-scenes attack on a 25-year-old ballerina.
He is accused of punching Catarina Lappin in a backstage row during a
performance of A Midsummer Night's Dream in Edinburgh's Festival Theatre on
October 6.
A spokesman for Lothian and Borders Police, who were asked to investigate last
month, yesterday said a report had gone to the procurator-fiscal at Edinburgh.
``A 33-year-old man has now been charged in connection with this alleged
incident,'' he said.
A spokeswoman for Scottish Ballet said the company was unable to comment
because it was now a police matter.
The company, which is currently staging its Christmas production Peter Pan at
the Festival Theatre, is thought to have conducted its own investigation into
the incident after a complaint by Ms Lappin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mother's plea on car bull bars</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Calum MacDonald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995575</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MOTHER whose daughter was seriously injured by bull bars fitted to a vehicle
has joined a Labour campaign to outlaw them.
Mrs Sharon Moule, of Essex, who has been nursing her daughter, Victoria, said:
``Children are most at risk and I am demanding immediate action in Parliament
to tackle this problem.''
``Victoria was very badly injured and is still having hospital treatment. She
had head injuries, lost her vision and had to have facial surgery. The bars
pushed a piece of bone out of her pelvis. They should be banned.''
Shadow Consumer Minister Nigel Griffiths and Labour MP Paul Flynn launched the
latest phase of their campaign at the Commons.
Last year, 35 people were killed and 1145 injured in accidents involving
vehicles fitted with bars, originally used in Australia to protect against
kangaroos.
Mr Griffiths said: ``Moves to get the bars banned have the support of the RAC,
the AA, Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents and coroners dealing with
victims.''
The Government said last April it was powerless to ban bull bars, but the MPs
believe it is ignoring the advice of EU Transport Commissioner Neil Kinnock
that  immediate steps could be taken in the UK to ban bars being added to cars
and those which come fitted to imported vehicles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Possible conflict of interest' over contract raised</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995576</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE possibility of a conflict of interest involving a Scottish Office civil
servant seconded to a bank involved in a bid for the contract to build the new
Edinburgh Royal Infirmary was raised with Ministers yesterday.
Mr William Moyes, a Grade 5 officer who was head of the Purchasing Strategy
Division in the NHS management executive, has been on secondment to the British
Linen Bank since October 1994. The bank is involved in the Laing consortium,
which in May announced a #100m bid for the ERI contract, also being sought by
two other consortia.
Mr John McAllion, Labour's Scottish health spokesman, said he was alerted to Mr
Moyes's secondment by a report in The Herald and tabled a parlimentary question
about it. However, it was when he recently attended a Private Finance
Initiative seminar in Stirling and heard Mr Moyes introduced as the bank's
infrastructure finance spokesman that he became seriously concerned about a
possible conflict of interest.
He said: ``The latest Budget Report makes it clear that under the Private
Finance Initiative the public sector contracts to buy services and not assets.
Why then has the senior Scottish Office expert in purchasing health services
been seconded to just one bank involved in one consortium bidding for PFI
projects?''
He said the Scottish Health Minister, Lord James Douglas-Hamilton, should clear
up any doubts surrounding Mr Moyes' current position. ``We are therefore
calling on him to give an absolute assurance that there is no conflict of
interests and that Civil Service expertise is not being misused to promote the
commercial interests of one particular private consortium.''
A Scottish Office spokeswoman said there was no conflict of interest. Mr Moyes
had been seconded in the usual way.
She said: ``We understand the British Linen Bank is advising a number of
consortia bidding for a variety of projects in the UK. The purchasing process
for these projects is strictly defined by EC directives. The Scottish Office is
not involved in determining which consortia are chosen to bid for particular
contracts. This is a matter for the relevant NHS trusts and health boards.
Final decisions by Ministers will be taken on the advice of civil servants in
the usual way. Mr Moyes will not be involved in these.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Refreshingly creative</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sally Thompson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995577</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WONDERFULLY elegant restaurant has emerged at 141 Elderslie Street where once
there was a strictly vegetarian Indian establishment. Ivory's - like the Ashoka
across the road, which incorporates a vegetarian menu - is owned by the Purewal
family, and Bashee Sumal is the proprietress. Strictly non-Indian, Ivory's
offers fine European cuisine served in the most sophisticated yet relaxed
surroundings. Here indeed is the place to forget life's cares, to celebrate a
special anniversary or occasion, to have a leisurely escapist lunch - or a
Christmas party, as it's that time of year.
The decor and ambience at Ivory's is unique and intimate.
Warm marbled walls, subdued baize, intriguing artifacts and gilded napkin
rings, the warmth of Mandarin slate on the floor and lovely low-key paintings
set the scene for a memorable night out.
But the proof of the pudding of course is in the eating.
Ivory's menus are seductive and varied but not alarmingly extensive. So you can
be sure that every dish is freshly prepared using the finest of local produce.
The menu changes monthly too and there's a tantalising lunch menu for the
leisured classes as well as a mouthwatering selection of dishes for dinner.
Pan-fried Monkfish on a bed of Seaweed served with a ginger shallot cream is my
healthy choice for a special treat, but it's hard to resist the Supreme of
Pheasant, pheasant supreme filled with salmon mousse and wrapped in a lattice
pastry.
Scotch smoked salmon with oat-cakes and a dill and horseradish cream serve as a
perfect starter for my taste, but there's always a chef's home-made soup for
the homely inclined or a Seafood Pancake - seafood wrapped in filo pastry
served on a lobster sauce.
Ivory's Christmas lunch menu is refreshingly imaginative.
Yes, you can have Norfolk turkey, served with sage and chestnut stuffing,
chipolata and cranberry sauce, but there's a Delice of Trout stuffed with Prawn
Farci too, or Roast Gigot of Lamb with traditional mint sauce, or Medallions of
Pork topped with Stilton and served with a red wine glaze.
Vegetarians will find tasty and sophisticated dishes to tempt their palates at
Ivory's and for habitual curry-eaters who are looking for a relaxing,
less-piquant European alternative to eating out in town (parking no problem in
the evenings) where better than Ivory's?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dentists vote against chief executive KEITH SINCLAIR</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995578</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SENIOR dentists at Glasgow Dental Hospital and School have taken the unusual
step of passing a vote of no confidence in the trust's chief executive.
Concern among the 45 consultants and other permanent staff came to a head at a
monthly meeting of the hospital's division of dentistry last night when the
dentists passed by a large majority a vote of no confidence in chief executive
Dr Doreen Steele.
The move is unusual because, although consultants in any NHS trust might
complain about management, they rarely take matters as far as a formal motion
of this nature.
A total of 48 of the 52 dentists who were eligible to take part cast their
votes at the meeting and, of those, 34 favoured the vote of no confidence while
five were against it and nine abstained.
It is believed that the vote may be only about the third of its type among
staff at any NHS trust in Britain.
The hospital became an NHS trust in April, under the chairmanship of Sir James
Armour, retired Vice-Principal of Glasgow University, but dissatisfaction goes
back about a year.
There are about 60 senior staff in the dental division, including 15
consultants employed by the NHS and 30 honorary consultants employed by Glasgow
University.
Their complaints include allegations of a ``confrontational'' management style
and that clinicians are not being involved sufficiently in policy-making.
One of the dentists who attended last night's meeting said afterwards: ``It was
quite a sombre meeting and no-one really wanted to take such action but it was
inevitable.
``I was not surprised by the vote. What was surprising is that the senior staff
have been so patient since Dr Steele has been in office. The surprise is that
we didn't do something before now.''
He added that the dentists believe the matter should now be considered
carefully by the board.
``They can hardly ignore it. I think the consultants would hope that the board
would consider radically changing their policies or radically changing the
chief executive. That would be the most sensible course of action to take.''
Dr Steele, who has been chief executive since the hospital became a trust and
was formerly general manager, did not attend the meeting and could not be
contacted last night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Drink-driving figures boost</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995579</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Positive breath tests in this year's anti drink-drive campaign are down by
almost 0.5%, according to figures released yesterday. Almost 22,000 motorists
have been stopped by police in Scotland since November 24, with 367 testing
positive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000123</DOCNO>
