<HEADLINE>DSS must pay private care</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995580</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOCIAL Security Secretary Peter Lilley yesterday failed in his bid to stop an
86-year-old widow in a private home getting #50 a week in attendance allowance
from his department.
The Court of Appeal said that Mrs Vera Steane was entitled to the cash while in
the care of the home because it was formerly run by the council. The ruling
opens the way for thousands of similar claims.
Her representative, Mr Peter Pilgrem, the Legal Services manager at Newport
County Hall on the Isle of Wight, said: ``Anyone living in private residential
homes for the elderly which were once run by the local authority can now claim
the allowance.''
Mrs Steane lives at Elmdon, a residential home on the Isle of Wight, which was
originally run by the local council. On May 10, 1991, it was leased to
Islecare, a private charity, under council privatisation plans.
The Secretary of State held that although she had transferred to a private home
and was no longer in supported council accommodation, the local authority was
still liable for any income support, not central Government.
Yesterday, Lord Justice Aldous, sitting with Lord Justice Hirst and Mr Justice
Forbes, dismissed Mr Lilley's appeal and the other judges agreed. They granted
leave for the case to go to the House of Lords because of its importance as a
precedent.
A legal expert said the case was an important breakthrough for local
authorities which had privatised their residential homes, since it allowed them
to shift care costs to central Government.
</TEXT>
