<RECORDNO>974995581</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOOD news for Glasgow gourmets is that the well-loved Ashoka has risen
phoenix-like from the ashes and has recently reopened under the careful eye of
new owners, the Purewals, a Glasgow family who are dedicated to re-establishing
the restaurant and restoring it to its former glories and beyond.
The Purewal family have had a long and fruitful association with Indian cuisine
in Glasgow. They used to own several famous Indian restaurants in the city. The
superb Creme de la Creme, Europe's largest and finest Indian restaurant is
theirs, and the vegetarian Ashoka of Elderslie Street has metamorphosed into a
wonderfully elegant European restaurant under their new and imaginative
ownership.
For the non-carnivorous or health-conscious who may have regretted the demise
of an exclusively vegetarian Indian restaurant there is good news. The Ashoka
has incorporated a vegetarian menu into its extensive  la carte, which covers
the finest and most imaginative Indian food to be had in the city.
The restaurant is transformed. Gone are the dark soft-furnishings and the
gloomy regimented tables, and in their place is a freshness and lightness of
decor which makes dining there a special occasion. Warm yellows complement the
specially commissioned murals of mountain scenes by Dai and Jenny Vaughan,
Tiffany glass windows enhance the dreariest drizzle of a Glasgow December, and
floors are of beautiful, richly textured Mandarin slate.
The Ashoka can seat a surprisingly large number on its two floors, but the
Purewals have cut down a little on tables to make for a more spacious and
elegant eating experience. For those offices who have not yet fixed a venue for
the annual jamboree, the Ashoka is a splendid bet and Parminder Purewal is
willing to accommodate eleventh-hour bookings. Christmas lunch or dinner at the
Ashoka is a tempting option too for those who can't face the strains and
stresses of a home entertainment. Otherwise, for shoppers or workers, the
Ashoka is open seven days a week from noon until midnight except on Sundays
when the restaurant is open from five until midnight.
For the curious, by the way, Ashoka was an Emperor of India c274-232BC. He was
converted to Buddhism by a miracle and became its ``nursing father'', as
Constantine was of Christianity.
</TEXT>
