<DOCNO>GH951208-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Inquiry told of man's last hours</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN who went to a police station to collect her husband was told she
couldn't see him as he'd just been pronounced dead, a court heard yesterday.
Mrs Irene Low, 61, of Dubbieside, Methil, Fife, made the claim at a fatal
accident inquiry at Kirkcaldy Sheriff Court.
Sheriff William Christie heard that a large crack was found in Mr David Low's
skull after his death at Levenmouth police station on March 26.
The previous evening, the couple each had a sherry and Mr Low, 53, went for a
walk.
Shortly after 3am, Mrs Low was roused by a neighour, who said her husband had
been found lying in the road. Mrs Low telephoned the police station and was
told he had been examined by a doctor and was alright.
At the station the next morning, ``I began to get a bit suspicious and asked
what was wrong but they didn't say,'' Mrs Low said. ``I asked if I was getting
to see Dave and a policeman said, `No, I am sorry, he's just been pronounced
dead'.''
Asked if his death had shocked her, she replied, ``yes, he went out for a walk
and never came back.''
Publican, Mr John Band, 54, a former schoolmate of the dead man, said Mr Low
had arrived at his tavern on the evening of March 25 and consumed, at most, six
drinks before leaving about 2.30am.
Mr John Rhines, 51, said he was driving friends home when they saw Mr Low lying
unconscious at the side of the road.
One of his passengers, barmaid Ms Lorraine Morrison, 37, said she noticed the
back of Mr Low's head was covered in what appeared to be dried blood.
Police arrived minutes later and collected Mr Low.
Tayside Detective Chief Superintendent James Letham, 50, who carried out an
independent investigation, said a surveillance film of the police station
interior showed a doctor spent just 23 seconds in Mr Low's cell.
However, Kirkcaldy pathologist Dr Muhammed Nawroz, 44, who performed the
post-mortem examination said there was no chance of Mr Low's survival even if
he had received immediate treatment.
Dr Nawroz said Mr Low had suffered an extensive brain haemorrhage which ``would
be in keeping with him falling on a hard surface'' and unlikely to have been
caused by a car. He said Mr Low had 272mg of alcohol in his blood.
The doctor said he would not have expected a lay person to detect the severity
of Mr Low's injuries.
The inquiry continues today.
</TEXT>
