<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shop raider with knife jailed again</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995584</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN wielding a knife who held up a shopkeeper weeks after completing a
sentence for assault and robbery was jailed for six years yesterday.
Lord Ross, the Lord Justice Clerk, told Michael Carr that such offences were
becoming far too common and the courts had do what they could to protect
shopkeepers.
Carr, 23, admitted assaulting Mr Steven Lyon, 28, in the shop at Angle Park
Terrace, Edinburgh, on September 26 this year by menacing him with a knife. He
forced him to open the cash register, demanded money, and robbed the shopkeeper
of #285.
Mr Craig Scott, Advocate-depute, told the High Court in Edinburgh that Carr, of
Lomax Road, Queenslie, Glasgow, had a criminal record stretching back to 1987.
In September 1992 he had been sentenced to four years for assault and robbery
and had been released in July this year.
The shopkeeper was able to give police a fairly detailed description and Carr
was arrested two days after the incident.
The Advocate-depute explained that the incident had had a significant impact on
Mr Lyon, who was now considerably more anxious about the chances of a further
hold-up in his shop.
Mr William McVicar, defence counsel, said that the accused had spent much of
his life in custody. At the completion of his last sentence in July he had been
put out on the streets with no idea of what to do with himself.
</TEXT>
