<DOCNO>GH951208-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour plans task force to help clean up football</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995585</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday unveiled plans for a football task force designed to tackle
hooliganism and restore the sport's tarnished image.
The party wants to clean up a sport which it says has suffered from thuggery by
far-right extremists and appalling behaviour by supporters and players.
Labour also set out to crack down on financial scandals, bungs, allegations of
match-fixing and drugs use by players.
The party's Charter for Football also would address issues such as escalating
ticket prices, restrictive TV coverage and the precarious financial position of
small, lower league clubs.
COMPUTERS all over Britain are set to fail in just over five years because of a
technical hitch, the Prime Minister was told yesterday. Tory David Atkinson, MP
for Bournemouth East, said it was because computers were not programmed to
recognise the double-zero of the year 2000. This would have ``immense
consequences'' for British business and government departments, Mr Atkinson
said.
THE Government yesterday announced plans to reform the ancient system of
military justice, including a greater say for Service members on whether cases
should be heard by a court-martial or a commanding officer. Armed Forces
Minister Nicholas Soames said in a written reply that the changes would be
introduced in the Armed Forces Bill, currently going through Parliament.
UNDER-AGE smokers are netting the Treasury an estimated #100m in tax every
year, the Government disclosed last night. The figure was based on the results
of surveys by the Office of Population Censuses and Surveys in four years since
1990.
</TEXT>
