<DOCNO>GH951208-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Legal challenge could halt rail sell-off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995586</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HIGH Court judge will decide today whether rail franchise director Roger
Salmon should sign over the first three franchises next week or restart the
tendering process from scratch, thereby delaying and perhaps even derailing the
privatisation programme.
Mr Justice Macpherson yesterday heard allegations that minimum services allowed
under rail privatisation were set so low that they were ``in defiance of
guarantees given to Parliament''.
In a legal challenge that could throw the Government's sell-off plans into
confusion, Mr Nigel Pleming QC, for the Save Our Railways pressure group, told
the court that instructions from former Transport Secretary John MacGregor,
aimed at safeguarding service levels based on existing timetables, had not been
obeyed by Mr Salmon.
The challenge centres on the first tranche of franchises covering the Great
Western, South West Trains, and the London, Tilbury, and Southend, due to be
finalised next week, and the second batch, including InterCity East Coast,
Network SouthCentral, Midland Main Line, and Gatwick Express.
Mr Pleming told the judge the director had acted outside his discretion and in
breach of his duty under the 1993 Railways Act, the aim of which was to put the
publicly-owned railways and railway services into private ownership.
In March last year, Mr MacGregor had published a document stating that: ``For
the initial letting of the franchises, your minimum service levels for railway
passenger services is to be based on that provided by BR immediately prior to
franchising.''
This was in line with guarantees given to Parliament over minimum services,
said Mr Pleming. In defiance of those guarantees, Mr Salmon had unlawfully set
passenger service requirements that effectively ``diminished the level of
service'' that could be guaranteed.
Mr Salmon had acted as if he could ``pick and choose'' existing services and
there was a very vague approach to which services were to be protected and
which were not.
Mr Jeremy Sullivan QC, for the franchise director, said the scheme's opponents
had misinterpreted the situation.
Their argument largely rested on the interpretation of the instruction
requiring minimum service levels to be ``based on'' that provided by BR prior
to franchising.
He said: ``On the ordinary interpretation of the words `x is to be based on y'
they don't mean `x is to be the same as y' or `x is to be the same as y with
minor variations'.''
When read as a whole, the emphasis of the guidelines and instructions given to
Mr Salmon was on getting value for money and on flexibility to encourage
commercial initiative.
Mr Sullivan said that if assurances were given to Parliament which were not
carried through, that was a matter for Parliament and not the courts.
Mr Sullivan stressed that the passenger service requirement (PSR) laid down by
Mr Salmon was not intended to reflect the service level which was actually
going to be provided by a franchisee. The majority of those currently tendering
for franchises were offering to provide service levels above the PSR, he said.
Mr Justice Macpherson, announcing he would give his judgment at 2pm today,
said: ``It is no easier for a judge when argument on both sides is so good.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The magic touch</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Carole Woddis</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995587</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Carole Woddis explores the string of Scottish hits at London's Bush Theatre
WELL, we hardly need wait for the Sunday papers. David Harrower's Knives in
Hens has, like Mike Cullen's The Cut, Chris Hannan's Evil Doers and The Baby,
and the ubiquitous Trainspotting, made the journey to London's Bush Theatre to
be greeted with something close to rapture.
Michael Billington in the Guardian declared it a ``remarkable theatrical
debut''. The Independent called it ``a first play of unusual assurance, wit,
and intelligence'', while the Times's Benedict Nightingale, though describing
it as ``dour and difficult,'' found it ``a genuinely original evening that
raises questions about the nature of language, God, and civilisation itself''.
True, Nick Curtis, of the Evening Standard, struck a carping note. But even he
had to admit that: ``Harrower's play is a debut of rare promise.'' Meanwhile,
in its very first week Harrower's play jumped straight to number one in Time
Out's prestigious Critics' Choice.
All of which makes an interesting contrast with the reception meted out to the
Tron's Dumbstruck and Wildcat's Bedfellows - Scottish imports which earned some
of the worst crits of 1995.
So what is it about the Bush? Why do they seem to have had the midas touch
where others have failed? Ian Brown of the Traverse puts it very simply:
``Dominic Dromgoole, the Bush's current artistic director, has good taste. He's
got a good eye and knows things that will work well for him.''
Dromgoole puts it another way. ``You know when it's quality writing; you can
practically smell it. The same is true of Irish writing.'' Dromgoole
acknowledges they've drawn heavily on the Traverse and their system of
nurturing writers but, he maintains, the Bush's success with Scottish plays is
not due to any intrinsically pro-Scottish policy decision.
``We've picked these plays primarily because we think they're the finest
writers; they're all in their funny ways specific to their own situations
rather than trying to be Scottish.''
There is, however, one other aspect to be mentioned in connection with the
Bush's string of Scottish successes. As Brown says: ``It's got to be work that
travels. Comedy is so much harder.''
That's a view shared by Nick Kent whose Tricycle Theatre suffered a mauling
with Bedfellows. ``I love theatre that's visceral and engages with the
community. I saw a review of Bedfellows in the Sunday Times and thought it
would fit into ours. But it seems the minute you take something out of its own
community, you divorce it from its roots. It gets judged in a different
context, and more harshly, so that what started out as an excuse for a hooley
takes on instead more of a shrieking, village-hall type of piece.
``The plays that go down well in London now are from a younger age group -
exactly the same as the Irish syndrome, 19 to 28-year-olds. Angry,
rock-oriented. There's an audience for that. But when you bring something
political, it doesn't seem enormously relevant to us. If you're political, you
can get your head round it. But most of our audiences don't seem to want to be
bothered.
``The Cut and Trainspotting are much more to do with young people, universal
issues they can relate to. They draw the crowds.''
Call English audiences lazy if you like - and I've heard similar excuses for a
whole range of plays - the answer is surely that the magic elements which make
a play gell with audiences are part talent, part quality, and part the
zeitgeist of the moment. The best playwrights seem able to externalise and give
shape to all of them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major set for power battle with Brussels Heath warns on Government tactics</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995588</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister will use next week's Euro-summit to press the United
Kingdom's case for less rhetoric and more action from Brussels, Foreign
Secretary Malcolm Rifkind told the Commons last night.
He was speaking during a debate on Europe which once again exposed divisions on
both sides of the House on the issue, and brought a warning from Tory former
Prime Minister Sir Edward Heath that the Government should not set out a
defined position before talks took place.
The Prime Minister, at Question Time, gave a firm commitment that at next
year's summit on Europe's future he will oppose the extension of qualified
majority voting, ``massive'' new powers for the European Parliament and signing
up to the Social Chapter.
He confirmed that the Government was considering bringing out a White Paper on
Europe, but insisted its policies on these areas were firm and would not change.
Mr Major first clashed on the issue with Labour leader Tony Blair and was then
told by veteran Tory Euro-sceptic Teddy Taylor (Southend East) that a White
Paper would ``draw to the public's attention to the ever-widening gulf between
the Government and Opposition, which, under its present leadership, is destined
to surrender more of our liberty and our power and our jobs to Brussels.''
Mr Major replied: ``That does seem to be clear in many of the speeches of
Labour MPs, though not universally, for they seem to sing a different tune on
some occasions.''
The Government was considering the desirability of a White Paper, but had made
clear on a number of occasions that there were some areas which certainly would
be opposed in the negotiations.
EU leaders meet in Madrid on Friday and Saturday of next week, when the likely
agenda for next year's ``Maastricht II'' inter-governmental conference will be
discussed.
Mr Rifkind told the House: ``At Madrid, our Prime Minister will again reinforce
the message that we want progress on enhancing competitiveness, improving the
quality and reducing the quantity of legislation, and deregulating labour
markets to make them more responsive, creating jobs and reducing unemployment.''
Claiming that the battle was being won, Mr Rifkind said: ``We want less
rhetoric, more action, and we will continue to push strongly for this.''
The Foreign Secretary clashed repeatedly with his Labour Shadow Robin Cook, who
claimed that Euro-sceptics were dictating the Government's European policy.
``The Euro-sceptics are in charge,'' he said. ``There is now no hoop too tight
through which Ministers will not slim down their beliefs in order to squeeze
through.''
He reaffirmed Labour's commitment to a single currency when conditions were
right, stating: ``The test of convergence for the single currency has to be the
convergence of the real economy - industry, jobs, productivity, output - not
just the financial criteria the Government signed up to in the Maastricht
Treaty.''
Sir Edward warned both the Prime Minister and the Foreign Secretary that saying
``this is in our interest and that's that'' was not negotiation.
The former Premier, who took Britain into the Common Market, drew scornful
cries from Tory Euro-sceptics when he spoke in favour of Britain signing the
Social Chapter and introducing a minimum wage, and pressed for a single
currency to be introduced as quickly as possible.
Pro-European Tory ex-Minister Edwina Currie (Derbyshire South), who was
defeated in her bid to become an MEP at the last Euro-elections, told the House
she hoped Britain would be ``courageous'' enough to join a single currency when
the time came.
For the Liberal Democrats, European Affairs spokesman Charles Kennedy said:
``This is a broken-backed Government and a terminally split Tory Party over
Europe. We can expect them to wrap themselves in the flag - the Union flag - as
the election approaches. They will fight an increasingly chauvinistic
campaign.''
q The Prime Minister told MPs that Britain is ``profoundly dissatisfied'' with
some decisions taken by the European Commission of Human Rights but will not
withdraw from it.
Instead, the Government is to take up the question with the commission and deal
with it ``in some way in the future'', he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Messiah, City Hall, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Magee</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995589</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF you had turned up for this Messiah expecting the customary massed host of
singers and full-blown orchestra then you would be forgiven for being initially
a little taken aback. With only 20 singers on stage, no apparent soloists, and
a 15-piece orchestra, it might well have looked like this was to be a pocket
version of Handel's seasonal evergreen.
Not so. Those previously acquainted with this performance by the John Currie
Singers will know how effective these small resources can be, any doubting
Thomas surely instantly reassured by the bright, lucid textures of the overture
and the commanding opening recitative from Dennis Haggerty. Establishing the
pattern for the performance, Haggerty stepped forward from the twin ranks of
the choir and delivered his aria, returned, to be followed in rotation by nine
of his colleagues, thus sharing round the solo slots.
All produced highly expressive singing, allowed lots of air space by the
sympathetic support of the orchestra under John Currie's very positive
direction. Capitalising on the opportunity for tightness of ensemble playing
that such small numbers bring, he drove the work forward at a cracking pace
without ever losing articulation. And what a performance he got in those
legendary choruses - crisp entries, clean notes, huge surges of power, and
razor-sharp finishes.
This was a radiant Messiah, and despite the non-stop commitment from the choir
throughout the evening they still had plenty in reserve to deliver a stirring
final chorus that shimmered gloriously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Opposition relishes chance to get its teeth into meaty matters</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter, Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>commons sketch</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974995590</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE was no evidence, said the Prime Minister, reading his brief carefully,
that eating meat gave humans mad cow disease.
``Oh, I don't know,'' chirruped the irrepressible Mr Tony Banks (Newham North
West - Lab.). ``Look at the Cabinet.'' The meat-eaters on the Treasury Bench
did their best to look in complete possession of their faculties.
Mr Jimmy Hood (Clydesdale - Lab.) had something of a forensic triumph when,
after accusing Mr Major of being ``decisively indecisive,'' the man obliged by
admitting that the Cabinet could not yet decide whether to produce a White
Paper on how its sees the future in Europe. With Mr Kenneth Clarke and Mr
Michael Portillo involved, one sees the difficulty.
Sir Peter Tapsell (Lindsey East - Con.) spoke grandly of the disorders across
the Channel as a grim warning of what happens when you try to shackle your
economy to a single European currency. He did this rather in the manner of a
Whig aristo reflecting on the early stages of the French Revolution.
Mr Major is, of course, too nice to relish the sight of another EU government
in even worse trouble than his own. He stood by Messrs Chirac and Juppe and
blamed their troubles, as doubtless they are doing, on the incapacity of their
socialist predecessors.
Mr Juppe is beginning to resemble the unfortunate royal minister Necker, but
may be comforted by the thought that Necker did not go to the guillotine.
Mr Blair, who cannot be paying attention to the observations of his Shadow
Foreign Secretary, Mr Robin Cook, made much of the Tory Party being split
between those who are keen on Europe and those who, if Sir Teddy and Bill Cash
will forgive the understatement, are not keen.
Mr Banks, who is working up to becoming a sort of Mother Teresa of the animal
kingdom, then cast politics to the four winds and begged Mr Major to join him
in urging people not to buy puppies for Christmas presents unless the pups were
going to be a lifelong commitment. Mr Major agreed. It was certainly easier
than steering a decisively indecisive course on the single currency.
We passed from one majority passion of the British public - animals - to
another - the Princess of Wales. The princess may see the way the political
wind is blowing or she may just have been furthering her campaign to become
queen of our hearts.
However, she had shared a platform with a Labour spokesman and several
organisations who are not great admirers of the Government's housing and
benefits policies. Her remarks were along the ``something must be done'' lines
which her husband's predecessor as Prince of Wales patented in the valleys.
It was not difficult for Mr John McFall (Dumbarton - Lab.) to couple this with
an attack on the indadequacy of Government policies for the homeless. Ministers
are thought to be a bit peeved at the company Diana was keeping on that
platform. However, one of his Ministers, Mr Nicholas Soames, having recently
shown the unwisdom of being rude about the beautiful princess, Mr Major simply
replied that the Government had cut the numbers sleeping in the streets
substantially and hoped to eliminate them - in the sense of finding them beds
with roofs over them - soon.
He inferred that there was a bit of a cult about sleeping rough among some
young people and implied that, like human sacrifice and liberal governments, it
could soon be a thing of the past.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Christmas Oratorio, City Hall, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Magee</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995591</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AND Lo! the season of festive music is upon us with the Scottish Early Music
Consort joining the Choir from St Mary's Episcopal Cathedral, Edinburgh, in
their attempt to bring a little stardust to a decidedly jaded City Hall. Tinsel
decorations draped the stage and auditorium but all the sparkle came from the
singing of the 12 adult lay clerks and 16 young boys and girls - aged eight to
13 - who make up the St Mary's Choir. In two cantatas from Bach's Christmas
Oratorio their diction was clear, they blended well, and the younger members
particularly, sang with an unassuming ease that was a delight to both watch and
hear. The choir even provided three soloists, Adrian Stones, Andrew Arthur, and
Nick Hall to stand in for the indisposed Fiona Milne.
The other soloists Alan Watt, Stuart Patterson, and Mhairi Lawson were all in
good voice, even if Miss Lawson tended to being swamped by the orchestral
accompaniment from the Baroque Orchestra of the SEMC.
The lighter side of the concert comprised three carols, some audience
participation in an up-beat reprise of Good Christmas Men Rejoice, and the
fiendish Concerto for Two Trumpets by Vivaldi. Robert Baxter and Alexander
McGrattan coped manfully on their valveless baroque instruments but were
upstaged by some brilliant lip work from the trumpet of Christopher Dicken in
the closing Bach cantata.
Gregory Squire generally directed with an even hand and tried hard to inject an
air of levity. The good-sized audience seemed well pleased, remaining sanguine
in the face of some awkward longeurs between numbers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ovary `saved for the future'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995592</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GIRL of three has become the youngest person to have pioneering surgery to
stop cancer treatment making her infertile.
Harriet Selka, who has a rare kidney cancer, had part of her ovary removed so
that it would not be damaged by radiotherapy.
The tiny section of tissue has been deep frozen and will be replaced after the
treatment is finished, possibly in 20 years.
Harriet, of Thurstonland, Huddersfield, is one of a handful of people to have
undergone the procedure.
It has been devised by a team led by Professor Roger Gosden, professor of
reproductive biology at Leeds General Infirmary, which is also about to begin
similar trials on males.
In the past, only adult male cancer patients have been able to retain their
fertility, by donating sperm before treatment.
Professor Gosden nows plans to help boys who have not reached puberty by
removing and freezing the cells in the testicles that manufacture sperm and
replacing them after treatment.
Harriet developed a form of cancer known as Wilm's tumour in July last year and
had one of her kidneys removed. She had the piece of her left ovary removed in
October and is now in remission from the cancer.
Her mother Elizabeth said: ``What Professor Gosden is doing is wonderful and if
it proves successful and he helps children that would otherwise be sterile to
have children themselves, it will be a compensatory bonus for what they've gone
through.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fatwa Patois, Tron Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995593</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS one-off rehearsed reading of Andrew Dallmeyer's new play kicks off the
Tron Theatre's admirable short season of New Scottish Writing, and will be
followed by a rehearsed extract on Friday of the company's next musical,
Stiff!, written by and starring Forbes Masson. On Saturday Michael Boyd will
direct a work-in-progress presentation of The Love We Find Ourselves, written
by Penetrator author Anthony Neilson.
Previous Tron Theatre Company successes have evolved from work-in-progress
presentations, such as The Trick is To Keep Breathing, The Steamie, and The Cut
but it is more difficult to discern potential from the rehearsed-reading
format. Dallmeyer's play has so many physical and visual gags that it clearly
needs a theatrical framework to realise the comedy.
All the same, this reading lacked the focus and energy necessary to suggest
that the piece could be successfully developed. Dallmeyer is an accomplished
wordsmith and the script packs an ebullient enough punch but the premise - a
young Muslim Glaswegian joke shop manager, Tariq Azid, bears a strong physical
resemblance to a controversial author Solomon Rashdie (sic) and is subject to
violent attacks because of this mistaken identity - is less imaginative than
the various vivid characterisations. The parallels to Salman Rushdie are too
dated and tired to have any satirical bite and the dramatic debate about Muslim
fundamentalism lacks sophistication.
Particularly unconvincing is Azid's abrupt nervous breakdown and sudden plunge
into the delusion that he is in fact Rushdie. Dallmeyer is a master of the pun
and parody - with a very witty spoof on Rushdie's literary style - but the
cohesion of the play was unconvincing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sheriff lets gunslinger off with a warning</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995594</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHERIFF forfeited a would-be cowboy's gun yesterday during an appearance in
Paisley Sheriff Court.
The court heard that Andrew ``Big Clint'' Henderson, 43, of Foxbar, was
practicing his cross-belly draw in front of friends in his living room when the
gun accidentally discharged.
The party of Wild West lovers had been due to visit the Outlaw Gunslingers'
Club in Glasgow when Henderson's revolver became snagged in the waistband of
his trousers and went off.
Ambulance men found Henderson sprawled on the floor with flash burns to his
inside leg. Police became involved because a firearm had inflicted the injury.
The replica handgun had been ``radically altered'', with the blocked-off barrel
opened up to allow flame to shoot out whenever it fired blanks, the court
heard. After being shown photographs of Henderson dressed in his cowboy gear,
Sheriff Robert McCallum ordered the firearm be forfeited but said, in the
circumstances, he was prepared to admonish the accused.
As he left the court, Mr Henderson said: ``I've been a member of the club for
six years. I love the clubs and have been all over the country, but I guess my
shootin' days are over now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BBC SSO, Glasgow Royal Concert Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995595</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I'm sure that the majority present last night at the BBC Scottish Symphony
Orchestra's 60th birthday concert will disagree, but neither the structure nor
overall content of the programme, it seemed to me, did the SSO justice.
Arguably the programme was too long, containing one modern work too many.
Certainly, with the two substantial and recently composed works hard up against
one another, then followed by a lacklustre version of Elgar's Enigma
Variations, it made for a vast and sprawling second half.
Additionally, neither of the contemporary pieces - both conducted with clarity
and expertise by Martyn Brabbins - was a display piece for the orchestra, nor a
major piece in its own right. Thea Musgrave's Journey Through a Japanese
Landscape, a stylised essay featuring Evelyn Glennie on marimba, was -
especially for this composer - a rather rambling piece, only revealing
Musgrave's typically muscular and brilliantly hectic pacing in its second
movement.
And Iain Hamilton's The Transit of Jupiter (commissioned for the occasion)
seemed, despite moments of great atmosphere - music for a film, perhaps -
terribly old-fashioned and lacking in direction: music redolent of the late
sixties in its abstract, intellectual manner. Something by one of the young
bloods, with a bit more of a wallop, would have shown the SSO at strength.
And, though conductor Jerzy Maksymiuk's accompaniment to pianist Dmitri
Alexeev's near-demented, bat-out-of-hell version of Rachmaninov's Paganini
Variations was edge-of-the-seat stuff, Elgar's Enigma Variations - turgidly
unfolded - just didn't seem the Polish conductor's piece. Surely some of his
incandescent Sibelius would have been more appropriate.
Overall, less of an event than it could and should have been.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trimble attacks Mayhew stance on Ulster's future</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995596</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NORTHERN Ireland Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew was accused yesterday of
``disinterested neutrality'' about the Province's place in the Union compared
with the position taken by Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth, who said last
week that the Government ``stood four-square behind the Union.''
Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble also criticised Sir Patrick's co-operation
``with a foreign government that is subject to a constitutional imperative to
destroy that Union.''
Sir Patrick said that Irish Prime Minister John Bruton had announced plans for
a referendum to renounce the republic's territorial claims over Northern
Ireland.
The Government had made clear that there would be no change in the Province's
status unless the people of Northern Ireland wanted it, and both he and the
Prime Minister had made it clear time and time again ``that we are very much in
support of the Union.''.
He insisted that security force weapons would not be considered by the
independent international commission headed by American Senator George Mitchell
which is to examine how illegally held arms can be decommissioned.
He was replying to Tory Lady Olga Maitland, who the Senator's appearance on a
BBC Newsnight programme, saying: ``Mr Mitchell laughed and said he would be
perfectly happy to look at Government weapons. Surely this is clearly not what
we had in mind.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Divorce sweetener</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995597</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEADING Thatcherite accused the Princess of Wales of trying to dodge the
``oblivion of divorce'' by manufacturing a new role for herself.
Sir Bernard Ingham, a former No 10 press secretary, condemned her as an
``elaborate confection sculpted by spin doctors''.
Writing in the Daily Express, he said: ``I cannot see any possible objection to
the princess ruining her beauty sleep by visiting the sick, the depressed, and
the dying. But . . . I draw the line at her claiming she has a special line to
people's hearts.''
He also suggested the princess's media exposure might please the palace:
``Another interview, another yard of rope. Sooner or later she will hang
herself.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Double threat to key city railway projects</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MacCALMAN Municipal Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995598</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE future of strategic rail projects in the West of Scotland, including the
#79m CrossRail project in Glasgow city centre, are doubly threatened by rail
privatisation and local government reorganisation.
The warning came yesterday from Strathclyde's transport official, Councillor
Charles Gordon, who fears that the severe charging regime adopted by Railtrack,
which now owns all railway infrastructure, could spell the end for strategic
investment.
He argued that situation could be exacerbated in April when Strathclyde region,
which ploughs an annual subsidy of more than #30m into the network, is replaced
by 12 unitary authorities who might find the scale of investment required quite
daunting.
Mr Gordon did not know anyone who found the terms of Railtrack investment
attractive. For example, the cost of CrossRail, which would link Glasgow's
North and South electric services, had doubled from an original Strathclyde
estimate of around #39m. Similarly the proposed reopening the Larkhall line in
Lanarkshire had burgeoned from a Strathclyde estimate of #7m to a Railtrack
estimate of #13m.
He said he was concerned that members of the new Strathclyde Passenger
Transport Executive, which after April 1 would comprise delegates from the 12
unitary authorities replacing the regional council, would look twice at huge
projects like CrossRail.
Meanwhile, a High Court judge will decide today whether rail franchise director
Roger Salmon should sign over the first three franchises next week or restart
the tendering process from scratch, thereby delaying and perhaps even derailing
privatisation.
Mr Justice Macpherson yesterday heard allegations that minimum services allowed
under rail privatisation were set so low that they were ``in defiance of
guarantees given to Parliament''.
In a legal challenge that could throw the Government's sell-off plans into
confusion, Mr Nigel Pleming QC, for the Save Our Railways pressure group, told
the court that instructions from former Transport Secretary John MacGregor,
aimed at safeguarding service levels based on existing timetables, had not been
obeyed by Mr Salmon.
In March last year, Mr MacGregor had published a document stating entitled
Objectives, Instructions, and Guidance for the Franchising Director, which
stated that: ``For the initial letting of the franchises, your minimum service
levels for railway passenger services is to be based on that provided by BR
immediately prior to franchising.''
This was in line with guarantees given to Parliament over minimum services,
said Mr Pleming. In defiance of those guarantees, Mr Salmon had unlawfully set
passenger service requirements that effectively ``diminished the level of
service'' that could be guaranteed.
Mr Jeremy Sullivan QC, for the franchise director, said the scheme's opponents
had misinterpreted the situation.
Their argument largely rested on the interpretation of the instruction
requiring minimum service levels to be ``based on'' that provided by BR prior
to franchising.
He said: ``On the ordinary interpretation of the words `x is to be based on y'
they don't mean `x is to be the same as y' or `x is to be the same as y with
minor variations'.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tory anger at princess's charity plea Major faces Commons questions after call to defend young homeless</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995599</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Princess of Wales was criticised by Tory MPs last night after delivering a
passionate plea on behalf of homeless young people who are forced to beg and
resort to prostitution.
She angered them by sharing a platform with Shadow Home Secretary Jack Straw
and making a speech which they saw as critical of Government policies towards
the homeless.
The Prime Minister was forced to defend the Government's approach at Commons
Question Time as the princess's outspoken intervention won Labour praise.
The princess's appearance at a meeting in London of the housing charity,
Centrepoint, came less than 48 hours after Mr Major's audience with the Queen
on Tuesday.
The princess wants to carve a niche for herself as a goodwill ambassador for
Britain and Mr Major is believed to think she can play a valuable role.
During her Panorama interview last month, the princess said she wanted a
meaningful role as the nation's ``queen of hearts''.
However, last night, Conservative politicians warned that she had blotted her
copybook by becoming ensnared in politics, appearing beside Mr Straw and
applauding his speech.
Tory MP Anthony Steen said: ``The fact that she shared a platform with Jack
Straw shows, unfortunately, how vulnerable she is to the influence of those who
want to exploit her unique position for party political ends.''
Former Minister Neil Hamilton said: ``She was very ill-advised. Jack Straw used
it as a political platform to attack the Government.''
Tory MP Harry Greenway claimed: ``She has been duped by a socialist speech
writer. She has done herself enormous damage with her friends and with
everybody else. She has made a serious error in appearing on a platform with
Jack Straw.''
In a hard-hitting and heartfelt speech, the princess appealed for homeless and
vulnerable young people to be given a better chance in life.
``We, as part of society, must ensure that young people - who are our future -
are given the chance they deserve,'' she said. She was appalled at the dangers
homeless young people faced on the streets and how vulnerable they were to
exploitation.
The princess cited ``16 and 17-year-olds who resort to begging - or worse,
prostitution - to get money in order to eat.''
``It is truly tragic to see the total waste of so many young lives - of so much
potential.''
Centrepoint insisted last night that the princess had not known Mr Straw was to
be at the event when she accepted the invitation.
A spokesman said Home Secretary Michael Howard had been its guest last year and
it was the Opposition's turn this year. The spokesman said: ``The princess has
been our patron since 1991 and since then she has been a regular visitor to all
our projects, sometimes on an informal basis.''
Centrepoint is angry at Government moves in the Budget to cut housing benefit
for young people under 25 and has warned that this would lead to more homeless
young people.
The leader of the Commons, Mr Tony Newton, moved to play down the row, saying:
``Members of the royal family have frequently shared platforms with members of
the Government.''
However, Mr Major was forced to respond after the princess's comments were
seized on at Commons questions by Labour's John McFall, who said she had
``highlighted the inadequacies of the present system'' for homeless youngsters.
The Prime Minister said: ``The Government has been dealing with this problem in
a comprehensive fashion for some time and has made remarkable improvements over
the last few years.
``The Government is providing around 5000 places in permanent and temporary
accommodation for people who otherwise would sleep rough.
``There has been a remarkable reduction in the number of people sleeping rough.
Plans to eliminate that entirely continue and I look forward to that day being
reached.
``We are fully committed to ensuring there is no necessity for some people to
sleep rough and we very much hope that the culture that has grown up among some
people of doing so is a culture that can change and be broken.''
q The Duchess of York said yesterday that she had dropped the idea of a
Christmas skiing holiday in Switzerland this year - so that her daughters could
spend more time with their father. The decision, which the duchess mentioned
during a charity engagement at Dorking, Surrey, adds to the prospect of a big
royal family get-together over the traditional Christmas break at Sandringham.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A `gangland execution'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES McKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995600</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE men found shot dead on an isolated farm track could have been the victims
of a gangland ambush, police said last night.
The men were known criminals and appeared to have been lured to the area before
being ``executed''. The killings bore the hallmarks of a gangland vendetta,
possibly involving drugs.
Their bodies were discovered in Workhouse Lane, in Essex, by a farmer and a
friend as they went to feed pheasants.
Each man had been shot through the head at point-blank range.
All were from Essex and were identified as Patrick Tate, 37, of Gordon Road,
Basildon; Craig Rolfe, 26, of Calshot Avenue, Chafford Hundred, Grays; and
Anthony Tucker, 38, of High Road, Fobbing.
They were shot as they sat in a Range Rover in a tree-lined track, 300 yards
off a busy main road near Rettendon. Police have not ruled out the possibility
it was a ``professional hit''.
Detective Superintendent Ivan Dibley said: ``They are known to us as criminals
and certain lines of inquiry are taking place with that knowledge.''
The vehicle was parked in a spot popular with courting couples from Rettendon,
four miles from the home of schoolgirl Leah Betts who died last month after
taking one ecstasy tablet on her 18th birthday.
Over the past 20 years, criminals from the East End of London have been moving
into the Essex area, now believed to be a base for leading drug dealers.
Police believe it likely the victims drove there for a pre-arranged meeting.
A hole had been blasted through a window of the Range Rover, indicating that
the first person to die was shot by someone standing outside the vehicle.
Speaking at White House Farm near to where the bodies were found, Mr Dibley
added: ``I would say that whoever made an arrangement for this vehicle to be at
this isolated location, for whatever reason these three people drove down here,
I would say that they had some local knowledge of that lane.''
Home Office pathologist, Dr Paula Lannas, and a ballistics expert were called
in.
Mr Kenneth Jiggins, 47, a bricklayer, said he and Mr Peter Theobald, of White
House Farm, found the bodies.
He said the Range Rover was parked in front of a locked gate they needed to
pass through to get to the pheasants.
Mr Jiggins said: ``It was certainly not a shotgun that was involved. I would
think it would have to have been a rifle or a handgun.''
Police could not confirm that only one person was involved in the shootings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No headline present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995601</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Actor David Richmond waits `in the wings' for Clamjamfrie theatre company's
free show, Satellite, in Glasgow Cathedral precinct tomorrow at 7.30pm. It
presents the everyday life of the city as seen by angels who have fallen to
earth.
</TEXT>
