<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour leader foresees a New Union in the UK for a new century Blair promises Scots a veto on tartan tax</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALF YOUNG Economics Editor and BENEDICT BROGAN                                                    ...</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995602</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR is not planning to raise taxes in the first term of a Scottish
parliament, Mr Tony Blair said yesterday, in a move designed to kill off the
electoral threat posed by the Tory ``tartan tax'' campaign.
The Labour leader also promised his party would not use the parliament's
discretionary tax powers unless the plans had been put first to the Scottish
electorate. ``Taxes will only go up if the people vote for them.''
However, he made clear he was not issuing a ``new constitutional prescription''
for the devolved parliament. The power to vary income tax, up or down, by 3p in
the pound, will be in the legislation for the assembly introduced in the first
year of a Labour government.
But he does expect Labour to put any proposed tax change to the Scottish
electorate. ``Parties that are going to raise tax have a political obligation:
if we intended to raise tax we would say so when we called the election,'' he
said.
In an exclusive interview with The Herald on the eve of his two-day visit to
Scotland, Mr Blair went on: ``There will be no tax raised at all unless the
party goes into an election promising it and succeeds. We have no plans to do
that, never mind anyone else.''
Taking stock - with evident confidence - of Labour's home rule plans, Mr Blair
offered the prospect of New Labour delivering a New Union with the rest of the
United Kingdom. ``A New Union is what Scotland and what Britain needs for a new
century.''
Mr Blair returned repeatedly to the ``tartan tax'' charge that the ``Tory lie
machine'' was attempting to pin on Labour. He claimed the whole Tory Government
had abandoned policy in favour of propaganda, and said Labour would ``come out
of its corner fighting'' against it.
``What we do from now is we counter the lies, we speak the truth, we make the
case, and we make it not just to the ordinary citizens of Scotland who get a
better democratic deal but we make it to business to show how they will get a
better deal,'' he said.
Of Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth he said: ``He's not a Government
Minister, he's a propagandist for the Conservative Party, and that propaganda
is designed primarily to get up and running the same machine that was in
existence before the last election. I call it the Tory lie machine.''
Clearly the biggest ``lie'' that Mr Blair feels he must confront is Mr
Forsyth's claim a Scottish assembly today would mean a 3p in the pound rise in
income tax for every Scot tomorrow. ``The Tory lie that should be nailed is
this idea that the Scottish parliament means that your tax goes up. The
Scottish parliament means nothing of the sort. Taxes only go up if the people
vote for them,'' he said.
However, the Tories were last night sticking to their tartan tax claim. Mr
Major was reported as saying Scottish firms would be hit by higher wage demands
as a result of such a tax.
Mr Blair also accused the Scottish Secretary of abandoning support for the
constitutional status quo. ``He has been forced to admit that the status quo no
longer holds. I think that was a strategic move of enormous importance because
from that moment on the issue is no longer whether there's change but what type
of change.''
There is no doubt Mr Forsyth's tartan tax campaign has stung Labour. Mr Blair's
apparent determination to resist any devolved tax change before the first
assembly elections and his stated belief that any subsequent change should be
put to the electorate first confirms that impact.
As part of his national campaign to persuade business and industry of New
Labour's electability, Mr Blair arrives in Edinburgh today to address the
Edinburgh Chamber of Commerce. Tonight he will speak before a business audience
at a gala dinner in Glasgow.
Even before his arrival, the SNP had joined in the attack. Its chief executive,
Mr Michael Russell, claimed that by limiting the powers of the Scottish
parliament Labour would turn it into a ``pushover''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Defiant council vows to keep up cheese checks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995603</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE local authority that lost its legal bid to destroy #27,000 worth of Lanark
Blue cheese was yesterday unrepentant, despite coming in for serious criticism
from the presiding sheriff.
Clydesdale District Council said Government guidelines had been followed to
protect consumers and it was regrettable that the court had not decided in its
favour.
The director of environmental health, Mr Duncan McDougall, said his staff would
continue to monitor cheese produced by Mr Humphrey Errington, of Dunsyre,
reputedly a favourite with the royal family.
Mr McDougall added: ``We will do this as a matter of routine as we would with
any other food manufacturer in our area.''
When asked about the costs now facing the council, estimated at up to #350,000,
he said: ``The councillors have all been given a copy of the sheriff's judgment
and will discuss it at the next full meeting (December 20).''
He would not comment further about Sheriff John Douglas Allan's criticism of
the department's handling of the case and his description of it as ``dogmatic,
confrontational, and combative''.
Earlier this week, the sheriff refused to grant Clydesdale an order to destroy
several tonnes of the deep-frozen cheese and declared the cheese was fit to eat.
The council claimed tests revealed the cheese was riddled with the food bug
listeria monocytogenes.
Clydesdale's food officers may find their hands are tied in future if they
discover other food products with the same listeria because of legal precedent
set by the Lanark Blue judgment.
Mr Errington said he was taking legal advice about suing the council for his
#120,000 costs in the Lanark Sheriff Court case.
He is also considering making a complaint to the Local Government Ombudsman
alleging maladministration by the council.
q The BBC could face legal action after breaking a sheriff's embargo forbidding
publication of his written judgment in the Lanark Blue cheese case.
BBC Scotland's Reporting Scotland programme on Wednesday evening carried
details of Sheriff Allan's ruling, despite a covering letter written by him
banning its use before midnight that night.
A spokesman for the BBC remained defiant about reporting the judgment.
He said the judgment was dated December 5 and therefore became a public
document at that time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SIDS theory discounted</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995604</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABORATORY tests have invalidated the theory that cot deaths are caused by
toxic gases from plastic or fireproof mattress covers.
Scientists from the Public Health Laboratory Service in Bristol examined
mattresses involved in 23 sudden infant deaths and found only one trace of the
fungus suspected of producing the gases.
Their published report suggests the chemist who came up with the theory may
have mistaken bacteria commonly found in the environment for the fungus.
The chemist's theory and a television report last year fanned public fear about
the mattresses and worried parents worldwide, an editorial in the scientific
journal Lancet said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Schools inspectors cross swords for dance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995605</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By BARCLAY McBAIN
Education Correspondent
ALL secondary school pupils should take part in more than one of the many forms
of dance, a report on physical education teaching and learning recommends. The
report from the Scottish Office schools inspectorate - endorsed by Scottish
Office Education Minister Raymond Robertson - says all pupils should have a
grounding in Scottish dancing.
It advises that teachers should make opportunities available for curricular and
extra-curricular sporting and dance activities to all secondary pupils.
It also urges teachers to recognise the potential of school sport for nurturing
competition and co-operation.
Pupils can now take Standard Grade and Higher courses in PE and Mr Robertson
said sports helped schools identify their ethos, the characteristics which made
them effective.
``Physical education has a vital contribution to make to improving the nation's
health, of which school sport plays an important part . . ,'' he added.
</TEXT>
