<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UNITED THEY STAND Herald poll puts Scots businesses to the test on devolution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Iain Wilson, Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995606</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
CBI Scotland is to take a public stance on whether a Scottish Parliament will
be good or bad - following pressure from prominent members to
drop its neutral course on devolution.
Its views will be formally expressed once all political parties are questioned
on constitutional change, and after widespread consultation of the membership.
No timescale was given, but chairman Andrew Cubie insisted last night: ``If,
after the process is completed, we are satisfied the implications are
detrimental to business, we will say so.'' However, he confirmed any action
will fall short of an outright political campaign.
Mr Cubie, who stressed CBI Scotland was apolitical, was adamant that harmony
within the organisation was now ``absolute''.
The decision to evaluate the effects of a Scottish parliament on business,
competitiveness, and inward investment came within hours of yesterday's Herald
report that many top businessmen are furious at CBI Scotland's ``weak and
timid'' stance on devolution.
Several threatened to withdraw from the organisation unless arguments against
a
tax raising assembly, in particular, were taken on board by the organisation.
Mr Cubie emerged from the Scottish Council's monthly meeting to declare:
``There is no split.'' Director Iain McMillan added: ``We have been in touch
with leading members and they are at ease with the way we are progressing.''
Today, an exclusive Herald poll reveals that not one of the 25 top performing
companies in Scotland has declared they will move elsewhere.
The poll strips their anonymity over attitudes to a Scottish parliament. It
has
been claimed that up to 15 leading companies would ``quit Scotland'' if the
promised Labour-Liberal Democrat parliament with tax raising powers came to
pass.
But these firms have never been named - and the Scottish Chambers of Commerce
has dismissed talk of companies pulling out if devolution was introduced as
``pure humbug.''
However, CBI Scotland is now acting over an alleged clamour among prominent
members to drop its ``bland, neutral'' line.
In a statement, it said political parties would be questioned on their
proposals for ``the governance of Scotland;'' effects of change will be
evaluated, and members' consulted.
``All these contributions will be benchmarked against the clearly-defined CBI
objectives and, at the appropriate time, a CBI statement will be contributed
to
the debate.''
Labour and the Liberal-Democrats, architects of an assembly with tax raising
powers, believe the warnings of revolt were stage managed by members who also
support the Tory Party and the Union.
However, the so-called rebels will also be happy because the CBI must now take
a firm line on devolution. They include members of the Tory Party, whose
leadership is urging businessmen to protect the Union.
Mr Bill Hughes, chairman of Grampian Holdings, yesterday confirmed his board
will consider withdrawing from the CBI unless business interests are
represented. He was confident the organisation will not now ``chicken out''
over devolution.
Lord Goold, chairman of building group McTaggart and Mickel, earlier confirmed
his board will withdraw CBI subscriptions unless its neutral stance was
abandoned.
The Herald's straw poll, which insisted a veil of secrecy be lifted, produced
many a bullish response - but not one public declaration that Scotland would
be
abandoned for pastures new.
Scottish and Newcastle and the Weir Group were the most antagonistic of all
towards a tax-raising Assembly.
Lord Weir, chairman of the Weir Group, said the proposals for a Scottish
parliament were poorly thought out and a recipe for rancour and dissension.
</TEXT>
