<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Another senior doctor resigns</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN MacDERMID Medical Corresponden</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995607</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
t
A SENIOR doctor, the second this week, has announced his resignation from a NHS
management post in protest at policies which he claims are starving the
hospital service of funds.
Mr Christopher Adams, a consultant neurosurgeon at the Radcliffe Infirmary in
Oxford, describes in the British Medical Journal how he quit as head of his
department when his unit was forced to drop clinical standards to meet the
demands being made on it.
They found themselves having to perform ``day case'' brain surgery, carrying
out craniotomies before returning patients in waiting ambulances to their
referring hospitals because there were not enough beds at the Radcliffe.
His comments follow the resignation on Wednesday of Professor Richard Olver as
vice-chairman of Tayside Health Board in protest at the management style of the
board and the draining of resources from the hospital service.
Yesterday, Professor Olver, 54, said: ``The gap between rhetoric and reality
has become too much for me.
``(Health) spending in the UK is less as a proportion of GDP than almost any
other developed country.''
Meanwhile, the second doctor to resign, Mr Adams, said his unit had been
penalised for being one of the most efficient in the NHS, increasing the number
of neurosurgical procedures from 600 in 1972 to 2500 last year.
It was the cheapest in the country - with an average cost of #1994 per case
compared with #3124 for England as a whole - with no waiting list.
However, the facilities available put them well below the generally recognised
minimum levels for safe neurosurgery. They were, as he put it, hyperefficient.
However, instead of being given more resources, they were asked to make annual
efficiency savings of 3% demanded by the Department of Health.
This was used to reduce the price to purchasers, which resulted in more
patients being referred. Income from private patients, which the surgeons had
hoped would be spent on expansion of their department to meet the growing
demands, was used instead to meet the 3% savings.
``We have had to introduce waiting lists, morale has slumped, and the service
deteriorated. If we had gone on like this, we would have ended up as an
emergency-only service,'' he said. Eventually the consultants had to relieve
the pressure the only way they could, by stopping private work.
</TEXT>
