<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dounreay faces prosecution for workers' contamination</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Corresponde</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995608</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GOVERNMENT regulatory body is preparing a report for the procurator-fiscal in
Wick that could lead to Dounreay being prosecuted following the radiation
contamination last summer of five workers employed by a private contractor to
help clear up the plant's controversial low-level nuclear waste pits.
Last week HM Nuclear Installations Inspectorate reported to the Dounreay local
liaison committee that it was investigating the case of two men who had
received radiation doses of up to 10 times those normally expected for Dounreay
workers. It said it was taking matters further and conceded that prosecution
was possible.
Shortly afterwards the number of men involved was revised upwards to four, and
it emerged yesterday that there was a fifth man. But a Dounreay spokesman said
yesterday that while a fifth man had been surveyed, the dose he received was
well below the level of concern.
A spokesman for the NII, however, told The Herald last night: ``I have been
informed by our site inspector at Dounreay that there is a fifth man and we
will be citing him in the report we are currently preparing for the fiscal,
because although the dosage is very low, our concerns have been over the
management of the project rather than the dose levels.''
The procurator-fiscal in Wick, Mr Alasdair MacDonald, said yesterday that the
NII had alerted him to its investigations.
The five men concerned all worked for Thurso-based Probabilistic Risk
Assessment, one of the first companies hired under compulsory competitive
tendering to work with nuclear waste at the plant.
They were employed to help with the remedial work going on at the plant's
low-level waste pits, recovering old drums that had been left to rust and
compacting them for disposal within new drums.
Dounreay this week issued a statement to its workforce confirming that four men
had ingested radioactive dust: ``Of the four employees of Probabilistic Risk
Assessment, one had an intake resulting in a whole-body radiation dose of about
10mSv. The remaining three had significantly lower intakes and radiation doses.
``To put this into context, the legal maximum annual whole-body radiation dose
is 50mSv. The self-imposed UKAEA limit is 20mSv; and the range of dose to
Dounreay radiation workers in recent years has been 1-10mSv.
``Dounreay's own investigation into the incidents is nearing completion. It
will be trying to answer three main questions:
Was the radiation dose to the men, during the course of their work, being
properly measured and speedily assessed and acted upon?
Were those responsible for maintaining a safe working environment adequately
monitoring the job? Was the equipment provided for such things as ventilation,
handling and protective clothing adequate for the job?''
The Caithness plant is also drawing up plans for the removal of 4500 tonnes of
topsoil from around the top of the waste shaft, which suffered an explosion in
1977 and has often been suggested as a possible source of the spots of
radioactive contamination found around the plant in the past 18 months.
Meanwhile management has also written to Greenpeace taking issue with a news
release stating that if Dounreay wins a contract to reprocess foreign research
reactor fuel, waste would stay at Dounreay while vitrified waste from
Sellafield was sent back to America.
The Atomic Energy Authority spokesman at Dounreay, Mr Ian Shepherd, wrote
saying they had misunderstood the position. Substitution could only take place,
he told Greenpeace, if a national nuclear waste repository had been established.
</TEXT>
