<DOCNO>GH951208-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Judge in drug case overruled Pusher is jailed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995609</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A YOUTH who sold ecstasy and was allowed his freedom by one of Scotland's
leading judges began a four-year sentence yesterday after a successful Crown
appeal.
Three judges in the Court of Criminal Appeal ruled Lord McCluskey had been
wrong to defer sentence for two years on 19-year-old Paul Lee.
Lee had been caught after selling ecstasy outside an Ayrshire disco.
About a month before Lee's arrest, someone had died at the disco after taking
ecstasy.
Lord Hope, the Lord Justice General, stressed that the court had a duty to the
public to impose a custodial sentence in a case such as this.
Dealing with the deferred sentence, Lord Hope said: ``It is contrary to the
sentencing policy which this court has felt itself obliged to follow in the
public interest to deter and punish those who engage in the supply to others of
class A drugs, especially to young people frequenting a disco.
``This is the only way the court can fulfil its responsibility to the public in
these cases.
``It must be brought home to those who engage in this activity for their own
gain, or who may be tempted to do so, that it is an activity which may bring
about a risk of serious damage and even death to those who consume those drugs.
``It follows that the court has to deal severely with these cases and normally
a custodial sentence will be inevitable.''
Lee, of Greenhill Crescent, Paisley, appeared at the High Court in Kilmarnock
in September this year and admitted being concerned in the supply of ecstasy on
January 22.
The court was told police went to the Metro disco in Saltcoats after an
anonymous tip-off and caught Lee after he ran away. He had #590 in cash and 19
ecstasy tablets on him. He admitted he had been selling the tablets at #10
each. Lord McCluskey decided to defer sentence on Lee, a first offender, for
two years. Mr Paul McBride, for the Crown, yesterday argued that it was
inappropriate to defer sentence in a case like this.
Mr McBride said that in his report to the appeal court Lord McCluskey had
stated that deterrent sentences had no significant effect on crime levels and
that rehabilitation was not realistic in the Scottish penal system.
The judge said he was aware that Young Offenders' Insitutions had a very high
rate of re-offending.
Mr McBride submitted that Lord McCluskey had produced a series of observations
about custodial sentences and appeared to be suggesting that such sentences
should never be imposed.
Lord Hope promised a considered response in due course to the comments Lord
McCluskey had made in his report to the appeal court.
The appeal court had made it clear that severe sentences would normally be
imposed unless there were strong mitigating features.
Mr Martin Jones, defence counsel, argued that Lord McCluskey had not ruled out
the possibility of a custodial sentence, but postponed that question by
deferring sentence on a young first offender who had a job and appreciated how
foolish he had been.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
