<DOCNO>GH951208-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>News prolongs active life</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995610</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE secret of retaining mental agility in old age is daily mental exercise,
such as listening to news bulletins, doing puzzles, and filling in forms, a
medical expert said yesterday.
Dr David Weeks of the Royal Edinburgh Hospital, a clinical neuro psychologist,
writes in the magazine She that another factor is having friends of all ages.
He has studied the habits of 3500 men and women who looked between 12 to 14
years younger than their age.
People of advancing years, while feeling younger, admitted to testing
themselves intellectually, and retaining a sense of fun and curiosity.
In contrast, he said, those who believed that growing old meant losing mental
agility were more likely to see their prophesy come true.
Dr Weeks also observed that many people living longer and looking younger were
spurred into changing their lifestyle after losing someone close.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prison inquiry after escape</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995611</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE governor of Barlinnie prison in Glasgow has ordered an inquiry into how two
prisoners were able to escape while returning from a supervised visit to a
local swimming pool.
The two men, who are not considered to be dangerous to members of the public,
managed to slip away from guards yards from the prison gates.
Steven Naylor, 23, and a second man who cannot be named for legal reasons, were
both low risk, D-category prisoners who carried out domestic duties at the
maximum security jail.
They were in a group of about six other prisoners allowed the use of the
swimming pool at nearby Smithycroft Secondary School.
After finishing a supervised closed session at the pool on Wednesday night, the
two men ran off.
A spokesman for the Scottish Prison Service said the guards followed
instructions not to chase escapers and radioed for help.
``The prison governor has ordered an investigation into the circumstances of
the escape,'' said the spokesman.
Naylor, from Airdrie, was given a three-and-a-half year sentence at the town's
Sheriff Court in November last year.
The other man was a convicted prisoner facing outstanding charges. Strathclyde
Police have been informed and are investigating.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Guppy allowed out on bail</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995612</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DARIUS Guppy, disgraced friend of Earl Spencer, was freed on bail yesterday
after being given leave to appeal against a jail term for refusing to pay
compensation for a bogus gems robbery.
Mr Justice May, at the High Court, allowed bail on condition of a #200,000
surety and that he stay at his home address.
Mr Spenser Hilliard, Guppy's counsel, said after the hearing that Guppy had
finished his five-year sentence for staging the bogus robbery but was now
appealing against a three-year sentence for failing to comply with a
compensation order.
In April, Guppy lost his appeal against the five-year sentence but fines of
#539,000 were cut to #227,000 and converted into a compensation order in
favour
of Lloyd's insurers who were defrauded when they paid up #1.8m for the bogus
gems robbery.
Guppy was told to pay the money within three months or serve the extra three
years.
Guppy, 30, of Notting Hill, was sentenced at Snaresbrook Crown Court in March
1993 for conspiracies to defraud, steal, and commit false accounting and VAT
offences.
In 1990, the Old Etonian who was best man to Earl Spencer at his wedding,
conned insurers for compensation after faking an armed robbery of a #1.8m
jewellery collection in a New York hotel room. His business associate,
Benedict
Marsh, was jailed for five years and similarly fined.
They paid Peter Risdon, an acquaintance, #10,000 to stage a bogus raid,
stealing gems from their hotel safe and leaving them tied up on their beds.
Last April, the judge said he believed Guppy still had access to ``ill-gotten
gains''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Funding crisis for harbours</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995613</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLANS to improve piers and harbours in the Highlands and Islands have been
threatened by the Scottish Office, a Highland councillor claimed.
In a letter from the Scottish Office, the council has been told that harbour
grants under the Fisheries Act 1955 have been stopped, and unless applications
were in before November 28, no further money would be granted under this
scheme.
According to North-West Sutherland councillor Francis Keith, this will have
serious effects on projects throughout the North.
``In Kinlochbervie, we were planning to deepen the entrance to the harbour at a
total cost of #750,000,'' he said.
``The withdrawal of the grant means we cannot go ahead. That means we cannot
induce foreign fishing vessels to land at Kinlochbervie, and that is serious.''
The effects could be wider. There are fears that ERDF funding for piers could
also be affected.
``This could also affect some transport piers,'' said Councillor Keith. ``It
will be of concern to all the harbour trusts around the coast.''
The position is equally serious in the Western Isles. According to Mr Duncan
MacInnes, secretary of the Western Isles Fishermen's Association, a study that
has been under way on fishery piers will now be useless and deterioration of
facilities is inevitable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No arms surrender, says IRA</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995614</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE IRA said last night it would not surrender its weapons.
The announcement came hours after it was confirmed the international
commission, set up to examine ways of decommissioning terrorist weapons, was to
have its first meeting in New York at the weekend, with sessions in Belfast and
Dublin next week.
In a statement released in Dublin, the IRA said there was ``no question'' of it
meeting ``the ludicrous demand for a surrender of IRA weapons either through
the front door or the back door''.
It added: ``British bad faith and Unionist intransigence has raised a huge
question mark over the potential of the twin-track approach.''
The ``twin track'' policy of a commission to look at arms and exploratory talks
between the British and Irish governments with the local political parties was
agreed by Mr Major and Irish Premier John Bruton on the eve of the visit by
President Bill Clinton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000158</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000158</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>City plans for GPs' medical night centres New network designed to cope with increasing out-of-hours workload</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995615</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NETWORK of overnight medical centres where patients can be seen by GPs is
expected to be up and running in Greater Glasgow early in the New Year.
It will be the first development in the UK on such a scale - covering more than
900,000 patients - since the Government put up #45m to meet the cost as part of
the out-of-hours settlement with GPs earlier this year.
There are expected to be six or seven centres spread around the city, each
manned by two doctors and support staff.
However Dr Kenneth Harden, chairman of the Glasgow Local Medical Committee,
said yesterday that patients for whom it was clinically necessary would still
be able to get a home visit.
These would be provided by the existing deputising services used by many
practices, or by GPs who had opted to continue doing their own night calls. The
LMC is also negotiating with the Scottish Ambulance Service to provide
transport for patients who would have difficulty reaching one of the centres.
This would use the Patient Transport Service ambulances which provide
non-emergency transport during the day, and lie unused at night.
Dr Harden said the out-of-hours workload had doubled over the past four years,
and GPs had been finding it increasingly difficult to provide a high-quality
service.
It was not intended as a substitute for hospital accident departments, which
had X-ray and other facilities for dealing with trauma.
``It will clearly not be a drop-in centre. The telephone number will be
publicised and people will be expected to phone in first. We hope it will not
be abused - if people come in with non-urgent things then urgent cases may not
get the care they need when they need it,'' he said.
The centres will not be new-build but will be located in existing premises -
Stobhill Hospital and Victoria Infirmary have expressed an interest in
accommodating them and it is intended to locate one in Drumchapel.
Scotland's share of the #45m is #4.9m, of which Greater Glasgow gets #877,000.
The service has to be in place by April next year to benefit from the money and
a similar sum will be available the following year.
``We hope it will be ongoing,'' said Dr Harden.
The money will be used to staff the centres and pay for the patient transfer
service and communications support - including a fax link so that GPs will know
the following morning what had been happening to their patients through the
night.
However, the salary of the doctors themselves will be met by GPs subscribing to
the overnight centres, since they are still responsible for their patients.
Dr Barbara West, the LMC secretary, said research had shown that one centre for
50,000 patients - the ratio previously favoured - was not a very efficient use
of resources, and that one per 150,000 would be the most efficient.
``There is a real recruitment crisis in general practice and one of the reasons
cited by young doctors is the need to be on call at night and do their job
during the day.
``Having looked at the workload we think that each could be safely and
effectively staffed by two doctors and a nurse, with trained telephone
operators and a security presence. Research has shown that in an area of
150,000 people, night calls before midnight average 10 every hour, and after
midnight 2.5 per hour,'' she said.
Mr Danny Crawford, chief officer of Glasgow Local Health Council, said: ``We
would want to be assured that this does not mean a reduction in cover for the
public out-of-hours. When this was first mooted it was in the context of
possible acute hospital closures. I hope that is off the agenda.'
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000159</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000159</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murder trial sees street video</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995616</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN accused of drugging and murdering a secretary was seen with her on a
street videotape hours earlier, a court heard yesterday.
Constable William Wilson, 46, said Mr Richard Karling, 43, was filmed meeting
33-year-old Miss Dorothy Niven.
The tape, screened at the High Court in Glasgow, allegedly showed Miss Niven
being helped from the Pancake Place restaurant, in Union Street, by a woman an
hour later. Next day, she was found dead in bed.
Mr Karling, of Bellview Crescent, Ayr, denies that on June 27 last, in the
Pancake Place, he administered Temazepam to Miss Niven, and took her in a taxi
to her home in Busby, where he forced her face into a pillow and murdered her.
He has lodged special defences of incrimination and alibi.
Miss Lyn Harley, 31, of Cochrane Street, Bellshill, said she worked beside Miss
Niven at the Students' Loan Company. She said Miss Niven told her she had taken
out an interdict against Mr Karling, to prevent him from following and phoning
her after they split up.
Paramedics told Mr William Totten, prosecuting, they were called to the house
at Busby on the afternoon of June 28 and were met by Mr Karling.
Mr Douglas Shepherd, 36, said the woman was face-down on the bed and had been
dead for some time. He said: ``Her neck was bent back at an unnatural angle.''
Mr Alexander Lochrie, 37, said Mr Karling told him he had been Miss Niven's
boyfriend for seven years and that she was a diabetic.
He said Mr Karling told him the woman had become ill at a restaurant the
previous day.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951208-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951208-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How the top 25 firms replied to major question</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Iain Wilson, Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995617</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S top performing company, Standard Life, depicted at the last election
as active campaigners against devolution, is adamant its position was much
mis-reported. But clearly concerns still exist. These are the responses from
the leading 25 firms, in running order, on being asked their views on the
formation of a Scottish parliament:
Standard Life: In recent months has spoken to all political parties and told
them again of the sensitivities of the financial services sector in particular
to constitutional change.
``We think there is now a greater understanding of our continuing concerns on
the impact of devolution - especially in terms of the likely ensuing
uncertainty - on our business,'' said Mr Scott Bell, group managing director.
2. Royal Bank of Scotland: No comment.
3. Scottish Widows: ``Our stance is clear. Our over-riding priority is to
protect the interests of policyholders.
``Any assessment of the impact of constitutional change is bound to be
hypothetical at the present time. However, if it were to come about, with a
consequent impact on policyholders' investments, we would respond to the
situation accordingly.
``In terms of future growth, we recognise our main market will continue to be
England for a long time. We believe our contribution to the economy of Scotland
is important, and trust constitutional change would not result in that
situation being jeopardised.
``In the meantime, we must recognise that uncertainty in our long term business
is undesirable both for existing clients and prospective ones.''
4. General Accident: Awaiting details of the form a Scottish Parliament will
take, the firm pointed out it operates under a range of political systems and
Governments in over 40 countries.
``However, the company recognises shareholders' interests are paramount and
therefore if any future Scottish constitution meant that General Accident was
disadvantaged against its competitors based in England, the board would need to
review the position.''
5. ScottishPower: ``We will clearly work with any system set up by a democratic
elected Government. However, we would emphasise the over-riding need for any
new system to avoid harming the competitive ability of Scottish-based companies
by imposing any extra tax burden.''
6. Bank of Scotland: No comment.
7. United Distillers: No comment.
8. Scottish Amicable: ``Our interests are those of our shareholders. We are
keeping close contact with all the parties to ensure their interests are
understood,'' said head of strategic marketing Brendan Llewellyn.
``In particular it is important to us that the personal and corporate taxation
regime does not disadvantage Scottish based companies trading in   the UK.''
9. Scottish and Newcastle: See report opposite.
10. Scottish Equitable: ``If anything happened that jeopardised our existing or
new customers, we would take whatever action necessary to protect our
position,'' said marketing director Graeme Dumble. ``Our success in the last 10
years is based on taking a pragmatic business view. We must satisfy customer
requirements, and if any moves in terms of the Scottish situation called that
into question then we would take action . . .
``It would cause concern if some of our English-based competitors saw
advantages by knocking us for not being English-based.
``Such a perception from our customer base would be a big issue for us. It
would not do to be put at a disadvantage in an already competitive market. We
have a responsibility to staff, customers, and shareholders to protect their
position.''
11. Scottish Provident: ``We see real value in having some Scottish affairs
debated and decided by Scots who, as I understand it, would be represented by
some form of proportional representation.
``However, there is one area where we have reservations,'' said group managing
director David Woods. ``It would be of concern if the parliament has powers to
raise tax, or to alter rates of tax between Scotland and the rest of the UK.
``This could be used by our competitors to damage our business. Most of our
competitors are based outside Scotland, as are the majority of our customers -
some 85%-90%.
``Whether real or not, these competitors could say to people: `Why put your
money with a Scottish company over a period of 20-25 years when the tax raising
powers could be different in five years' time?'.
``But I think Scottish life companies have an established record in particular
in producing good returns to all their policyholders in England as well as
Scotland.
``It is up to the industry in Scotland to make proper representations to those
who are elected. No-one would want to take actions that would precipitate the
demise of a strong Scottish industry, and one of the biggest employers.''
12. Scottish Hydro-Electric: ``This is essentially a matter for the Scottish
people, but from a business point of view Hydro-Electric would certainly not
want to be disadvantaged from having its headquarters in Scotland.''
13. Seagram Distillers: No comment.
14. Scottish Life: Following talks with Labour's economics spokesman Alistair
Darling, the company is ``much more relaxed about the devolution proposals than
four years ago, when many questions remained unanswered.''
Mr Jim Gilchrist, director and general manager, sales and marketing, added:
``Our conversations suggest there will be no corporate tax implications.
Provided there is no effect on our business, there is no reason to take a
negative attitude.''
15. Clydesdale Bank: Devolution will be good, if there is a clear financial
advantage to Scotland and puts more money into the pockets of Scots, according
to a spokesman. But that argument had not been made as yet.
16. Christian Salvesen: No comment.
17. John Menzies: No comment.
18. Compaq: No comment.
19. Scottish Nuclear: ``We have been watching the situation with interest . . .
we share some of the concerns which have been raised, but need to fully
understand the implications of change for our business before arising at any
decision.''
20. Weir Group: ``The proposals are poorly thought out; will produce very
difficult political consequences, and are objectionable on many grounds,''
declared Lord Weir, chairman.
Politically, they neither addressed the question of why Scottish MPs should
have a say in English domestic legislation while English MPs have none in
Scottish legislation.
Nor did they address why - with a significant transfer of political power to
Edinburgh - disproportionate Scottish representation in Westminster can
continue to be justified.
``In this situation, it is hard to see why English MPs will continue to agree
to the favourable financial treatment Scotland currently enjoys.
``All this will be a recipe for rancour and dissension, particularly if
different parties are in power in Edinburgh and Westminster, and may be the
start of the `slippery slope' towards independence and to minor country status.
``In financial terms, the Tartan Tax will not go up or down as Mr Blair
pretends. It will go up. We will be expensively overgoverned as a consequence,
and overgoverned by people who still hold to the tradition that extra
expenditure is the answer to all public ills.
``Scotland will be a less attractive place both for companies with
international businesses and for investors from abroad.''
21. Allied Distillers: ``We support bringing decision making closer to the
people. We also hope a Scottish parliament would bring a greater understanding
of our industry's needs in terms of competition worldwide. The downside would
be an additional tax on the people. We would want it to benefit Scotland,
rather than fund a new legislature,'' said trades relations director John
Campbell.
22. TSB: ``It is not our policy to take positions on specific political issues.
If legislation was proposed we would consider the Bill very carefully. The
impact on taxation would be the important element.''
23. Scottish Mutual Assurance: ``We have safeguarded 1000 jobs, created 300
more, and are extremely happy where we are,'' said director of strategy Ian
Gilmore.
``As a result of speaking to politicians, we are quite confident we have
nothing to fear. We understand there is no intention of pursuing corporate tax
raising powers.''
24. Cummins Engine Company: ``A key role for the proposed Scottish parliament
should be to further develop the large investment in Scottish industry from
leading multinational companies, helping to create an attractive and successful
business environment.''
25. Low and Bonar: No comment.
</TEXT>
