<HEADLINE>ScotRail stumped by extra leg</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974995618</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAIL staff at Inverness Station were put on alert after a glass eye and a
wooden leg were discovered among a misplaced belongings.
Customer service supervisor, David Parker, said: ``The eye was found in the
London-Inverness train and was claimed later. But the wooden leg, which was
actually left propped up against the station concourse seats, has never been
claimed. Surely someone has missed it?''
Fire death
A MAN who died following a fire in his house yesterday was named by police as
John Pirrie, 62, of Laighmuir Street, Uddingston.
Festive fare
SUPERSTORE Asda is set for a first 24-hour opening at Brunstane, in Edinburgh,
in the run-up to Christmas.
Man held
A MAN was remanded for a week at Falkirk yesterday accused of demanding that
police provide him with #30,000, a helicopter, two rifles, and a phone. Mr
Derek Thomson, 28, of Kinneil Road, Bo'ness, was also accused of threatening to
shoot police officers and two women on Wednesday.
Safe theft
A THIEF proved he had brawn not brains when he carried off a safe which
contained worthless papers. Police were yesterday hunting the man who netted
just #1 in a raid on chartered accountants Macfarlane Gray, Viewfield Place,
Stirling. A police spokesman said a man was later spotted pushing a heavy
object in a wheelbarrow.
</TEXT>
