<HEADLINE>Manifesto for higher taxation?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Iain Wilson, Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995619</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE CHAIRMAN of Scotland's biggest manufacturing company has warned a Scottish
parliament with tax raising powers will damage individual businesses and, above
all, inward investment.
Sir Alick Rankin, of S &amp; N, fears an opportunity to make Scotland wealthier,
more successful - and a more attractive place in which to work and live - will
be missed because of the threats to personal taxation.
Sir Alick also suspects the policies of a Labour-inspired solution to
devolution will result in a manifesto not only leading to higher taxes but
increased public expenditure, higher interest rates, and inflation.
He also spoke of the brewing and leisure group's concerns over the firm's
ability to continue a recruitment strategy which for many years has brought
high quality, skilled executives to the head office and subsidiary companies in
Scotland.
But he stressed the company, which employs 51,000, is intensely proud of being
Scottish and would never be a party to irresponsible threats to move operations
outwith Scotland, should home rule materialise.
``That is not our way. The voters will decide these matters,'' he said. ``But
we will argue for what is in the interests of business and enterprise in
Scotland.'' In response to our poll question on company attitudes to the
formation of a Scottish parliament, Sir Alick said:
``Like many other businesses, our general viewpoint is related to concerns
surrounding personal taxation threats which we believe to be damaging to
businesses and above all to inward investment.
``In that context, it seems to me that if there is to be a Scottish parliament
or devolution, it is an opportunity to make Scotland wealthier, more successful
- rather than an opportunity to make it as less attractive place in which to
live and work.
``If policies of a Labour-inspired solution to devolution result in a manifesto
which threatens higher taxation, an opportunity will have been lost to make
Scottish more prosperous.
``S &amp; N has for years been recruiting high quality, skilled executives into
Scotland to manage the policy strategy, functions and services.
``These people, recruited from England and Western Europe, will be unlikely to
come and relocate in Scotland under circumstances threatened by the
devolutionary situation. It is just not sensible to believe they would live and
work here.
``This company would be unlikely to find the same high calibre and quality of
external advisers locally, and would have to look for these advisers and
services from south of the Border, probably London. I am talking about advisers
and skills - corporate finance, legal, marketing, advertising, consultancy,
press relations, corporate affairs.
``I believe inward investment would be seriously disadvantaged after past
decades of successfully persuading foreign companies into Scotland. I believe
that Scotland would be a second line opportunity under these circumstances.
They would go to the North-east of England, Ireland, and other countries, in
particular if they wish to have a European Community base.
``Scotland, under better taxation circumstances, would be an obvious
opportunity for them. I think this would be damaged.''
Sir Alick went on: ``We in industry have clear memories of the very high burden
of local authority tax which it paid through the business rate in past years.
``I believe the politicians in a Scottish parliament would often be the same
people who were councillors in these local authorities which believed in heavy
taxation of business. I fear their memories would be short.
``All too often industrial companies paid out three times the local authority
rate as was paid in England.''
``In more general terms, I am nervous that the philosophies of wealth creation
and free enterprise will come a poor second to the inclination to increase
public expenditure; operate on higher interest rates, and under circumstances -
inevitably - of higher inflation.
``In general, industry needs more deregulation, less intervention from
parliaments, and fewer tiers of Government - not more.
``We are not in favour of the break-up of the Union and of the UK into what
would be inevitably smaller and less influential entities. These are issues
which big companies do face.''
</TEXT>
