<HEADLINE>The `unwelcome' mat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995620</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OPPONENTS laid down an ``unwelcome'' mat last night for the arrival of Labour
leader Tony Blair in Scotland today, with a barrage of questions and criticisms
of his taxation and devolution plans.
Scottish Conservative chairman Sir Michael Hirst led the fray, writing to Mr
Blair with a series of questions about the ``tartan tax''; the Scottish Liberal
Democrats accused Labour of being spineless on tax cuts; and the SNP
highlighted Mr Blair's ``Tory'' views on education, taxes, and VAT on fuel.
SNP leader Alex Salmond also challenged Mr Blair over his refusal to answer a
series of letters on the issue of the sovereignty of the Scottish people and
the Claim of Right signed by Labour MPs, which contrasted with the traditional
view of Westminster sovereignty and proved that ``on the Scottish question, New
Labour can't be trusted an inch''.
Last night Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson countered criticisms of
the decision to abstain on Conservative tax cuts this week. ``Labour did not
oppose the tax cuts because we believe that after enduring Tory tax increases
amounting to over #800 since 1992, families have had enough of this burden.
``Labour did not support the tax cut because it would not have been our
priority - that would have been to reduce VAT on fuel. As for the Conservative
letter, this is a pretty desperate spoiling tactic from Sir Michael Hirst,
designed to upstage Tony Blair's visit.''
Sir Michael was joined by Scottish Industry Minister George Kynoch in asking Mr
Blair:
q How would the leader of a Scottish parliament compete with a Welsh Secretary
for inward investment if there was an income tax differential?
q How did he justify a regressive tax which would hit the lower paid harder?
q How would he resolve the ``administrative nightmare'' for companies trading
and those working on both sides of the Border?
q Having backtracked on English assemblies, would he now reconsider the
``tartan tax''?
SLD leader Jim Wallace, addressing his party executive in Perth today, will
deliver an attack on Labour's ``spineless connivance in Tory tax cuts''. He
said Monday's Scottish Grand Committee meeting in Edinburgh would be a
``charade showing more clearly than ever how little say the Scottish people
have in determining Scotland's political priorities.''
He asks: ``How can Labour be trusted to promote education in Government when
they are so spineless in its defence in opposition?'' and adds: ``By sitting on
the fence on the Government's shameless tax bribes, Labour has done itself and
the people of Scotland a disservice.``
Mr Salmond said: ``Blair comes to Scotland with a policy platform which is
virtually identical to the Tories. On social policy, economic policy,
education, and training, it's becoming increasingly hard to tell the
difference. Scotland needs an alternative to the Tories, not a substitute.''
