<HEADLINE>A74 upgrade and M6 link by millennium Forsyth seeks private #190m for work</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995621</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOUR consortia are to be asked to tender for a #190m private finance project to
upgrade the A74 to motorway by the year 2000 and complete the M6 Border link.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth said yesterday the Road Management Group, UK
Highways, Border Highways, and Autolink Concessionaires would soon be
approached to bid for the ``vital and innovative project''.
The announcement was welcomed by the AA. A spokesman said: ``It appears that
the Government will keep its promise of completing the A74 to motorway by the
year 2000. It is also sensible that they have included the missing link south
of the Border.
``We are happy to see private finance schemes. It is early days but we are
hopeful that they will work well. The sooner the decision is made the better.''
Mr Forsyth said there were two significant construction schemes in the contract
as well as the operation and maintenance of the motorway from Carlisle to
Millbank.
The construction elements are the 18-mile section in Scotland from Paddy's
Rickle Bridge to Cleuchbrae and the upgrading of 5!s miles of the A74 in
England between the Border and Carlisle (Junction 44). Work should start
towards the end of 1996.
Mr Forsyth said: ``Private finance has found a way to ensure that these vital
schemes are taken forward together in the fastest possible timetable.
``The M6/A74 is Scotland's principal export route and therefore of key
importance to all sectors of our economy. Its upgrade has been the strategic
priority of our trunk road programme for the past decade.
``I am also delighted to welcome the agreement between the Scottish Office and
the Department of Transport which will allow the upgrading of the section
immediately south of the Scottish Border to be included in the tender
competition.
``This itself is another innovation and is made possible by the use of private
finance. Each department will pay its share of the total costs.''
The contract will take the form of design, build, finance, and operate and will
be the first time a DBFO contract has been used in Scotland.
In a DBFO contract, the contractor undertakes the design and construction of
the road and to raise the finance, and takes responsibility for the operation
and maintenance of the new road for the contract period.
In return, the contractor receives periodic payments or ``shadow tolls'' from
the Government based on traffic levels.
The group members of the four consortia are:
q Road Management Group - Amec, Brown and Root, Alfred McAlpine, Dragados, and
Morrison;
q UK Highways - John Laing, Tarmac, Welsh Water, and Transroute International;
q Border Highways - BICC, Trafalgar House Corporate Developments, and Connect
Roads;
q Autolink Concessionaires - Amey Holdings, Sir Robert McAlpine Ltd, and Taylor
Woodrow Civil Engineering Ltd.
Meanwhile, Mr Forsyth has given approval for the 5.3km dual carriageway A96
Blackburn by-pass to ease congestion in the Grampian town.
Mr Forsyth said: ``The A96 remains one of the Government's highest priorities.
I expect to confirm the start date for construction at an early opportunity.''
The decision follows the public inquiry held in April, 1994.
q A public exhibition of the proposals for the M6 between Carlisle and Guards
Mill will be held at the Metal Bridge Inn, Blackford, Carlisle, on Friday,
December 15, and Saturday, December 16.
</TEXT>
