<HEADLINE>Meetings planned on football incidents</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974995622</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Crown Office and Scotland's top police officers are set to meet and discuss
when criminal law should be applied to footballers involved in on-field
incidents, it emerged yesterday.
The planned talks between Crown Office officials and representatives of the
Association of Chief Police Officers in Scotland (ACPOS) could result in the
formation of a comprehensive legal strategy towards such incidents, covering
all professional and amateur sports.
The news came a day after the Crown Office confirmed that four Rangers and
Aberdeen footballers were not to be prosecuted following police investigations
into incidents during a match between the clubs in Glasgow last month.
The talks move was revealed in a reply from the Lord Advocate, Donald Mackay,
Scotland's most senior law officer, to Labour MP Brian Wilson, who has been
pressing for guidelines to be issued to procurators fiscal.
Mr Wilson, MP for Cunninghame North and parliamentary adviser to the Scottish
Professional Footballers Association, had stressed the urgent need for
consistency of approach among procurators fiscal and criticised as
``unhelpful'' the view that any action which might be an offence if committed
in the street could also result in prosecution if it took place on the football
field.
In his reply, the recently-appointed Lord Advocate said it was likely that
discussions would take place ``in the near future'' between Crown Office
officials and representatives of ACPOS.
Mr Wilson welcomed the Lord Advocate's response as an indication that ``serious
thought'' was being given to the issue of how far criminal law should be used
in matters previously thought to be for football itself.
He said: ``We need an end to this lottery, in which a fiscal watches a game
which happens to be on television and decides to order a police investigation.''
The secretary of the Scottish PFA, Mr Tony Higgins, also welcomed the Lord
Advocate's intention to consider how the law should be applied to all sports.
He said: ``We will be very happy to be involved in his consultations but I
would urge him to move quickly.''
q.Mr Dennis Canavan MP, convener of the all-party Scottish Sports Committee in
the House of Commons, is also due to meet the Lord Advocate and Solicitor
General Paul Cullen on Tuesday, along with a delegation from the committee, to
discuss the role of procurators fiscal in sporting events.
</TEXT>
