<DATE>951208</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ex-chairman of Hibs is fined #25,000 for revenue fraud</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974995623</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Hibs chairman Kenny Waugh was fined #25,000 yesterday for a five-year
tax fraud.
He admitted the #80,000 fraud, which involved giving his employees tax-free
bonuses for five years.
The former Edinburgh bookmaker earlier had pled guilty at Edinburgh Sheriff
Court to defrauding the Inland Revenue of #80,000 between August 1987 and
August 1992.
Sheriff Iain Macphail told Waugh that such a deliberate and persistent fraud
would normally mean jail. However, there were a number of mitigating factors,
including Waugh's age and poor health and the fact that the case has been
hanging over him for three years.
The sheriff said he also took into account the fact that Waugh, 58, was a first
offender and that he had always admitted the fraud.
He allowed Waugh six months to pay the fine and afterwards Waugh, who is
retired, said: ``Naturally, I am glad it is all over. As the sheriff pointed
out, the delay of three years and two months was tremendous stress.''
Mr Gordon Jackson QC, defending, told Sheriff Macphail that Waugh had not
benefited from the fraud himself but depute-fiscal Neil Allan said the Crown
took issue with that. Mr Allan said he failed to make the tax deductions, so it
was up to him to come up with the money.
``By his deliberate and calculated fraudulent actions he avoided a personal
liability to pay #80,000,'' he added.
Mr Jackson said that it would have been different if Waugh had made the
deductions and kept the cash but he did not make deductions and never actually
had the money.
At an earlier hearing, depute-fiscal Vicky Roger told the sheriff that the
fraud was very simple.
Waugh, of Glenlockhart Bank, Edinburgh, had a system whereby most of his
betting shop employees got an untaxed bonus each week.
``Normal wages were taxed under PAYE but no deductions were made from the cash
supplements,'' said Miss Roger.
Waugh started his business in 1963 and built it up into a successful firm.
During the time of the offence, he had between 11 and 17 branches and employed
a fairly large number of people.
Waugh got into the way of giving bonuses. If a betting shop had a good week,
the manager could take a bonus himself and pay one to other staff.
When it started it was not regular but, said Mr Jackson, it went on for so long
that it started to feel like an entitlement.
Waugh had to take 18 months off because of a serious illness and, during that
time, his managers continued to pay the bonuses.
Mr Jackson produced a letter to prove that Waugh had repaid the #80,000 to the
Inland Revenue.
``He has paid #80,000 because he `bunged' his employees over this period,'' he
said.
Mr Jackson added that the Inland Revenue was likely to seek more cash to cover
interest.
``They will be back for their final pounds of flesh,'' he said.
Mr Jackson described Waugh as a ``well-kent face'' in Edinburgh and said he had
played his part in the community and organised sporting charity events.
He now found himself branded as someone who had defrauded the taxman.
``It was not a man lining his pockets,'' said Mr Jackson.
</TEXT>
