<TEXT>
NO harm putting a penny in the old man's hat, but a seasonal suggestion that
``lucky'' 5p coins should be buried inside Christmas puddings hasn't gone down
well with safety watchdogs.
The old tradition went the way of the sixpence when the ``tanner'' was phased
out years ago - and, with no shortage of foreign objects swallowed by kids,
doctors weren't sorry.
``Reviving the custom now with such a small coin could put children at risk of
choking,'' a Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents (RoSPA) spokeswoman
warned yesterday, after a supermarket chain cooked up the idea. Children's
hospitals contacted by Check-Out backed the experts' advice to play it safe.
Other tips from RoSPA for an accident-free Christmas: Don't hang balloons or
paper chains near a light fitting or cards beside a fire; never use Christmas
tree lights outdoors, check they are to British Safety Standard BS4647, with a
kitemark; keep toys well away from old folks to prevent falls, and banish
children from the kitchen!
n DOG and bone = phone, so it's perhaps not surprising that BT has linked up
with PAL to offer customers free calls in exchange for special labels.
A dog guzzling one can of PAL a day for a month (the same offer applies to cats
eating Kit e kat) will earn its owner some 2!s hours' worth of free calls, BT
is telling customers this month.
While not looking a gift in the mouth, Check-Out has ascertained that if you're
calling long distance at peak times your canine credit will run out in just 15
minutes. The 2!s hours mentioned by BT refers to their local weekend rate and
translating the fine print, the cash value is #1.50.
Meantime, after we reported that Edinburgh greengrocer Yousaf Hussein had
challenged BT's claim that a banana costs more than some of their 10-minute
bargain calls - at the time he was selling bananas at 5p a pound - BT are now
making the comparison with a carrot. Watch this space!
