<HEADLINE>Scots choc up a first</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jane Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974995786</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
When it comes to sweet nothings Scotland leads the way as JANE SCOTT discovers
when a new chocolate bar is tested and found tasteful north of the Border
GUTFILL, indulgence and snack. You are what you eat, and the chocolate
industry, ever ready with a term to describe why we will pick a Mars over a
Flake or a Kit Kat in the sweetie shop, has us labelled as clearly as the
ingredients on a wrapper.
The UK chocolate snack bar market - or countline market, as the industry knows
it - is huge, and shows no sign of slimming down. In fact we buy more chocky
bars every year, literally defying the recession by indulging ourselves on an
annual 10.6kg of chocolate each. Much of this is in countline form, by far the
most important part of the UK confectionery market.
Competition is fierce, and chocolate manufacturers are bracing themselves for
the #2m launch in January of Siesta, a new wafer bar from Terry's of Chocolate
Orange fame.
Siesta was tried out in Scotland, where we revealed our legendary sweet tooth
and bought the bar in droves, making the marketing men very excited indeed.
Scotland is, apparently, the classic area for testing out new brands; Cadbury's
Time Out was first tasted here, as was Caramel.
As well as eating more sweets than anywhere else in the country, the reach of
our commercial TV stations allows advertising to pinpoint us directly, after
which we nip out, buy the bar and eat it in Scotland; rogue Siestas do not end
up in Bath, for example.
Siesta craftily panders to the traditional British tastes. We are a great
biscuit-eating nation (hence the wafer) and we love all things covered in
chocolate (the bar wears, naturally, a chocolate overcoat).
But the killer blow is the chocolate orange cream filling in the middle; we
have a deep and lasting love affair with orangey chocolate, seen as exotic
before the war when confectionery stars like Club biscuits and the Jaffa Cake
were launched, all but unobtainable during the bleak years of rationing and
finally an indulgence to be encouraged with the rise of advertising in the
fifties.
Its ingredients slot the bar right into the snack category of the countline
market, says Terry's Suchard marketing manager Dean Sanders.
``There seem to be three major ways of eating countlines,'' he says. ``One of
these is to combat hunger and to fill you up. We call it gutfill. It's a useful
term, and those are the heavier bars like Mars or Snickers.
``Those we call the indulgent bars are the soak-in-the-bath type. It's more a
sort of emotional comment than a physical need, brands like Flake and Caramel
or the Chocolate Orange bar.
``And then the final sort, which is the biggest market in the UK, are the snack
countlines, which are the ones that really fit with modern lifestyles, a
snatched break at the office or during the day, some sense of escapism from
where you are, but not an indulgent, luxurious break.''
The classic is Kit Kat, launched in 1935 and the biggest confectionery brand
with annual sales of nearly #215m. More than 6,000,000 of the bars are
manufactured each day, and the Have a Break, Have a Kit Kat slogan, so
important to the brand's success, was first aired in 1957.
The snack and wafer market is growing at about 7% a year as people work longer
hours and mealtimes become less of an institution. This is set to grow further
before the end of the century with the numbers of five to 14-year-olds swelling
by 3% (chocolate companies rely for a huge proportion of their sales on parents
packing a snack in the lunchbox).
A bar with the right ingredients can therefore establish itself quickly among
the big players, with Cadbury's Time Out, for example (a chunk of Flake between
wafers and covered with the obligatory chocolate) only four years old and yet
ranking at No 5 in the snacklist behind Kit Kat, Twix, Penguin and Club with
annual sales of #45m.
Richard Frost of Cadbury says the launch was vital in a market where the
company had no effective stake: ``At the end of the day the world doesn't
actually need another chocolate bar, so you have to try and work out what might
be the things that would tempt people to try something different.
Keen to make the most of a growing market, the big players are extending their
existing brands. In recent years traditional chocolate bars Aero, Dairy Milk or
Galaxy have come out in snack bar size to appeal to the on-the-hoof snacker,
while Cadbury is now promoting its pocket-pack chocolate.
The fill-you-up quality of a Mars bar keeps it a best-seller (3,000,000 are
made every day) but the parent company recently reformulated the recipe,
introducing ``a slightly lighter, smoother nougat'', equating with society's
hunger for lighter snacks.
THE market is also set to change at the top end as British tastes become more
educated about chocolate, much as they did with wine. We traditionally like our
chocolate bars milky, laced with caramel and fairly low in cocoa solids, much
to the disgust of continental chocoholics, who prefer a finer, sweeter taste.
We may see posher (and more expensive) continental bars like Ritter Sport
become more commonplace.
As competition becomes fiercer, however, predicts Sanders of Terry's Suchard,
we will see lesser-known brands of snack bar withdrawn from the market as the
cost of advertising outweighs the sales.
The British public, he says, is not so keen on experimenting with new tastes as
it is in munching through the old ones repackaged; in recent years the major
chocolate manufacturers have extended classic sweets like Mars, Twix, Kit Kat,
Yorkie, et al into ice cream, mini bars, giant bars and drinks.
These ``powerbrands'' will dominate into the next century, further entrenching
our growing habit of snacking on chocolate. And quite right too, says Sanders.
``I think the manufacturers of chocolate should recognise the magic and mystery
of chocolate. It's not just a food. It is something far more important.''
