Merry gizmos to one and all as Joe Donnelly look for a
sanity clause
WE HAVE searched long and hard, as the festive times approach at lightspeed, to
find the kind of gifts that adequately reflect our scientific and technological
heritage and the amazing advances achieved in the past 12 months.
It was not easy. It seems that the wonders of science are worthless unless they
can be converted into gadgets and knick-knacks. We browsed some of the major
retailers to get a taste of what will be filling our stockings. From the looks
of some of it, the best thing to be in stockings are feet.
The Science Museum's are not all connected to a science. Some are mere curios,
and others are just gimmicks. The reader must decide into which category fall
their Spherical Dice. They're said to work just like the cubic ones which, in
our misspent youth, always acted as if they were spherical, especially when
cash wagers were involved. These are dice which really do roll, but they
apparently obey the laws of probabilities, so you'll probably still lose -
#5.99 for three.
The museum does have a handy thing for those poor souls who can't programme the
video timer and forget which button does what on a digital watch. It's a
magic-touch watch which doesn't have a fiddly little winder adjustment system.
To adjust it you press the watch face itself. Simple enough for anybody whose
had a few, comes home five hours late and needs a scapegoat for #19.95.
Or how about the ultimate gift for crossword addicts in the microchip age? This
is an electronic crossword puzzler, a hand-held device, much like the
cryptographer's version of Sega mega drive, which ensures that puzzle fans are
never without a fix. It is programmed with 30,000 clues to make up a virtual
infinity of puzzles at the touch of a button. For those without any kind of
life, this is a snip at just short of #100 at the Science Museum.
In a similar vein, and a very similar price, the museum offers a hand-held
bridge game, obviously for people who can't find three others to play with, or
form a rubber, or whatever bridgists do.
Much more interesting, and this is for real children, is a pack of paper
gliders from a Japanese designer, which come in some very unorthodox designs,
but includes a paper version of the Stealth bomber. This little kit comes in at
#16.95, complete with a 65-page flight manual. Interesting, and it gets the
kids to actually make something which works.
We also liked the Reva wave machine, which is an interesting little liquid
sculpture which recreates the rhythmic and graceful motions of a wave as it
tilts gently from side to side. So says the brochure advertising this gizmo for
#39.
Over in the Gadget Shop, they seem to have the scientific edge with a data-link
watch which can download information from a personal computer. It is not an
absolute must to have phone numbers, schedules and appointments right there on
your wrist and readable at the highly improbable depth of 300ft below the
surface, but it's a gadget and it's got a microchip and that's good enough. It
also glows in the dark, so what more could you want for #120?
For really sad people, there's a motorised lottery selector which will, for
just under a tenner (battery not supplied) choose your random numbers. Sounds
like throwing good money after the millions going straight into London cultural
institutions. The sellers have the nerve to ask buyers to let them know if they
win. As Groucho said, there is no sanity clause.
For fun with real science we have to go to the States where the Brainstorms
company will flog an Ecosphere, which is a sealed glass ball containing water,
air, and some organics like shrimps and algae.
All it needs to be self-sustaining is light. The algae convert the light to
energy, the tiny shrimps and snails feed on it, expel what the algae needs to
live on, and so on. It's a mutually dependent little world of existence, and
one which every child should experience.
Brainstorms also offer a lifelike severed hand which police in several states
want to ban, they're so fed up with being called out to suspected mutilations.
Those Yanks have actually brought out a full-body suit for dogs. As if dressing
a pooch up in a polyester romper suit is not sufficient canine embarrassment,
this thing comes in a doggie skeleton pattern. So if you lose the torso kit, at
least you know what the inside of a Rottweiller looks like. Ah, the wonders of
science.
Some of the scientific innovations look like real fun. We like the talking
camera from Polaroid, a gadget which will take an instant photie and save you
the bother of saying ``Say Cheese''.
The 636 Talking Camera has a single-chip voice playback feature which lets you
either use one of three built-in jokey messages, or record their own for
playback just before the birdie is watched. Polaroid say their garrulous
picture box will ``surreptitiously record singing in the shower and then play
it back to the `Performing Diva' while capturing a priceless photo''. The whole
kit comes complete with film for #39.99.
For the real kids, the ones jammed up against games consoles, Nintendo Game
Boy, arguably the most successful hand-held game machine on the planet, comes
in a new range to supplement the state-of-the-art classic grey. The new
machines come now in a range of colours, including a transparent version which
lets players see the internal works.
Whatever the colour, the new-tint machines play Donkey Kong Land and Mario's
Picross. They're selling from between #40 and #60.
NEC have just developed a compact pocket-sized player for full-colour motion
video and audio. In fact it's tiny and the company boast that their Silicon
View is a breakthrough technology in real-time playback from data stored on a
credit card-size memory card.
It has no moving parts and is completely solid state which allows functions
including random access. This, however, is a present for Christmas future, as
it's yet to hit the market, but it will be here soon.
For future anorak wearers who want to major in conversational Klingon, how
about a range of accessories which transforms a PC into a Star Trek control
centre? There's a sculpted ``monitor mask'' which makes the screen look like
something out of a James T Kirk nightmare. The Multimedia disk holder is in the
shape of a shuttle craft and the mouse is in the form of a phaser.
Brainworks, the suppliers, say the whole kit is available from toy stores, at
#80 for the keyboard to #17 for the phasermouse.
Older kids like us might prefer something a little less ostentatious, like the
Amstrad Infopad, selling at about #400 and described as a pocket-sized personal
communicator. It's a little hi-tech gadget which integrates computing and comms
technologies across Europe.
This personal Info centre offers all the facilities needed by the mobile
computer user in one package. A credit card-style adapter will interface to
send faxes or hook up to the Internet. It receives information broadcast by a
pager, so it can be constantly updated for the travelling suit. It is, of
course, a personal organiser to boot.
As new technology heads for miniaturisation, the ecologically minded benefit
too. Here's a hi-tech set of binoculars that easily fits into a pocket. Small,
in this case, is beautiful, yet these little spyglasses have a huge
magnification of up to nine times, and they're as neat as opera glasses. Much
handier, at #100 upwards, than the big heavy field glasses the other
birdwatchers use.
There's a host of scientific reading matter on the shelves this year. As the
Internet is on such a roll, Paul Glister's Internet Navigator, at #20, is
probably the ideal bible for the beginner, and a handy ready reckoner for the
converted. It's got more than 700 pages of web directions and connections, and
is also, easy to comprehend. A handy one which we'll keep beside the modem.
On multimedia, Maris have brought out what they claim is the ultimate desktop
planetarium. It's called Red Shift 2, sells at a penny short of #50 and to be
honest, their boast is no idle one. This little CD-Rom astronomy package is
fascinating, as well as being addictive.
It has a range of 3D animated tours of the universe in some top-class
virtual-reality simulations. We have now seen the formation of the moon,
galaxies colliding, stars exploding into novae, and we've followed comets
through space. With a soundcard, viewers can travel the universe, or skim
through 700 stunning space images to the strains of the Red Shift Suite on
synth. Those of us condemned forever to this planet can get away from it all,
for hours at an end. This is escapism at its best.
For this Christmas, we have sent our list by E-Mail, and we wait expectantly.
If there is a Santa Claus, we hope he's listening and has noted the
aforementioned. Naturally, his workshop will be at the forefront of technology
and science. We can just imagine the jolly gentleman in the red space suit, as
he passes into earth polar orbit, chuckling . . . H2O H2O H2O.
Some of the scientific innovations look like real fun
